const TOPICS = {};

// ── Topic 1: yn2012_comp "学会___" ──
TOPICS['yn2012_comp'] = {
  promptEn:'Write a narrative essay titled "Learning to ___". Complete the title. About 500 words. Do not use real names or places.',
  contextEn:'Society is a school, life is our teacher. In setbacks we learn resilience; in adversity we learn survival; in anger we learn patience; seeing others\' mistakes we learn understanding; when hurt we learn forgiveness; when others struggle we learn caring...',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'A classic "growth insight" semi-open essay. The prompt suggests six directions (resilience/survival/patience/understanding/forgiveness/caring). Key: (1) choose a real-life event rather than empty moralizing; (2) show the transformation from "not knowing" to "learning"; (3) elevate to life insight at the end.',
    pitfallsEn:['Topic too broad—"Learning to Be Human" is less effective than "Learning to Apologize"','All philosophy, no story—lacking concrete events','Missing process—jumping straight to "I learned" without showing psychological change','Slogan-like ending—hollow parallel sentences'],
    keyPointsEn:['Pick a small angle, develop with one specific event','Describe the psychological contrast before and after "learning"','Let readers see how you "learned" step by step','End with natural elevation, don\'t force profundity']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'Learning Resilience',fullTextEn:'That summer, the blazing sun hung overhead as I stood at the edge of the swimming pool, my legs trembling uncontrollably.\n\n"Jump!" the coach\'s voice came from the water, but I was rooted to the spot. The blue pool water seemed to transform into a gaping monster. One by one, my classmates leaped in, splashing happily, while my eyes began to sting with tears.\n\n"No, I can\'t do this..." I muttered, turning to flee.\n\n"Stop." Dad\'s voice came from behind—quiet but firm. He walked over, crouched down to eye level, and said: "Being scared is normal. But you should know that everyone who can swim was once afraid. Resilience isn\'t about not being scared—it\'s about moving forward even when you are."\n\nI bit my lip and faced the water again. Taking a deep breath, I counted: "One, two, three!" I pushed off and jumped.\n\nIcy water engulfed me instantly. My ears filled with gurgling sounds. I flailed desperately, swallowing mouthfuls of water, my nose burning. Fear clutched at me like a giant hand dragging me deeper. In that moment, I remembered Dad\'s words and clenched my teeth, stroking as the coach had taught me.\n\nGradually, my head broke the surface. Sunlight made me squint, and I heard Dad clapping. I was actually—swimming!\n\nThat summer, I went from fearing water to learning breaststroke. Whenever I wanted to give up, I\'d remember the moment I leaped in. I understood: resilience isn\'t armor you\'re born with—it\'s strength that grows slowly from falling down and getting back up, again and again.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Environment + psychology create tension'},{fnEn:'Dialogue shows inner struggle and father\'s guidance'},{fnEn:'Jumping in → struggling → succeeding: the key turning point'},{fnEn:'From event to life insight'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Small story, big theme',detailEn:'Uses "learning to swim" to convey the grand theme of "resilience"'},{pointEn:'Psychological arc',detailEn:'Fear → hesitation → courage → persistence → success, complete transformation'},{pointEn:'Dialogue drives plot',detailEn:'Dad\'s line about resilience is the essay\'s core, naturally introduced through dialogue'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'The blue pool water seemed to transform into a gaping monster',whyEn:'Vivid metaphor that makes fear tangible and relatable'},{textEn:'Resilience isn\'t about not being scared—it\'s about moving forward even when you are',whyEn:'A defining quote that offers a unique take on resilience'},{textEn:'Resilience isn\'t armor you\'re born with—it\'s strength that grows from falling and rising',whyEn:'Closing metaphor that echoes the opening "trembling," creating circular unity'}]},
    {titleEn:'Learning Forgiveness',fullTextEn:'"I\'m never talking to you again!" I slammed my ink-stained painting on the desk and stormed off.\n\nThat painting had taken me a whole week—a gift for my art teacher on Teachers\' Day. But during recess, my deskmate Xiao Jie accidentally knocked over the ink bottle, and black ink spread across the paper like a merciless rainstorm drowning my carefully built castle.\n\nAll afternoon, I didn\'t say a single word to him. I ignored his eraser offerings, pretended not to hear his apologies. I moved my chair to the farthest corner and built a wall in my heart.\n\nAfter school, I found a note and a drawing in my desk. The note read in crooked handwriting: "I\'m sorry, I know you\'re angry. I can\'t draw well, but I tried to redo your painting from memory. I hope you\'ll forgive me." The drawing was clumsy, colors going outside the lines, but it was unmistakably my painting—he\'d recreated it from memory.\n\nMy nose suddenly stung. I remembered how last month when I broke his ruler, he just laughed and said "no big deal." Every time I forgot my textbook, he\'d silently push his to the middle so we could share.\n\nThe next morning, I placed a chocolate on Xiao Jie\'s desk with a sticky note: "Thanks for the painting—it\'s actually better than mine."\n\nHe froze for a moment, then broke into a huge grin. That smile taught me: forgiveness isn\'t losing—it\'s giving yourself and others a chance to start fresh. My clenched fist uncurled, and the wall in my heart quietly crumbled.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Dialogue opening, straight into conflict'},{fnEn:'Narrates the cause and the cold-shoulder period'},{fnEn:'Discovering the note and drawing—emotional turning point'},{fnEn:'Reconciliation action + insight'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Conflict-to-transformation arc',detailEn:'From anger to cold war to being moved to forgiveness—a complete, believable emotional journey'},{pointEn:'Power of details',detailEn:'The crooked note, clumsy drawing, and playful sticky note—all heart-touching details'},{pointEn:'Contrast deepens theme',detailEn:'My unforgiveness vs. his previous kindness to me creates stark contrast'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Black ink spread like a merciless rainstorm drowning my carefully built castle',whyEn:'An apt metaphor that captures both the ruined painting and the damaged friendship'},{textEn:'Built a wall in my heart',whyEn:'"Building a wall" metaphors emotional distance, echoing the ending "wall crumbled"'},{textEn:'Forgiveness isn\'t losing—it\'s giving yourself and others a chance to start fresh',whyEn:'Transcends simple "pardoning" with a thoughtful, nuanced understanding'}]},
    {titleEn:'Learning Gratitude',fullTextEn:'Every morning, when I crawled out of bed stretching and yawning, the kitchen already smelled of breakfast. I never thought this was anything special—until that winter morning.\n\nI woke up unusually early, before dawn. Passing the kitchen, I saw a small figure bent over the stove. In the dim light, Grandma\'s white hair looked like a layer of thin frost. Her hands were soaking in cold water washing vegetables, red and chapped, with cracks at the joints. Yet she hummed a tuneless song while deftly slicing potatoes.\n\n"Grandma, do you get up this early every day?" I asked from the doorway.\n\nShe turned, her wrinkled face breaking into a smile: "Why are you up so early? Go back to sleep! Grandma\'s used to it—old people don\'t need much sleep."\n\nDon\'t need much sleep? I remembered a few nights ago getting up for the bathroom and seeing her light still on at eleven—she was sewing a tear in my school uniform.\n\nBreakfast appeared on the table—steaming porridge, golden fried eggs, finely cut potato strips. I\'d eaten these countless times without ever thinking about the 5 AM alarm, the freezing water, and the cracked hands behind them.\n\nAfter school that day, I used two months of saved allowance to buy a pair of cotton gloves, red ones, very warm. I said nothing when I got home—just quietly placed them by Grandma\'s pillow.\n\nThe next morning, Grandma was bustling in the kitchen wearing those red gloves, her eyes glistening. She didn\'t say anything either—just shaped my fried egg into a smiley face.\n\nFrom then on, every morning\'s breakfast fragrance became a song to my ears—a wordless song about love. I learned gratitude: not the "thank you" on your lips, but seeing those who give silently, and silently giving back.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Daily scene sets up "never thought it special"—foreshadowing a shift'},{fnEn:'Seeing Grandma\'s early-morning labor—awakening'},{fnEn:'The cost behind everyday food—focus + panorama'},{fnEn:'Repaying with action—showing, not preaching'},{fnEn:'From specific event to understanding gratitude'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Progressive deepening',detailEn:'From "not special" → "seeing reality" → "giving back" → "understanding gratitude"—each layer deeper'},{pointEn:'Actions replace sermons',detailEn:'Doesn\'t write "I should be grateful"—buys gloves, egg becomes smiley face—lets actions speak'},{pointEn:'Details carry emotion',detailEn:'Cracked hands, midnight light, red gloves, smiley egg—each detail carries feeling'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Grandma\'s white hair looked like a layer of thin frost',whyEn:'An apt simile—white hair like frost is both literal and suggestive of hard work'},{textEn:'Behind them lay a 5 AM alarm, freezing water, and cracked hands',whyEn:'Concrete images deconstruct the "taken for granted," deeply touching'},{textEn:'A wordless song about love',whyEn:'Poetic ending that transforms breakfast aromas into a song—beautiful imagery'}]},
    {titleEn:'Learning Independence',fullTextEn:'In fifth grade, Mom started traveling for work more often. That Sunday, she was leaving again. Before going, she said: "There\'s food in the fridge. Try making lunch yourself, okay?"\n\n"Sure!" I thumped my chest confidently, thinking: it\'s just cooking, I\'ve watched Mom do it so many times.\n\nBut standing in the kitchen facing a cabbage, two eggs, and a block of tofu, I was dumbfounded. Wash first or heat oil? How much oil? How much salt? All those steps I\'d "learned by watching" turned into question marks.\n\nSteeling myself, I copied Mom\'s routine—washed rice and started the rice cooker. Then I started stir-frying cabbage—poured oil into a cold pan, and the oil hit the wet leaves, splattering everywhere. Startled, I nearly dropped the spatula and almost quit.\n\nBut my stomach wouldn\'t agree. Gritting my teeth, I pulled out my phone and searched "stir-fry cabbage tutorial," following step by step. This time, I heated the pan first, dried the vegetables—and the oil behaved. Stir, add salt, a touch of soy sauce—though I fumbled, the kitchen actually started smelling delicious!\n\nFrying eggs went smoother. I even improvised by cutting tofu into the egg batter—creating my own "original dish."\n\nAt 12:30, I sat at the table with a bowl of rice, a plate of stir-fried cabbage, and a plate of tofu egg. The rice was a bit hard, the cabbage a bit salty, the tofu slightly burnt—but I thought it was the most delicious meal I\'d ever had.\n\nI sent Mom a photo. She instantly replied with a thumbs-up emoji and: "My girl\'s grown up!"\n\nThat day I understood: independence isn\'t knowing everything—it\'s daring to try and figure things out when you don\'t. That first self-made lunch still lingers on my taste buds.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Background—Mom away, cooking challenge begins'},{fnEn:'Gap between expectation and reality—"watched" ≠ "can do"'},{fnEn:'From failure to searching tutorials to success'},{fnEn:'Shows results with self-deprecating humor'},{fnEn:'Defines "independence"'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Relatable selection',detailEn:'Cooking is something every child might experience—authentic and believable'},{pointEn:'Failure-to-success arc',detailEn:'Shows the mess first, then success—makes the "learning" process real'},{pointEn:'Humor adds color',detailEn:'"Original dish," "the oil behaved"—naturally funny, not forced'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'All those steps I\'d "learned by watching" turned into question marks',whyEn:'Precisely captures the "eyes say yes, hands say no" experience—very relatable'},{textEn:'Rice a bit hard, cabbage a bit salty, tofu slightly burnt—but the most delicious meal ever',whyEn:'Imperfect results are the most genuine joy'},{textEn:'Independence isn\'t knowing everything—it\'s daring to try when you don\'t',whyEn:'An accurate and insightful definition of independence'}]},
    {titleEn:'Learning to Listen',fullTextEn:'I always thought I was a good friend—until that day when Xiao Yu, eyes red, told me: "You never listen to me."\n\nThose words hit me like a bucket of cold water. I opened my mouth to argue, but thinking back... she was right.\n\nLast week she excitedly told me her hamster learned to do backflips—I just said "oh" and went back to my homework. The other day she said she bombed a test and felt awful—I tossed out "try harder next time" and ran off to play ball. Even yesterday, she kept looking at me hesitantly, but I was chatting with someone else and didn\'t notice.\n\n"It\'s not that I don\'t want to talk to you—it\'s that every time I do, you\'re not listening." Xiao Yu\'s voice was soft, like a leaf touching ground.\n\nThat evening, I sat at my desk for a long time. I recalled Mom saying: "You have two ears and one mouth—so you can listen more and talk less." I used to dismiss it as nagging. Now I realized it was wisdom.\n\nThe next day, I found Xiao Yu: "Tell me about your hamster?"\n\nShe looked at me suspiciously, then tentatively said a few words. This time, I put down my pen, looked her in the eyes, and truly listened. When she described her hamster always tumbling sideways during backflips, I burst out laughing—the image was genuinely funny. Her eyes lit up again.\n\nIn the days that followed, I practiced being "good ears": putting things down when others talk, making eye contact, not rushing to interrupt. I discovered Xiao Yu was actually a fascinating person who observed her hamster like a little scientist. These were things I\'d never have known when I was busy talking over her.\n\nAfter learning to listen, I gained not just a closer friend, but a new pair of ears for discovering the world.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Friend\'s one sentence sparks conflict—"you never listen"'},{fnEn:'Recalls various instances of "not listening"'},{fnEn:'Actively changes, truly listens'},{fnEn:'Sustained change + double reward'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Fresh topic choice',detailEn:'Doesn\'t choose common themes like "resilience" or "forgiveness"—"listening" is refreshingly original'},{pointEn:'Starting with flaws',detailEn:'Opens with "I was a bad friend"—starting with faults creates more tension than starting with virtues'},{pointEn:'Change needs action details',detailEn:'"Put down the pen, looked her in the eyes"—specific actions demonstrate change'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'"You never listen to me"—like a bucket of cold water',whyEn:'Opens with emotional impact—one sentence hooks the reader'},{textEn:'Xiao Yu\'s voice was soft, like a leaf touching ground',whyEn:'Exquisite simile capturing a disappointed yet gentle tone'},{textEn:'Not just a closer friend, but a new pair of ears for discovering the world',whyEn:'The double reward makes the theme richer'}]}
  ]
};

