TOPICS['yn2014_comp'] = {
  promptEn:'Write an essay titled "___, I Want to Tell You." Complete the title; have a clear theme, logical flow, specific content, smooth language, and genuine emotion; at least 400 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'An "emotional expression" semi-open essay. Fill in who you want to address (person/object/abstract concept). Key: (1) choose someone you truly have feelings about; (2) use a specific event to trigger the confession; (3) convey the "wanting to say but couldn\'t before" tension.',
    pitfallsEn:['Writing to celebrities—too distant, lacks authenticity','Saying "I want to tell you" throughout without specifics','Listing events without focus—becomes a log','Piling up flowery language instead of genuine emotion'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose someone with real emotional connection','Convey feelings through specific events','Show the "wanting but unable to say" psychological tension','Simple sincerity beats ornate language']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'Mom, I Want to Tell You',fullTextEn:'Mom, there are words I\'ve kept inside for a long time. Today, I want to tell you.\n\nDo you remember that evening last month? I scored only 72 in math and hid the test paper at the bottom of my backpack. When you asked my score, I stammered out the number. You went silent for a few seconds—seconds longer than an entire class period. Then you said: "Go correct your mistakes." Nothing more.\n\nI thought you didn\'t care anymore. But that night on my way to the bathroom, I overheard you on the phone with Dad, voice pressed low: "I\'m anxious too, but I don\'t want to put too much pressure on her..." Your voice trembled slightly.\n\nMom, I stood outside your door for a long time that moment. I\'d mistaken your silence for coldness. But it was actually tenderness—what remained after you swallowed your criticism and anxiety.\n\nThere have been so many moments like this. Every time I slam my door in a tantrum, you don\'t chase me to argue—you just quietly leave a cup of warm water at my door. When I do well, you smile; when I don\'t, you just cook an extra dish I love. Your love is never loud, but it\'s always there.\n\nMom, I want to tell you: thank you for always saving your patience for me and keeping your anxiety to yourself. I\'ll work harder from now on—not for grades, but so you won\'t have to whisper "I\'m anxious too" alone in the night.\n\nI can\'t say these words out loud, but I\'m writing them here, hoping you\'ll know.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Direct thesis—"words kept inside" creates anticipation'},{fnEn:'Test incident → overheard phone call → cognitive shift'},{fnEn:'Expands from one event to everyday love'},{fnEn:'Formally says the unsaid + makes a promise'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Letter-style confession',detailEn:'Uses second person "you" throughout, addressing Mom directly—intimate and sincere'},{pointEn:'Misunderstanding-to-understanding arc',detailEn:'From thinking Mom "doesn\'t care" to discovering she "swallowed her anxiety"—cognitive reversal touches hearts'},{pointEn:'Details carry emotion',detailEn:'Test hidden in backpack, seconds of silence, warm water at the door—all conveyed through details'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Those few seconds felt longer than an entire class period',whyEn:'Well-measured hyperbole precisely captures the agony of waiting to be scolded'},{textEn:'Your voice trembled slightly',whyEn:'One word "trembled" conveys all of Mom\'s restraint and heartache'},{textEn:'Your love is never loud, but it\'s always there',whyEn:'A concise summary that crystallizes the essay\'s emotional core'}]},
    {titleEn:'Teacher, I Want to Tell You',fullTextEn:'Teacher Li, you probably don\'t know—you changed my entire fifth grade.\n\nI had just transferred to a new school with no friends. I always sat alone, never going out during recess. Classmates called me "the mute," and I\'d just lower my head, making myself even smaller.\n\nOne day in Chinese class, you asked us to read aloud. I dreaded this most—I have a slight stutter, and I freeze up when nervous. Sure enough, when my turn came: "In spring, the—the—" The next word simply wouldn\'t come out. Someone in class laughed, and my face burned like fire.\n\nYou didn\'t tell me to sit down, and you didn\'t skip me. You walked to my desk, bent down, and in a voice only I could hear, said: "No rush. Deep breath. Let\'s read together."\n\nThen your voice wove with mine—"In spring, the footsteps draw near." You read slowly and steadily, like a hand guiding me past the hardest obstacle.\n\nFrom then on, you\'d quietly tell me before each class which passage we\'d be reading, letting me practice ahead. Two months later, I read an entire paragraph fluently for the first time—and the whole class applauded. In that moment, I suddenly felt I could be good enough.\n\nTeacher Li, I want to tell you: thank you for not telling me to "sit down," but choosing to "read together." That wasn\'t just a reading lesson—it was the most important lesson of my life: when someone struggles, don\'t make them retreat; walk through it with them.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Directly states the subject and core—"you changed me"'},{fnEn:'Transfer student\'s struggles and stuttering humiliation'},{fnEn:'Teacher\'s response—the pivotal event'},{fnEn:'Two months of change'},{fnEn:'Extracts life lesson from teacher\'s actions'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Single core event',detailEn:'The entire essay focuses on just "reading aloud"—focused and deep'},{pointEn:'Expressive dialogue',detailEn:'"No rush, deep breath, let\'s read together"—nine words paint a wonderful teacher'},{pointEn:'From being helped to understanding help',detailEn:'The closing insight isn\'t just gratitude—it\'s understanding the meaning of the teacher\'s actions'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Making myself even smaller',whyEn:'"Smaller" vividly depicts an unconfident child\'s posture'},{textEn:'Your voice wove with mine',whyEn:'Not "reading for" but "reading with"—showing respect and companionship'},{textEn:'Like a hand guiding me past the hardest obstacle',whyEn:'Accurately metaphorizes the companionship of sound into something tangible'}]},
    {titleEn:'Childhood, I Want to Tell You',fullTextEn:'Childhood, I want to say goodbye to you. Not because you weren\'t good, but because I\'ve grown up.\n\nRemember that path to school? Wildflowers lined both sides, and I\'d always squat down to count petals. Five on one, six on another... I\'d count until I was late, getting my name written down by the hall monitor. But I could never understand—flowers are so beautiful, why can\'t I stop and count?\n\nRemember that old banyan tree? During ten-minute breaks, my friends and I climbed it like monkeys, perching on the thickest branch, feeling like the tallest people in the world. When wind blew, the leaves rustled like applause.\n\nRemember that rainy day? I deliberately walked without an umbrella, splashing through puddles all the way home. Raindrops dripped from my hair to my nose, and I stuck out my tongue to catch one—cool, with a hint of earth. Mom scolded me when I got home, but I secretly giggled all night.\n\nBut now, that path has become a wide road, the wildflowers gone. The old banyan still stands, but I\'d never climb it—not because I can\'t, but because it feels "childish." On rainy days, I dutifully carry an umbrella—not afraid of getting wet, but because there\'s a test tomorrow and I can\'t catch a cold.\n\nChildhood, I want to tell you: I know you haven\'t gone far. You\'re hiding in those days of counting petals, in the rustling leaves, in the cool taste of raindrops. I\'ll grow up, but I won\'t forget.\n\nThank you for teaching me that the most precious things in the world are the sceneries that pass by before we can say goodbye.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Saying "goodbye" to childhood—sets a nostalgic tone'},{fnEn:'Counting petals on the path—innocence'},{fnEn:'Climbing the banyan—fearlessness'},{fnEn:'Splashing in puddles—freedom'},{fnEn:'Present vs. past contrast—the cost of growing up'},{fnEn:'Farewell + gratitude'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Personified subject',detailEn:'Treats "childhood" as a friend to converse with—a fresh angle'},{pointEn:'Montage method',detailEn:'Three independent vignettes in parallel, each with vivid imagery'},{pointEn:'Past vs. present shows depth',detailEn:'The contrast isn\'t criticizing growth but appreciating it'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Flowers are so beautiful, why can\'t I stop and count?',whyEn:'A child\'s innocent question—simple yet profound'},{textEn:'Wind blew, leaves rustled like applause',whyEn:'Vivid personification captures childhood\'s joyful atmosphere'},{textEn:'The most precious things are sceneries that pass before we can say goodbye',whyEn:'A closing golden line that transcends childhood nostalgia into life philosophy'}]},
    {titleEn:'Dad, I Want to Tell You',fullTextEn:'Dad, it\'s been so long since you held me.\n\nI remember when I was little, you carried me every day, lifting me over your head yelling "airplane takeoff!" I remember riding on your shoulders to see lanterns—your shoulders were the best viewing platform in the world. But somehow, your most frequent words to me became: "Did you finish your homework?"\n\nEvery day you come home late. When the lock clicks, I\'m already in bed, watching your shadow through the door crack—bending over to change shoes, moving slowly, tiredly. Sometimes you push my door open to peek—thinking I\'m asleep, you gently close it. But I\'m not asleep. I\'m waiting for you.\n\nOne weekend, I finally gathered courage: "Dad, can you take me cycling?" You hesitated, glanced at work messages on your phone, then said: "Sure."\n\nThat afternoon, we rode along the riverside greenway for a long way. You rode faster than me, turning to shout "keep going!" just as the sunset hit your face. I suddenly noticed grey hairs at your temples and fine lines when you smiled.\n\nWhen did you age so much? My heart clenched.\n\nDad, I want to tell you: I know work is exhausting, I know your overtime is for our family. But I also want you to know—I don\'t need you to buy me lots of things. I just need you, sometimes when you push my door open, not to just peek and leave—but to sit down and hear about my day at school.\n\nYou haven\'t held me in a long time. But that\'s okay—I can hold you.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'One sentence thesis, simple yet powerful'},{fnEn:'Childhood closeness vs. present distance'},{fnEn:'Dad\'s late-night routine—pretending to sleep while waiting'},{fnEn:'Cycling event—reconnecting + noticing Dad\'s aging'},{fnEn:'Saying what\'s on the heart'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Opening is the climax',detailEn:'First line "it\'s been so long since you held me" immediately triggers emotional resonance'},{pointEn:'Everyday scenes',detailEn:'Shadow changing shoes, peeking through the door—the most ordinary yet most moving images'},{pointEn:'Reversed echo ending',detailEn:'Opening "you haven\'t held me" → ending "I can hold you"—role reversal, deeply moving'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Your shoulders were the best viewing platform in the world',whyEn:'A warm metaphor that makes fatherly love tangible'},{textEn:'But I\'m not asleep. I\'m waiting for you',whyEn:'The simplest possible truth—maximally powerful emotionally'},{textEn:'You haven\'t held me in a long time. But that\'s okay—I can hold you',whyEn:'Role reversal from receiver to giver of love—a mark of growth'}]},
    {titleEn:'Books, I Want to Tell You',fullTextEn:'Dear books, if you had ears, I\'d have so much to tell you.\n\nBefore third grade, honestly, I kind of hated you. Every evening after homework, Mom made me read you for half an hour. In my hands, you were like a brick—heavy, with characters packed densely together, making me yawn.\n\nBut one day, I randomly opened Charlotte\'s Web in the library. A pig and a spider—sounded silly. But as I read, I forgot everything around me. When Charlotte wove "SOME PIG" into her web, my nose stung. When Charlotte died, I buried my face in my arms, pretending to rest, secretly wiping tears.\n\nAfter that, you completely transformed in my eyes. You were no longer a brick but a door—opening Journey to the West, I soared through clouds with Sun Wukong; opening Grass House, I smelled straw in Youmadi\'s sunshine; opening The Little Prince, I learned that "what is essential is invisible to the eye."\n\nBooks, the most magical thing about you is: you lie there perfectly still, yet take me anywhere. You have no voice, yet you\'ve said the most to me.\n\nNow my bookshelf is full, but my world has grown larger because of you. Books, I want to tell you: thank you for turning a yawning little kid into a young person who cries, laughs, and thinks.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Sets up past—once hated books'},{fnEn:'Turning point—Charlotte\'s Web moved me'},{fnEn:'Fell in love with reading, lists multiple books'},{fnEn:'Summarizes books\' magic + reflection'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Personifying a non-human subject',detailEn:'Treating books as a friend with ears—uniquely creative angle'},{pointEn:'Attitude transformation arc',detailEn:'Hatred → turning point → love—a clear psychological journey'},{pointEn:'Specific titles add authenticity',detailEn:'Mentioning Charlotte\'s Web, Journey to the West, Grass House, The Little Prince proves genuine reading'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'In my hands, you were like a brick',whyEn:'Vivid metaphor captures a child\'s resistance to reading'},{textEn:'No longer a brick but a door',whyEn:'Contrasting metaphors—brick to door—attitude shift at a glance'},{textEn:'You have no voice, yet you\'ve said the most to me',whyEn:'A paradox that poetically captures the essence of reading'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic 3: km2017_comp "最美丽的___" ──
TOPICS['km2017_comp'] = {
  promptEn:'Title: The Most Beautiful ___. Fill in a suitable word on the line, such as "heart," "language," "moment," "scene," "scenery," etc., to complete the title, then write your essay. Express genuine feelings, ensure smooth sentences and specific content. At least 400 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'The prompt offers five directions (heart/language/moment/scene/scenery), but the high-scoring strategy is to choose a more specific, unique word. "Most beautiful" implies: (1) comparison—this is more beautiful than others; (2) discovery—finding beauty in the ordinary.',
    pitfallsEn:['Writing about scenery but only listing without emotion','Choosing too broad/abstract a word like "The Most Beautiful Life"','Only describing external beauty without inner beauty','Missing the "most" comparison—why is this the "most"'],
    keyPointsEn:['A small, specific word ("silhouette," "smile," "lie") outshines big words','Use a specific scene/event to embody "beauty"','Include a process of "discovering beauty"—from overlooking/misunderstanding to discovering/understanding','Inner beauty scores higher than outer beauty']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'The Most Beautiful Lie',fullTextEn:'I always thought beauty and lies were two words that would never meet. Until that winter.\n\nGrandma was hospitalized. Every time we visited, she\'d cheerfully say: "It\'s nothing, just a little cold. I\'ll be home in a couple of days." I believed her because she still seemed energetic, sitting up in bed peeling oranges for me.\n\nBut one day, I secretly overheard Mom crying in the hallway. Dad said: "Don\'t let the child know. Mom said she doesn\'t want her granddaughter to worry." I hid around the corner, heart pounding. That night I looked up the words from Grandma\'s medical chart online, and the explanation on the screen made my hands start shaking.\n\nThe next day at the hospital, Grandma said her usual "It\'s nothing." But this time, I noticed the wrinkles at her eyes were deeper than before, and there was a large purple bruise where the IV needle went in. She pushed the biggest orange segment into my hand and said: "Grandma\'s oranges are so sweet. Try one."\n\nI took the orange and smiled: "Really sweet."\n\nActually, that segment was sour. But I also chose to lie.\n\nLater, Grandma had surgery and recovered well. The day she was discharged, she held my hand and said: "See? Grandma told you it was nothing." I nodded hard, tears spinning in my eyes, forcing myself to hold them back.\n\nThat was the most beautiful lie I\'ve ever seen—not meant to deceive, but to protect. Grandma used "it\'s nothing" to hold up my peace of mind, and I used "really sweet" to guard her hope.\n\nSome lies are warmer than the truth.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Beauty + lie paradox sparks curiosity'},{fnEn:'Grandma\'s first "it\'s nothing"—I believed it'},{fnEn:'Overhearing the truth'},{fnEn:'Knowing the truth, hearing "it\'s nothing" again—completely different feeling'},{fnEn:'Grandma recovers'},{fnEn:'Mutual lies are both expressions of love'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Oxymoron topic selection',detailEn:'"Beautiful lie" is itself a paradox, creating built-in tension'},{pointEn:'Dual lies echo each other',detailEn:'Grandma lies to me, I lie to Grandma—mutual protection and warmth'},{pointEn:'Taste conveys emotion',detailEn:'"Sour orange called sweet"—simplicity at its most powerful'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Beauty and lies are two words that would never meet',whyEn:'Opens with cognitive conflict, provoking thought'},{textEn:'Actually that segment was sour. But I also chose to lie',whyEn:'The essay\'s most powerful two sentences—short and devastating'},{textEn:'Grandma used "it\'s nothing" to hold up my peace of mind, and I used "really sweet" to guard her hope',whyEn:'Balanced parallel structure perfectly captures the two-way love'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Most Beautiful Silhouette',fullTextEn:'Every morning at 7:10, there\'s always a figure in an orange vest at the school gate, vigorously waving a small red flag. She\'s our school\'s traffic volunteer—a grey-haired auntie.\n\nHonestly, I never used to look at her properly. Every day passing the school gate, I\'d just chat with classmates. In my eyes, she was nothing but a moving "orange piece of furniture."\n\nUntil one day after school, a sudden downpour hit. The road by the school gate turned into a small river, vehicles and pedestrians jammed together. I huddled under the eaves, not daring to cross. Then that orange figure charged into the rain. One hand held up the red flag to stop cars, the other hand gripped a young child\'s hand, splashing through ankle-deep water to escort the child to the other side. Then she ran back for a second child, a third...\n\nRainwater streamed down her hair, the orange vest soaked and clinging to her body. Her pant legs were covered in mud. But her steps never stopped.\n\nWhen it was my turn to cross, she took my hand with her rain-soaked, pale-white hands and smiled: "Walk slowly, don\'t fall." I suddenly felt a lump in my throat.\n\nFrom that day on, every morning passing the school gate, I\'d greet her: "Good morning, Auntie." She\'d always smile with delighted surprise. I no longer saw just "orange furniture," but a person who arrived before us every day and left after us.\n\nThe most beautiful silhouette isn\'t necessarily under a spotlight. Sometimes it stands at the school gate, wearing a rain-soaked orange vest.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Introduces the character + previous indifference'},{fnEn:'Core event in the rainstorm'},{fnEn:'From bystander to being helped—emotional turning point'},{fnEn:'Attitude change + theme elevation'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'From ignoring to discovering',detailEn:'First writing "never looked at her properly," then being moved—the contrast makes the change more powerful'},{pointEn:'Greatness in ordinary people',detailEn:'Writing about a traffic volunteer instead of parents or teachers—unique selection'},{pointEn:'Environment drives emotion',detailEn:'The rainstorm is both the event catalyst and emotional backdrop'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'In my eyes she was nothing but a moving "orange piece of furniture"',whyEn:'Self-deprecating metaphor that honestly admits previous indifference'},{textEn:'Rain-soaked, pale-white hands',whyEn:'Intensely visual detail that evokes sympathy'},{textEn:'The most beautiful silhouette isn\'t necessarily under a spotlight',whyEn:'The ending breaks the common "parents\' silhouette" pattern with social awareness'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Most Beautiful Failure',fullTextEn:'"Third—place!" When the host announced my ranking, my heart felt like someone squeezed it hard.\n\nIt was the district speech competition finals. I\'d prepared for a whole month, practicing expressions in the mirror daily, correcting my tone against recordings. My goal was clear—first place. But I only got third. Standing on the podium, my smile looked paper-thin.\n\nOn the way home, I didn\'t say a word. Dad glanced at me, didn\'t offer comfort, just silently drove to Green Lake. He got out and said: "Let\'s walk."\n\nGreen Lake\'s evening breeze carried floral scent. After walking half the lake, Dad pointed at a crooked tree growing from a rock crevice: "See this tree—does it grow straight?"\n\n"No."\n\n"But it survived. A tree that grows from rock crevices is tougher than one in a greenhouse." He paused, then added: "Third place isn\'t failure. Knowing you can still improve—that\'s the real gain."\n\nThat night, alone in my room, I pulled up the competition video and watched it again. This time I didn\'t look at rankings—just at myself. I noticed one section where my hand was shaking the whole time, and another part where I spoke too fast. These were things I couldn\'t see no matter how much I practiced—the competition was a magnifying glass that revealed them.\n\nLater, I posted that third-place certificate right above my desk. Whenever someone asks why I don\'t display a first-place one, I smile and say: "Because this one taught me the most."\n\nThe most beautiful failure is the kind that helps you see yourself more clearly. Its beauty isn\'t in the result—it\'s in the courage and direction it brings.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Competition results announced—gap between expectation and reality'},{fnEn:'Dad drives to Green Lake + tree in rock crevice—mentorship'},{fnEn:'Re-watching the video → self-discovery'},{fnEn:'Posting the certificate + thesis statement'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Unconventional word choice elevates meaning',detailEn:'"Beautiful" paired with "failure" creates collision beyond the expected'},{pointEn:'Using objects to convey reasoning',detailEn:'The crooked tree in the rock crevice—nature\'s analogy makes the lesson easier to accept'},{pointEn:'Actions prove insight',detailEn:'Not just "understanding" but re-watching the video and posting the certificate—actions ground the essay'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'My heart felt like someone squeezed it hard',whyEn:'Tactile metaphor for disappointment—more authentic than "heartbroken"'},{textEn:'A tree from rock crevices is tougher than one in a greenhouse',whyEn:'Dad\'s words are plainly powerful—the essay\'s intellectual core'},{textEn:'The most beautiful failure is the kind that helps you see yourself more clearly',whyEn:'A precise, insightful definition of "failure\'s beauty"'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Most Beautiful Sound',fullTextEn:'What\'s the most beautiful sound you\'ve ever heard? A singer\'s high notes, a piano melody, or waves crashing against rocks? For me, the most beautiful sound is the "I\'m fine" that comes after Grandma\'s cough.\n\nGrandma\'s throat has never been great—her voice always carries a slight rasp. When I was little, I loved hearing her hum songs. Those old songs, filtered through her raspy voice, somehow gained the flavor of passing years.\n\nLast winter, Grandma\'s cough became more and more frequent. Every phone call, she\'d cough twice then say "It\'s nothing, just the cold weather." Mom told her to come to the city to see a doctor. She said "Country air is better—a few days\' rest and I\'ll be fine." Stubborn as an old ox.\n\nWhen we went back for New Year, I noticed Grandma had lost a lot of weight. But she was still bustling around the stove making my favorite roasted potatoes and rice cakes, flipping them while coughing, coughing while laughing: "There there, your grandma hasn\'t lost her touch yet."\n\nThat night, I lay beside Grandma, listening to her breathing. Very soft, occasionally interrupted by a suppressed cough—as if afraid of waking me. Moonlight squeezed through the window crack, illuminating her face. So many more wrinkles than I remembered.\n\nSuddenly I felt that her "I\'m fine" was the most beautiful yet most heartbreaking sound in the world. Because what she really meant was: "Don\'t worry about me—as long as you\'re doing well."\n\nAfter New Year, back in the city, I mailed Grandma a scarf with a note: "Grandma, remember to wrap up when it\'s cold. I\'m fine—and you need to be fine too."\n\nThe most beautiful sound sometimes isn\'t about how pleasant the tone is, but about how much love is hidden inside it—love it doesn\'t want you to know about.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Rhetorical question introduction + childhood memories'},{fnEn:'Coughing worsens—cause for worry'},{fnEn:'Going home for New Year—specific scenes'},{fnEn:'Understanding the true meaning of "I\'m fine"'},{fnEn:'My response + thesis'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Sound as the thread',detailEn:'The entire essay is strung together by sounds—humming → coughing → "I\'m fine" → breathing'},{pointEn:'Auditory approach to family love',detailEn:'Instead of hugs or tears, it uses sound—a unique sensory angle'},{pointEn:'Responsive ending',detailEn:'Grandma says "I\'m fine," I respond "You need to be fine too"—an emotional full circle'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Those old songs gained the flavor of passing years through her raspy voice',whyEn:'Turns a flaw into a feature—warm expression'},{textEn:'A suppressed cough, as if afraid of waking me',whyEn:'An extremely fine detail capturing Grandma\'s silent thoughtfulness'},{textEn:'How much love hidden inside that doesn\'t want you to know',whyEn:'One sentence explains why the sound is beautiful'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Most Beautiful Hands',fullTextEn:'There\'s an old man who sells roasted sweet potatoes by the school gate. His hands are the most beautiful hands I\'ve ever seen.\n\nYou must think I\'m joking. His hands are rough as tree bark, with indelible soot embedded in the creases between his fingers, and darkened nail beds. In winter, the backs of his hands are covered in cracked fissures, each crack lined with red. By appearance alone, these hands have nothing to do with "beauty."\n\nBut did you know? Every morning at six, he pushes his tricycle cart to the school gate. The roasting oven runs extremely hot, and he doesn\'t wear gloves—"Can\'t flip them right with gloves on." Every sweet potato is turned by hand, one by one, until the skin is golden-crisp and the inside oozes honey.\n\nOne rainy day, a young girl fumbled for change to buy a sweet potato, her hands shaking from cold, coins scattering on the ground. The old man bent down to help pick them up, pressed the money back into her hand, and handed her the best-roasted sweet potato: "Grandpa\'s treat today." Then he wiped his jet-black hands on his apron and smiled sheepishly.\n\nThe little girl ran off hugging the warm sweet potato. I stood nearby watching his hands reach back toward the oven fire, thinking: How many years has he been roasting sweet potatoes? How many people has he fed? Aren\'t those cracks and soot just the medals that labor and kindness left behind?\n\nLater I wrote a journal entry called "The Sweet Potato Grandpa at the Gate." My teacher wrote in the comments: "You discovered beauty in the ordinary—that itself is beautiful."\n\nThe most beautiful hands aren\'t pale, slender, and manicured. They\'re hands that have pushed hard for a living and warmed others along the way.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Presents the "counterintuitive" claim—rough hands are beautiful'},{fnEn:'Beauty of labor—the daily roasting routine'},{fnEn:'Beauty of kindness—giving a sweet potato on a rainy day'},{fnEn:'Reflection on what labor and kindness mean'},{fnEn:'Teacher\'s comment + thesis elevation'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Contrast creates tension',detailEn:'First describing how ugly the hands are, then how beautiful—the greater the contrast, the greater the impact'},{pointEn:'Social awareness perspective',detailEn:'Writing about an ordinary laborer rather than family or teachers shows observation and humanistic concern'},{pointEn:'Cleverly borrowing another\'s voice',detailEn:'The teacher\'s comment naturally elevates the essay without seeming forced'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Hands rough as tree bark, with indelible soot in the finger creases',whyEn:'Doesn\'t shy from "ugliness"—honest description builds momentum for the later "beauty"'},{textEn:'Aren\'t those cracks and soot just the medals left by labor and kindness',whyEn:'A rhetorical question redefining "flaws" as "medals"—a brilliant shift in perspective'},{textEn:'Hands that pushed hard for a living and warmed others along the way',whyEn:'Two uses of "for" capture the two dimensions of ordinary beauty'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic 4: yn2018_comp "改写《两小儿辩日》" ──
TOPICS['yn2018_comp'] = {
  promptEn:'Rewrite the classical text "Two Children Debating the Sun" as a short story. Make it vivid and specific. You may create your own title. At least 400 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'The key to rewriting is: (1) stay faithful to the original plot without translating sentence by sentence; (2) add reasonable descriptive details (environment, character appearances, expressions, actions, psychology); (3) use modern vernacular to create interest; (4) keep the characters distinct. Core elements: two children debate whether the sun is nearer at dawn or noon, each with their own reasoning, and even Confucius cannot decide.',
    pitfallsEn:['Translating the classical text word-for-word—that\'s translation, not rewriting','Only dialogue without scenes—reads like a script, not a story','Added content strays from the original—over-adaptation','Ignoring Confucius\'s role—his reaction is crucial'],
    keyPointsEn:['Give the two children distinct personality traits','Add environmental description (early morning road, trees, wind, etc.)','Enrich dialogue details to make the debate entertaining','Confucius\'s reaction should embody the spirit of "intellectual honesty"']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'How Far Away Is the Sun?',fullTextEn:'On a spring morning, the mist hadn\'t yet cleared. Beside a flagstone path, under two old scholar trees, two children were arguing red in the face.\n\nThe tall boy was called Ah Dong, and the short girl was Xiao Tang. They\'d grown up in the same village and loved to debate everything—from how many legs ants have to whether fish in the river dream. Today\'s topic was extra big—the sun.\n\n"Look, look!" Ah Dong pointed at the just-risen sun, his cheeks glowing from the dawn light. "The morning sun is as big as a cartwheel, but by noon it\'s only plate-sized. What does that mean? It means the sun is closer in the morning and farther at noon! Things look bigger when they\'re close!"\n\nXiao Tang rolled her eyes and put her hands on her hips: "All you know is size! Feel the morning breeze—chilly, right? Now feel the noon sun—hot as a steamer! Why? Because at noon the sun is closer to us! Close means hot! Far means cold! How can you not understand something so simple?"\n\n"That\'s twisted logic!" Ah Dong got heated.\n\n"You\'re the twisted one!" Xiao Tang fired right back.\n\nJust as they were arguing at fever pitch, an elderly man in a tall hat and long robes walked by, leaning on a bamboo staff. Behind him followed several refined-looking students. Ah Dong and Xiao Tang looked—wasn\'t this the great scholar Confucius who traveled the kingdoms? Villagers said he knew everything from astronomy to geography, and no question could stump him.\n\n"Master! Master!" Both children ran over, each tugging a sleeve. "Please settle this—is the sun closer to us in the morning or at noon?"\n\nConfucius stroked his beard and listened carefully to both arguments. His brow slowly furrowed, and he pondered for a long while. His students all gathered around, waiting for the teacher\'s wisdom.\n\nBut Confucius shook his head and smiled gently: "This question—honestly, I can\'t answer it either."\n\nBoth children\'s eyes went wide. They looked at each other, then burst out laughing together: "Haha! Everyone says you know everything, but there are things you don\'t know too!"\n\nConfucius laughed as well. He told his students: "To know what you know and to know what you don\'t know—that is true knowledge. Heaven and earth are vast, and no one can know everything. These two children taught me something—it\'s no shame to say \'I don\'t know\' when you truly don\'t."\n\nThe sun climbed higher, the mist cleared, and Ah Dong and Xiao Tang were already debating the next topic on the roadside: "Do you think the moon is home to a rabbit or a toad?"',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Environmental description + character introduction'},{fnEn:'Two children present their arguments with vivid metaphors and actions'},{fnEn:'Asking Confucius to judge'},{fnEn:'Confucius honestly admits not knowing, states the philosophy'},{fnEn:'Fun ending—a new debate begins'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Character individuation',detailEn:'Giving the two children names and personalities (love of debate) makes them vivid'},{pointEn:'Colloquial dialogue',detailEn:'"Twisted logic," "hot as a steamer"—colloquial expressions bring the classical text to life'},{pointEn:'Faithful to the original\'s essence',detailEn:'Confucius\'s "knowing what you know" statement preserves the educational meaning'},{pointEn:'Playful ending',detailEn:'Debating the moon—suggests the spirit of inquiry never stops, leaving a lasting impression'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'From how many legs ants have to whether fish dream',whyEn:'Vividly captures the two debate-loving children\'s daily life'},{textEn:'Xiao Tang rolled her eyes and put her hands on her hips',whyEn:'Action description brings the character to life on the page'},{textEn:'It\'s no shame to say "I don\'t know" when you truly don\'t',whyEn:'Conveys Confucius\'s wisdom in plain language children can understand'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Roadside Debate',fullTextEn:'Once upon a time in the Spring and Autumn Period, Confucius was traveling with his disciples when they heard two young voices arguing near a small village.\n\nApproaching, they saw two children of about seven or eight sitting under a large tree, glaring at each other, neither willing to yield. Beside them sat two bamboo baskets with vegetables spilling out—they\'d apparently been returning from the market and started arguing, forgetting all about the vegetables.\n\n"I\'ve told you eight hundred times!" The boy in blue drew a sun on the ground with a stick. "When the sun first rises in the morning, it\'s huge—like a carriage canopy. By noon? It shrinks to a plate. Everyone knows things look bigger when they\'re close and smaller when they\'re far. So the sun is near in the morning and far at noon!"\n\nThe boy in red snorted a laugh: "You use your eyes, I use my body! Is it cold when you step out in the morning? Cold! Is it hot standing under the noon sun? Hot! You feel hotter near a fire and cooler far from it—even a three-year-old understands! So the sun is obviously nearer at noon and farther in the morning!"\n\n"Seeing is believing!"\n\n"Feeling is truth!"\n\nTheir voices grew so loud they scared the birds off the tree.\n\nConfucius found this highly interesting. He signaled his disciples to be quiet and stepped forward, saying gently: "Good day, young sirs. The question you\'re debating is quite scholarly. Might I think it over too?"\n\nSeeing the distinguished-looking elder, both boys quieted down, awaiting the answer.\n\nConfucius thought and thought, stroked his beard three times over without stroking out an answer. He shook his head with genuine sincerity: "I\'m embarrassed to say—I truly don\'t know the answer to this."\n\nThe boys froze, then burst into laughter. The blue-clothed boy picked up his spilled vegetables: "Let\'s go, let\'s go—if even the greatest scholar doesn\'t know, this really is a tough question!"\n\nThe red-clothed boy followed: "But I still think I\'m right!"\n\n"I\'m clearly the right one!"\n\nTheir voices faded into the distance. Confucius watched them go, then turned to his disciples: "Today I learned a lesson—the knowledge between heaven and earth is infinite. Staying humble and daring to admit ignorance—that is true wisdom."',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Confucius traveling introduces the scene naturally'},{fnEn:'Two children\'s debate—added fun detail of drawing the sun'},{fnEn:'Confucius\'s curiosity and contemplation'},{fnEn:'Children leave, continue debating'},{fnEn:'Confucius teaches his disciples'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Everyday scene-setting',detailEn:'Spilled vegetable baskets—this kind of everyday detail makes the classical text approachable'},{pointEn:'Third-person omniscient narrator',detailEn:'Opening with "Once upon a time"—storyteller voice makes it feel like listening to a tale'},{pointEn:'Humor',detailEn:'"Stroked his beard three times without stroking out an answer"—humor makes Confucius more relatable'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Vegetables spilling out—apparently they\'d started arguing and forgot the vegetables',whyEn:'Original everyday detail makes the scene more real and fun'},{textEn:'Stroked his beard three times without stroking out an answer',whyEn:'Humorous description diffuses the embarrassment of "the great scholar not knowing"'},{textEn:'The knowledge between heaven and earth is infinite; staying humble and admitting ignorance is true wisdom',whyEn:'Elevated but not preachy—naturally expressed through Confucius\'s voice'}]},
    {titleEn:'Who\'s Right, Who\'s Wrong',fullTextEn:'Long, long ago, in a small town in the state of Lu, morning sunlight was filtering through thin clouds.\n\nBy the creek on the east end of town, two little boys were squatting on the ground drawing circles. One was called Shitou (Stone)—dark-skinned with a booming voice. The other was called Douzi (Bean)—fair-skinned with a quick mind. They were neighbors and the town\'s famous "debate duo."\n\n"Shitou, look!" Douzi pointed at the big red sun in the east. "The morning sun is so huge—like the stone mill we use for tofu. But at noon? It shrinks to the size of a copper coin. Bigger things are closer—that\'s called \'near-big, far-small.\' My mom uses this principle when measuring fabric for clothes!"\n\nShitou shook his head dismissively, fanning himself: "You just look, I feel. Feel right now—a cool breeze, right? Try again at noon—so hot you\'d want to dive into the creek! Why? Because the sun is closer at noon! Don\'t believe me? Try hugging the fire in the stove—the closer, the hotter. That\'s common sense!"\n\n"So you\'re saying I\'m wrong?"\n\n"I\'m just saying I\'m more right."\n\nJust then, a group arrived from outside town. The elder at the front had a gentle face and deep eyes. Shitou slapped Douzi\'s shoulder: "Look! My grandpa says that\'s Confucius! The most learned man in all the land!"\n\nThe two children sprinted over and blocked the road. Douzi spoke first: "Master, is the sun closer in the morning or at noon?" Shitou nodded vigorously beside him: "Yeah yeah, whatever you say goes!"\n\nConfucius crouched down and listened carefully to both children. He was silent for a moment, then stood up, brushed the dust off his robe, and said with a smile: "Both of your observations are very careful, and both of your reasons make sense. But this question... I truly don\'t know the answer."\n\nThe children exchanged glances and burst out laughing. Douzi said: "Even a great scholar like you has things he doesn\'t know?" Confucius nodded earnestly: "Of course—there are far too many things in this world. How could one person possibly know them all? Not knowing is simply not knowing."\n\nShitou scratched his head: "So who\'s right about our question?"\n\nConfucius thought for a moment: "Perhaps you\'re both right, or perhaps neither is. What matters is—you\'re willing to observe, to think, to debate. That\'s more precious than the answer itself."\n\nWith that, Confucius and his disciples continued on their way. In the sunlight, two small figures had already started a new debate: "So tell me, where do rainbows come from?"',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Time, place, and character setup'},{fnEn:'Both sides argue with everyday metaphors'},{fnEn:'Confucius appears and responds'},{fnEn:'New question begins—the beauty of cycles'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Everyday names for characters',detailEn:'"Shitou" and "Douzi" feel more relatable than "Child A and B"'},{pointEn:'Modernizing classical metaphors',detailEn:'"Stone mill" and "copper coin" fit the ancient setting but are understandable to modern readers'},{pointEn:'Confucius\'s warmth',detailEn:'Crouching down to listen, brushing off dust—these actions transform a sage into a kind old man'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'You\'re willing to observe, think, and debate—that\'s more precious than the answer itself',whyEn:'Transcends the right-or-wrong debate to celebrate the spirit of inquiry'},{textEn:'I\'m just saying I\'m more right',whyEn:'Childlike logic that makes you laugh'},{textEn:'So tell me, where do rainbows come from',whyEn:'Ending with a new question suggests curiosity never stops'}]},
    {titleEn:'That Morning\'s Quarrel',fullTextEn:'Dawn was just breaking, roosters still crowing. On the east end of the small village stood two households. On the left lived Little Fish, on the right lived Iron Egg. Both were about seven years old.\n\nEarly that morning, Little Fish carried a small stool to the yard gate to watch the sunrise. The sun had just peeked over the mountain, red and round, as big as the village\'s large iron cooking pot. She was mesmerized, murmuring: "The sun is so big..."\n\n"Of course!" Iron Egg had somehow appeared beside her, still chewing half a steamed bun. "The morning sun is big because it\'s close to us. By noon it runs far away and gets smaller."\n\nLittle Fish thought about it, then countered: "No way! You say the sun is close in the morning, then why is it so cold? I was shivering when I came out. If the sun were really close, it should feel like squatting by the stove!"\n\n"That—that\'s because—" Iron Egg was stumped, nearly choking on his bun.\n\n"Because what? Can\'t explain?" Little Fish grinned triumphantly. "Cold in the morning, hot at noon—clearly the sun is closer at noon!"\n\nIron Egg wouldn\'t concede: "But I can see it with my own eyes! Big means close!"\n\nLittle Fish held firm: "What my body feels! Hot means close!"\n\nBoth argued until their faces turned red. Just then, a passing gentleman overheard their conversation and stopped. He wore a slightly worn but very neat long gown, and his eyes were full of amusement.\n\n"Well now, you two are having quite the lively discussion," the gentleman walked over. "I\'m from far away, and I find this question quite fascinating myself."\n\nIron Egg and Little Fish each presented their reasoning. After listening, the gentleman pondered for a long while. He crouched down and told the children: "You both make good points, but though I\'ve read books my whole life, I can\'t answer this question either."\n\n"What?" both children exclaimed in unison.\n\nThe gentleman stood up, looking at the gradually rising sun: "There are far too many mysteries in the world—even a question like how far the sun is from us still has no answer. So never stop asking questions."\n\nHe walked away. Iron Egg swallowed the last bite of his bun and said to Little Fish: "Coming to watch the sunrise again tomorrow morning?"\n\nLittle Fish nodded: "Yes. Maybe we can figure out the answer ourselves."',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Discussion arises naturally from a daily scene'},{fnEn:'Both sides argue, interspersed with everyday actions'},{fnEn:'The old gentleman (Confucius) appears and responds'},{fnEn:'A warm promise—continue tomorrow'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Not naming Confucius',detailEn:'Writing him as "a passing gentleman" makes the story more natural'},{pointEn:'The steamed bun as a prop',detailEn:'Chewing the bun, nearly choking—everyday details add fun'},{pointEn:'Open ending',detailEn:'"Maybe we can figure it out ourselves"—encouraging the spirit of exploration'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Iron Egg was stumped, nearly choking on his bun',whyEn:'Physical reaction captures the embarrassment of being out-argued—more vivid than psychological description'},{textEn:'A slightly worn but very neat long gown',whyEn:'Not luxurious robes but "worn yet neat"—better fits Confucius\'s traveling image'},{textEn:'Maybe we can figure out the answer ourselves',whyEn:'A child\'s optimism and confidence—the warmest possible ending'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Sun of That Year',fullTextEn:'If the sun could speak, it would surely want to tell those two children: stop arguing—you\'re both right.\n\nIt was a spring morning two thousand five hundred years ago. On a grass-lined path, two children were arguing about the sun. Funny thing is, they weren\'t fighting over who got the first treat or who ran faster, but about when the sun was closer to them.\n\nOne said morning—"Look how big it is!" He spread his arms wide to demonstrate. The other said noon—"Feel how hot it is!" She fanned her palm vigorously. Each had their own reasons, their own evidence, and neither could out-argue the other.\n\nAs it happened, Confucius passed by. This elderly man, revered as a "sage" by the world, was also stumped by this question. He thought it over and honestly said three words: "I don\'t know."\n\nTwo thousand five hundred years have passed. Scientists finally have the answer: the distance between the sun and Earth is virtually the same in the morning and at noon. The sun looks bigger in the morning due to ground-level visual reference (an optical illusion), and it feels hotter at noon because sunlight strikes at a more direct angle. So—both children were right, and both were wrong.\n\nBut what I admire most isn\'t the final answer, but those two children from 2,500 years ago. Though they lived in an era without telescopes or computers, they had already learned to observe and think. They used "size" and "temperature" to reason—though their conclusions differed, their methods were both scientific.\n\nConfucius was even more admirable. As a "sage," he could have made up any answer to bluff his way through, but he chose to say "I don\'t know." Those three words are worth more than a hundred wrong answers.\n\nWhile rewriting this classical text, I wondered: if one day I faced a question I couldn\'t answer, would I be as candid as Confucius and say "I don\'t know"?\n\nI hope I can. Because "I don\'t know" isn\'t an endpoint—it\'s the starting point of all exploration.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Personified sun perspective—novel'},{fnEn:'Concisely retells the original story'},{fnEn:'Adds modern scientific explanation'},{fnEn:'Praises the children\'s and Confucius\'s spirit'},{fnEn:'Connects to self, states the theme'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Narrative-commentary hybrid rewriting',detailEn:'Not just telling a story but adding personal reflections—more depth'},{pointEn:'Ancient-modern contrast',detailEn:'2,500 years ago vs. today\'s science—temporal span makes the theme grander'},{pointEn:'Personified opening',detailEn:'The sun speaking—one sentence distinguishes this from all other rewritings'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'If the sun could speak, it would tell those two children: stop arguing—you\'re both right',whyEn:'Extremely novel personified opening that breaks all conventional rewriting patterns'},{textEn:'Those three words are worth more than a hundred wrong answers',whyEn:'A resounding evaluation of "I don\'t know"'},{textEn:'"I don\'t know" isn\'t an endpoint—it\'s the starting point of all exploration',whyEn:'The essay\'s core golden line, elevating the theme to epistemology'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic 5: yn2019_comp "___节" ──
TOPICS['yn2019_comp'] = {
  promptEn:'If you could create a fun holiday—like "No Socks Day," "Sleeping Day," "Mud Playing Day"...what kind of holiday would you establish? Write with "___Day/Festival" as the title, sharing your creative idea, explaining why you want to establish this holiday, and telling everyone what interesting activities you hope to have on this day. Write fluently and in order, about 350 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'This is a "creative imagination" essay. The core is: (1) the holiday name should be fun and unique; (2) there should be a reasonable "reason for establishing it"—why is this holiday needed; (3) describe specific activities in detail; (4) ideally include "imagined scenes" that immerse the reader.',
    pitfallsEn:['Holiday name too ordinary—"Reading Day" or "Sports Day" lacks creativity','Only naming it without explaining why—why is this holiday needed','Activity descriptions too vague—"everyone has fun" is too generic','Imagination defies logic—fun should still be reasonable'],
    keyPointsEn:['Holiday name needs a hook (funny/warm/unconventional)','The establishment reason should connect to real-life pain points','Describe 2-3 specific activities with vivid imagery','Consider adding an imaginative twist or warm ending']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'Compliment Festival',fullTextEn:'If I could establish a holiday, I\'d create "Compliment Festival."\n\nHave you noticed? In our lives, criticism seems far more common than praise. Score 98, and Mom says "Where did those 2 points go?" Draw a painting, and a classmate says "That looks like a pig." Come in fifth in a race, and Dad says "Four people beat you." Over time, nobody feels comfortable complimenting others, much less complimenting themselves.\n\nSo I\'m establishing Compliment Festival! On June 1st every year—yes, the same day as Children\'s Day. Double the happiness.\n\nOn this day, everyone must sincerely compliment at least three people. You could compliment your deskmate\'s handwriting, praise Mom\'s cooking, tell the bus driver he drives smoothly, or even compliment the street sweeper for making the road shine like a mirror.\n\nSchools would hold a "Compliment Competition"—not comparing who gets the most compliments, but who gives the most creative ones. Like someone complimenting the teacher: "Teacher Li, your eyes light up when you teach—like the sun—and our whole class is illuminated!" The whole room applauds!\n\nThe most special part is "Compliment Yourself." Everyone looks in a mirror and names three of their own strengths. Don\'t laugh—try it yourself. You\'ll find it\'s much harder than complimenting others. But after you do, you\'ll definitely think: Hey, I\'m actually pretty good.\n\nI believe if Compliment Festival really existed, the world would be much warmer. Because every sincere compliment is like a seed, planted in someone\'s heart, destined to bloom someday.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Directly reveals the holiday name'},{fnEn:'Reality of too few compliments in life'},{fnEn:'Time setting'},{fnEn:'Rule: compliment three people'},{fnEn:'Compliment Competition'},{fnEn:'Most special: compliment yourself'},{fnEn:'Warm aspiration'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Born from life\'s pain points',detailEn:'"More criticism than praise" is every child\'s real experience—easy to resonate with'},{pointEn:'Specific activity design',detailEn:'Compliment three people, competition, compliment yourself—three activities building progressively'},{pointEn:'Warm yet deep',detailEn:'Seems funny but actually addresses mental health—the concept rises above mere "fun"'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Score 98, and Mom says "Where did those 2 points go?"',whyEn:'So relatable—nearly every child has experienced this'},{textEn:'Not comparing who gets the most compliments, but who gives the most creative ones',whyEn:'Clever design turns "complimenting" into a skill competition'},{textEn:'Every sincere compliment is like a seed',whyEn:'Warm metaphor gives the essay a poetic conclusion'}]},
    {titleEn:'Silence Festival',fullTextEn:'I want to establish a "Silence Festival." You heard right—on this day, nobody in the entire world is allowed to speak.\n\nWhy? Because our world is just too noisy. In class the teacher talks, during break classmates shout, at home the TV blares, outside cars honk...from morning to night, our ears never get a break. I often wonder: if one day the whole world suddenly went quiet, what would that be like?\n\nSilence Festival would fall on the second Saturday of May every year.\n\nOn this day, you can\'t speak, but you can "express" in other ways. You can write notes to friends, smile at Mom with your eyes, draw a heart on the window with your finger. People would discover: you can communicate without a mouth, and some things are actually more sincere when written than spoken.\n\nIn class, the teacher fills the blackboard with notes, and students copy quietly. From outside come sounds usually drowned out by noise—birdsong, wind rustling through leaves, a distant clock tower chiming the hour. It turns out the world has been talking all along; we were just too loud to hear.\n\nAfter school, Mom hands me a note: "Made your favorite braised pork today." I draw a big smiley face on the back. In that moment, I feel that note is warmer than any words.\n\nWhen Silence Festival ends, the first thing everyone says out loud would surely be—those important words they\'d always wanted to say but never had.\n\nSilence, sometimes, is another way of expressing.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Surprising holiday name'},{fnEn:'The world is too noisy—sparks reflection'},{fnEn:'Activities: note exchanges, quiet classroom, Mom\'s note'},{fnEn:'Speaking the important words + meaning of silence'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Reverse-thinking topic',detailEn:'"Not speaking" is counterintuitive—counterintuitive is interesting'},{pointEn:'Discovering truth through imagination',detailEn:'After silence, hearing birdsong and wind—returning to nature\'s beauty'},{pointEn:'Emotional elevation',detailEn:'The first words spoken are "the important ones"—silence makes you think about what\'s worth saying'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'The world has been talking all along; we were just too loud to hear',whyEn:'A philosophical discovery that gives the imaginative essay intellectual depth'},{textEn:'Drew a big smiley face on the back of the note',whyEn:'Wordless communication feels even warmer'},{textEn:'Those important words they\'d always wanted to say but never had',whyEn:'Silence → reflection → speaking from the heart—perfect logic'}]},
    {titleEn:'Mistake Festival',fullTextEn:'I want to establish a "Mistake Festival"—on this day, making mistakes won\'t get you criticized; instead, you\'ll be encouraged.\n\nYou probably think I\'m crazy. But think about it: haven\'t we been terrified of making mistakes our whole lives? Write one wrong character on a test and lose two points. Fail an experiment and hear "How can you be so stupid?" Even losing a game feels shameful. Gradually, many people stop daring to try new things—what if they mess up?\n\nMistake Festival falls on April 1st every year (close to April Fools\' Day—easy to remember).\n\nOn this day, schools hold a "Greatest Mistakes" sharing session. Teachers go first, sharing mistakes from their childhood—you\'d never guess that your stern math teacher once calculated 3×7 as 28! The whole class erupts in laughter—not mockery, but pure delight.\n\nThen students share their mistakes. Someone drank a big gulp of soy sauce thinking it was cola. Someone wrote "Teacher has worked hardly" instead of "hard." Someone fell eleven times on their first try riding a bicycle. After each story, everyone applauds—because behind every mistake was a brave attempt.\n\nThe most important segment is called "Try Again." Schools set up experience stations: those who can\'t draw can scribble freely, those who can\'t sing can belt out whatever, those who can\'t cook can experiment. Nobody judges you, nobody grades you. Did it turn out badly? Congratulations—you\'re learning!\n\nI believe this holiday would change many people. Because every "can" in the world started with a "can\'t." Every "right" grew out of a "wrong."\n\nHappy Mistakes!—that\'s Mistake Festival\'s motto.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Counterintuitive holiday name—creates suspense'},{fnEn:'The reality of fearing mistakes'},{fnEn:'Teachers and students share mistakes'},{fnEn:'"Try Again" experience stations'},{fnEn:'Mistake → growth philosophy + motto'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Addresses a real educational pain point',detailEn:'"Fear of making mistakes" is a genuine psychological issue with high relevance'},{pointEn:'Progressively layered activities',detailEn:'Listen → share → do: from passive to active, increasing engagement'},{pointEn:'Strong critical thinking',detailEn:'"Every right grew from a wrong"—philosophical depth'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'The math teacher once calculated 3×7 as 28',whyEn:'A specific numerical detail makes the scene believable'},{textEn:'Did it turn out badly? Congratulations—you\'re learning',whyEn:'One sentence overturns conventional thinking'},{textEn:'Every "right" grew out of a "wrong"',whyEn:'A golden-line ending worthy of any exam essay'}]},
    {titleEn:'Swap Day',fullTextEn:'I want to establish a "Swap Day." On this day, parents and children swap roles—children become the parents, parents become the children.\n\nWhy this holiday? Because I feel my parents just don\'t understand me. They always say "You kids have it so easy these days" and "We didn\'t have these luxuries growing up." But they don\'t know that never-ending homework, non-stop extracurricular classes, and constant exams are anything but relaxing.\n\nSwap Day falls on the first day of summer vacation every year.\n\nAt 6:30 this morning, the child wakes the parents: "Get up! Three test papers waiting for you today!" Dad rubs his eyes and says he doesn\'t want to get up. The child puts on a stern face: "If you don\'t do your homework, how will you ever find a job?"\n\nIn the morning, Mom is "assigned" two hours of advanced math class—let her experience what it\'s like to not understand anything but not be allowed to leave. At lunch, the child says: "You can\'t eat that dish—too oily, not healthy. Eat more vegetables."\n\nIn the afternoon, Dad attempts a fifth-grade Chinese test. Halfway through the essay he collapses in his chair, declaring it\'s too hard. The child says coolly: "Only 200 words and you\'re tired? The requirement is 500."\n\nBy evening, the swap ends. The family of three sits on the sofa, staring at each other. Dad says: "Your homework is really hard." Mom says: "Two hours of class is really exhausting." I say: "Being a parent is tough too—the noodles I made for lunch, even I didn\'t want to eat them."\n\nThen we all laughed together.\n\nSwap Day isn\'t about making anyone more tired—it\'s about having everyone walk a day in the other person\'s shoes. Understanding sometimes only takes one day.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Reveals the holiday name and rule'},{fnEn:'Pain point: parents don\'t understand'},{fnEn:'Activities shown chronologically through the day'},{fnEn:'End-of-swap: both sides\' reflections'},{fnEn:'Theme of mutual understanding'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Cleverness of role reversal',detailEn:'Having parents experience children\'s lives naturally creates comedy and depth'},{pointEn:'Real conflicts',detailEn:'"Too much homework" and "exhausting classes" are real parent-child tensions—grounded topic'},{pointEn:'Two-way understanding',detailEn:'Not just parents understanding kids—the child understands parents too: "the noodles I didn\'t even want to eat"'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'If you don\'t do your homework, how will you ever find a job?',whyEn:'Child mimicking parent\'s tone—maximum satirical effect'},{textEn:'Only 200 words and you\'re tired? The requirement is 500',whyEn:'Role reversal comedy that makes you laugh'},{textEn:'Walk a day in the other person\'s shoes',whyEn:'The "shoes" metaphor captures "understanding" vividly and deeply'}]},
    {titleEn:'Apology Day',fullTextEn:'I want to establish an "Apology Day." On this day, everyone must say the "sorry" they owe to someone.\n\nSome apologies, if delayed too long, become impossible to say. Last semester I got into a fight with my good friend Xiao Lin—I was the one who said hurtful words first. That afternoon I already regretted it and wanted to apologize, but I just couldn\'t bring myself to. The next day I was going to say it, but he was absent. The third day he came, but I felt too much time had passed and it would be awkward. Just like that, one day dragged into the next, and to this day we still haven\'t made up.\n\nI\'m surely not the only one with "owed apologies." So I\'m establishing Apology Day—the first day of every school year.\n\nOn this day, everyone can write an "apology card" and drop it into an "Apology Mailbox" in the school lobby—no signature needed. It could say: "Sorry, I said you ran slow at last year\'s sports day," or "Sorry, I never returned the eraser you lent me." The cards get posted on an "Apology Wall," and whoever sees their message can take it.\n\nTeachers can participate too. Imagine receiving: "Sorry, I was too harsh when I criticized you last time. You\'d actually improved a lot." If you received a card like that, you\'d surely feel: so this is what it\'s like to be cared about.\n\nApology Day\'s final segment is the "Reconciliation Ceremony." Two people who want to make up stand face to face in the middle of the field. No words needed—just extend a hand and shake. The whole school applauds.\n\nSome say "sorry" is hard to say. That\'s okay—write it down first. Taking the first step makes everything after easier.\n\nMy reason for creating Apology Day is simple—I don\'t want to lose another friend over an unsaid "sorry."',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Holiday name + rule'},{fnEn:'Real personal experience'},{fnEn:'Apology mailbox and wall'},{fnEn:'Teachers participate too'},{fnEn:'Reconciliation Ceremony'},{fnEn:'Concise, powerful ending'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Starts from personal experience',detailEn:'Creating the holiday because of a personal inability to apologize—the most authentic motivation'},{pointEn:'Activity design with warmth',detailEn:'Anonymous cards lower the barrier; the reconciliation ceremony adds ceremony'},{pointEn:'Ending returns to the personal',detailEn:'From a public holiday back to private emotion—echoes beginning and end'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'One day dragged into the next, and to this day we still haven\'t made up',whyEn:'Authentically captures "apology procrastination"'},{textEn:'So this is what it\'s like to be cared about',whyEn:'The essence of apology isn\'t admitting fault—it\'s letting others know they matter'},{textEn:'I don\'t want to lose another friend over an unsaid "sorry"',whyEn:'The final sentence is both the holiday\'s mission statement and a heartfelt confession'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic 6: km2020_comp_a "科幻故事" ──
TOPICS['km2020_comp_a'] = {
  promptEn:'Science and technology that don\'t yet exist in real life but might be realized in the future—technologies that could impact people\'s lives or destinies. Spread your scientific wings, unleash your wildest imagination, and write a sci-fi story. Create your own title.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'Key to sci-fi essays: (1) the tech concept should have some plausibility (an extension of existing science); (2) don\'t just describe the tech—include characters and story; (3) convey reflection on technology through the story (pros and cons); (4) create your own title—make it eye-catching.',
    pitfallsEn:['Just listing tech features—reads like a product manual, not a story','Tech concept too arbitrary—magic isn\'t sci-fi','No conflict or plot—sci-fi still needs story','Ignoring human emotion—good sci-fi is about people, not just technology'],
    keyPointsEn:['Build the story around one core technology','Include characters, plot, and conflict','Naturally weave in reflections on technology','The ending can leave lingering thoughts or provoke thinking']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'The Memory Bakery',fullTextEn:'In 2088, an unassuming little shop opened in a corner of the city, its sign reading three words: The Memory Bakery.\n\nThis shop sold only one kind of bread—bread baked with your memories inside. Take a bite, and you relive that memory.\n\nA boy named Chen Xing was a regular. He never bought his own memory bread. Every time, he bought the same one—"Grandma\'s Summer." It was the summer he was five, spent at Grandma\'s countryside home. The moment the bread touched his lips, he returned to that cicada-filled afternoon: Grandma fanning him with a palm-leaf fan while telling stories, mung bean soup bubbling on the stove, the old yellow dog dozing under the tree shade. Everything was warm, slow, and sweet.\n\nGrandma passed away last year. Chen Xing could never taste her mung bean soup again, but in this bakery, he could return to that summer over and over.\n\nLater, a white-haired old man came in. He bought a bread, took one bite, and tears fell. "This is my wedding day memory," he said. "My wife\'s been gone three years. I was starting to forget what her smile looked like. Thank goodness for this shop."\n\nThe shop owner was a quiet, taciturn middle-aged man. When asked why he opened this shop, he\'d only say: "Because some things shouldn\'t be forgotten."\n\nBut one day, a scientist walked in, expression grave: "Memory bread has a side effect—the more you eat, the weaker your ability to create new memories becomes. You\'ll sink deeper and deeper into the past, forgetting to live in the present."\n\nChen Xing heard this, clutching the uneaten bread in his hand, and froze for a long time. He thought of that summer, thought of Grandma, then gently set the bread back on the counter.\n\n"Thank you," he told the owner. "I\'ve decided to go make a bowl of mung bean soup myself."',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Sci-fi premise—memory bread'},{fnEn:'Two warm memory bread stories'},{fnEn:'Scientist reveals the side effect—technology\'s duality'},{fnEn:'The protagonist\'s choice—looking forward'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Sci-fi + humanities',detailEn:'Memory bread is the sci-fi element, but the story\'s heart is longing for lost loved ones'},{pointEn:'Dialectical pros and cons',detailEn:'First showing tech\'s beauty, then revealing the side effect—not black and white'},{pointEn:'Character choice IS theme',detailEn:'Chen Xing putting down the bread and going to make soup—choosing to live in the present'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Everything was warm, slow, and sweet',whyEn:'Three adjectives capture the texture of childhood memories'},{textEn:'The more you eat, the weaker your ability to create new memories',whyEn:'A sci-fi concept harboring profound philosophy'},{textEn:'I\'ve decided to go make a bowl of mung bean soup myself',whyEn:'From "remembering Grandma" to "doing it yourself"—the best tribute is carrying on'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Last Tree',fullTextEn:'In 2120, only one tree remained on Earth.\n\nIt was planted inside a massive glass dome, guarded by robots around the clock. People traveled from all over the world to see it, waiting in line for three hours. This tree had become Earth\'s most precious "artifact."\n\nTwelve-year-old Lin Xiaoye first saw this tree during a holographic projection class. "What is that?" she asked the AI teacher.\n\n"That\'s a banyan tree," the AI teacher said. "It produces oxygen and provides habitat for birds and insects. A hundred years ago, trees were everywhere on Earth."\n\n"Everywhere?" Lin Xiaoye couldn\'t imagine. Her city was built entirely of metal and plastic. Air was manufactured by purifiers, food synthesized from nutrient solutions. She had never smelled a flower\'s fragrance, never heard the sound of wind through leaves.\n\nThat weekend, Lin Xiaoye convinced her parents to take her to see the tree. After four hours in line, she finally stood before the glass dome.\n\nThe banyan wasn\'t very tall. Its leaves were slightly yellow, its bark lined with cracks. But when a gust of artificial wind blew through, the leaves swayed gently, making a soft "sha sha sha" sound. Lin Xiaoye\'s eyes suddenly grew moist—she didn\'t know why, but that sound made her feel as if she were remembering something from very, very long ago.\n\n"Can you open the dome so I can touch it?" she asked the guard robot.\n\n"No. Physical contact could introduce bacteria and accelerate its death."\n\nLin Xiaoye pressed her hand against the glass, gazing through the cold barrier at those green leaves trembling in the breeze. In her heart she whispered: I\'m sorry. We came too late.\n\nBack home, Lin Xiaoye made a decision—she would become a botanist and bring trees back to Earth. Not one, but ten thousand, a million.\n\nThat night, she dreamed: everywhere she looked, there were trees, and wind whispered through leaves, sha sha sha.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Shocking sci-fi premise—only one tree left'},{fnEn:'Protagonist\'s unfamiliarity with "trees"—mirrors reality'},{fnEn:'Going to see the tree—moved by the "sha sha" sound'},{fnEn:'Resolution + dream'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Warm dystopia',detailEn:'Not horror-movie fear but quiet sadness—more emotionally moving'},{pointEn:'Defamiliarization technique',detailEn:'Making a child unfamiliar with "trees"—the reader\'s familiar thing becomes strange, amplifying impact'},{pointEn:'Sensory trigger for memory',detailEn:'The "sha sha" sound triggers genetic memory of nature—a sophisticated concept'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'She had never smelled a flower\'s fragrance, never heard the sound of wind through leaves',whyEn:'Parallel negation sentences that break your heart'},{textEn:'That sound made her feel as if she were remembering something from very, very long ago',whyEn:'Hints at genetic memory—both sci-fi and poetic'},{textEn:'I\'m sorry. We came too late',whyEn:'One sentence carries all of humanity\'s environmental regret'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Time Post Office',fullTextEn:'If you could send a letter to your future self, what would you write?\n\nIn 2077, Earth\'s first "Time Post Office" appeared. For one time coin (roughly equivalent to one minute of your life), you could mail a letter to any future date. The letter would appear at your door on that exact day, without fail.\n\nEleven-year-old He Ming sent a letter to his thirty-year-old self: "Hey, future me, hello! What do you do for work now? Have you been to the moon? Do you remember the summer of fifth grade? That summer you made a wish—to become an astronaut. Did you make it?"\n\nAfter mailing the letter, He Ming thought about it every day. He wondered: how would his thirty-year-old self answer when he got the letter?\n\nThis thought changed him. From then on, whenever he wanted to slack off on homework or quit physical training, he\'d think of that letter—if the version of himself nineteen years later opened the letter and found he\'d accomplished nothing, how disappointed would he be?\n\nTwo years later, He Ming sent another letter. This time to his twenty-five-year-old self: "I\'m in sixth grade now. My math improved a lot, and I scored full marks on the fitness test. I\'m walking toward you."\n\nThe Time Post Office owner was a white-bearded old man. Someone asked him: "Can these letters really be delivered to the future?"\n\nThe old man smiled: "Whether the letter arrives doesn\'t matter. What matters is that the moment you wrote it, you\'d already decided the direction of your future."\n\nHe Ming did become an astronaut. On his thirtieth birthday, no letter appeared at his door. But he wrote one himself—to his eleven-year-old self: "Thank you for that letter back then. Your wish—I made it come true for you."',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Time Post Office sci-fi premise'},{fnEn:'He Ming sends a letter → the letter changes him → second letter'},{fnEn:'The owner\'s answer reveals the truth'},{fnEn:'Letter didn\'t arrive but the dream came true'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Sci-fi is the shell, growth is the core',detailEn:'The Time Post Office is the premise; the real story is "self-motivation"'},{pointEn:'Twist ending',detailEn:'The letter didn\'t arrive—implying the post office might just be a well-intentioned "trick," but the effect was already achieved'},{pointEn:'Self-dialogue',detailEn:'Writing to future self → writing back to past self—beginning and end form a time loop'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'One time coin, roughly equivalent to one minute of your life',whyEn:'The "time coin" concept is novel, implying time is the most precious currency'},{textEn:'The moment you wrote it, you\'d already decided the direction of your future',whyEn:'Core golden line—the power of self-expectation'},{textEn:'Your wish—I made it come true for you',whyEn:'Beginning-end echo, from making a wish to fulfilling it—warm closure'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Translation Earbuds',fullTextEn:'In 2065, the best-selling invention was a pair of translation earbuds called "Omni-Lingua." Put them on, and you could understand any language in the world—including the language of animals.\n\nFifth-grader Su Xiaomi\'s entire world changed the first time she walked into the garden wearing the earbuds.\n\n"Don\'t step on me! Don\'t step on me!" the grass beneath her feet cried. She jumped aside in fright.\n\nSparrows chattered in the tree: "Ugh, the wind is so strong today. My new nest is tilting again." "Want me to help?" "No thanks, your wings are shorter than mine."\n\nAnts in the corner marched in formation chanting: "Left right left, left right left! Cookie crumbs spotted on the left—all units, move out!"\n\nSu Xiaomi laughed so hard she squatted on the ground and couldn\'t get up. She\'d never known the garden was this lively every day.\n\nBut gradually, she heard different sounds. The old tree in the backyard sighed: "My roots are sealed under concrete—I can barely breathe." The fish in the pond said: "The water is getting murkier. Three of my neighbors moved away last month." The stray cat curled in a cardboard box by the door said: "So cold. Nobody fed me again today."\n\nSu Xiaomi stopped laughing. She took off the earbuds, and the world went quiet again. But she knew—those voices had been there all along. She just hadn\'t been able to hear them before.\n\nThe next day, she did three things: chiseled a few holes in the concrete around the old tree\'s roots so they could breathe; bought fish food with her allowance and tossed it into the pond; built an insulated shelter for the stray cat with a bowl of cat food.\n\nThe translation earbuds were later banned from sale—because some people heard their pets talking behind their backs, causing disputes. But Su Xiaomi had no regrets. Because she\'d already learned to "hear" those voices without the earbuds—all you need to do is crouch down and really look at the world.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Translation earbuds premise'},{fnEn:'Fun animal and plant dialogues—light and humorous'},{fnEn:'Hearing nature\'s cries for help—reversal'},{fnEn:'Taking off the earbuds and taking action'},{fnEn:'Earbuds banned + deeper insight'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Sweet-then-bitter emotional rhythm',detailEn:'First the funny dialogues make you laugh, then the sad ones make you think'},{pointEn:'Environmental theme naturally woven in',detailEn:'No preaching—conveyed through the animals\' and plants\' "voices"'},{pointEn:'Humorous ending with depth',detailEn:'Pets talking behind owners\' backs—humor that hints "hearing too much has drawbacks too"'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Left right left! Cookie crumbs spotted on the left—all units, move out!',whyEn:'The ants\' "military language" is irresistibly funny'},{textEn:'My roots are sealed under concrete—I can barely breathe',whyEn:'The transition from fun to heartbreak—the old tree\'s words are the most moving'},{textEn:'Just crouch down and really look at the world',whyEn:'No technology needed, just attention—the deepest possible conclusion'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Time Camera',fullTextEn:'In a dusty corner of the attic, I found a strange camera. Its casing was old copper, and beside the lens was a small dial engraved with two arrows: "Past" and "Future."\n\nCuriously, I turned the dial to "Past" and snapped a photo through the window. The print came out—the same view outside, but the trees were taller and greener, the sky bluer, and a group of children in old-fashioned uniforms played jump rope in the schoolyard. A line of small text at the bottom read: April 12, 2005.\n\nOh my—this was this place twenty years ago!\n\nExcitedly, I turned the dial to "Future" and snapped another through the window. This print made me freeze—the trees outside were gone, replaced by rows of grey high-rises. The sky was a murky yellow. No children in the schoolyard, just a few masked adults hurrying past. The bottom read: April 12, 2045.\n\nI didn\'t want to believe it. I took several more shots, all showing the same thing—the future was grey.\n\nI put down the camera, ran downstairs, ran to the schoolyard. The sky right now wasn\'t as blue as twenty years ago, but the trees were still there, birds still sang, classmates played basketball. I took a deep breath—the air still smelled of grass.\n\n"There\'s still time," I told myself.\n\nI put the camera away and told no one. But from that day on, I started conserving water, sorting recyclables, and never wasting food. When classmates asked why I\'d suddenly changed, I\'d just smile and say: "Because I\'ve seen the future."\n\nEvery today is the past of some future. The choices we make today become tomorrow\'s photograph.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Discovering the mysterious camera'},{fnEn:'Photographing the past—beautiful'},{fnEn:'Photographing the future—bleak'},{fnEn:'Returning to the present—there\'s still time'},{fnEn:'Changing behavior + golden-line conclusion'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Past-present-future triple contrast',detailEn:'Three time points form a vivid contrast'},{pointEn:'From passive discovery to active change',detailEn:'Not just "seeing" but "doing"—action gives sci-fi real-world significance'},{pointEn:'Environmental message wrapped in sci-fi',detailEn:'Using sci-fi to package an environmental theme—powerful without preaching'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'The air still smelled of grass',whyEn:'Sensory description emphasizing "it\'s not too late yet"'},{textEn:'Because I\'ve seen the future',whyEn:'A one-line answer that\'s powerful and mysterious'},{textEn:'Every today is the past of some future',whyEn:'Golden-line ending—a clever play on time concepts'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic 7: km2020_comp_b "难忘的小学生活" ──
TOPICS['km2020_comp_b'] = {
  promptEn:'Six years of primary school life have flown by. Soon we\'ll bid farewell to our beautiful campus, to the teachers and classmates we\'ve spent every day with. These six years surely hold unforgettable people or events. Please write an essay titled "Unforgettable Primary School Life."',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'This is the quintessential graduation-season essay. The key: (1) don\'t write a chronological log—you can\'t cover all six years; (2) choose 1-2 most memorable moments and develop them deeply; (3) create a "farewell" emotional atmosphere; (4) the ending can express gratitude or look ahead.',
    pitfallsEn:['Year-by-year log—no focus','Piling up "unforgettable" without specific details—hollow','Only writing happy times without growth—lacks depth','Slogan-like ending—empty phrases like "I\'ll never forget"'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose 1-2 core moments and develop them deeply','Use specific people, dialogue, and scenes to recreate memories','Weave in reflections on growth, not just reminiscence','The ending should have lingering resonance—finding appreciation in farewell']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'Unforgettable Primary School Life',fullTextEn:'The last winter of sixth grade, the blackboard at the back of the classroom changed its theme—"Goodbye, My Primary School."\n\nI stood before the board, chalk in hand, suddenly unsure what to write. Six years of things—too many to sort out which to remember first.\n\nFinally I wrote one sentence: "Thank you for that rainstorm in third grade."\n\nIt was autumn of third grade, a downpour without warning. After school, only Xiao Yu and I were left in the classroom—neither of us had brought umbrellas. We waited nearly an hour, but the rain didn\'t let up at all. Xiao Yu rummaged through his bag and pulled out a crumpled plastic bag: "How about... we use this?"\n\nWe tore the bag open, tied it to our heads with backpack straps, and charged into the rain. We fell twice on the way, shoes completely flooded, pant legs splattered with mud. But we were laughing the entire time. At the entrance to our neighborhood, he said something I\'ve remembered for three years: "From now on when it rains, let\'s just run together. Two people getting rained on get less wet than one."\n\nThat makes zero logical sense. But strangely, I really did feel like two people getting rained on was less wet than one.\n\nOver the next three years, Xiao Yu and I were practically inseparable. We teamed up for the science competition (blew up a lightbulb but still placed third), got punished standing in the hallway together (for passing notes in math class discussing weekend plans), and made a promise under the banyan tree by the field: "Let\'s go to the same middle school."\n\nNow I stood at the board, and Xiao Yu walked over, glanced at what I\'d written, and smiled: "You still remember?"\n\n"Of course."\n\nHe said nothing more. He picked up another piece of chalk and beside my sentence drew a wobbly umbrella and two stick figures running in the rain.\n\nThe setting sun happened to shine through the window, gilding the chalk drawing on the board in gold.\n\nUnforgettable primary school life—you don\'t need to fill an entire blackboard. One rainstorm, one person, is enough.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Writing on the board in sixth grade—triggers a memory'},{fnEn:'Third grade rainstorm—the core event'},{fnEn:'Three years of friendship (overview)'},{fnEn:'Friendship echoed at the blackboard'},{fnEn:'One-sentence thesis'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'One event for six years',detailEn:'Not greedy—just one rainstorm and one friendship, focused and deep'},{pointEn:'Dialogue as golden line',detailEn:'"Two people getting rained on get less wet than one"—illogical but emotionally perfect'},{pointEn:'Objects thread the narrative',detailEn:'Blackboard → rain → drawing on the board—objects consistently tie the essay together'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Two people getting rained on get less wet than one',whyEn:'Childlike logic that beats any philosophical truth'},{textEn:'Blew up a lightbulb but still placed third',whyEn:'Humorous parenthetical aside adds flavor of real life'},{textEn:'One rainstorm, one person, is enough',whyEn:'Minimalist ending—less is more'}]},
    {titleEn:'Unforgettable Primary School Life',fullTextEn:'The afternoon after the graduation photo was taken, I sat alone in the empty classroom and discovered a line carved into the corner of my desk—"Zhang Xiaomin was here, September 1, 2019."\n\nThat\'s what I\'d secretly carved on my first day of school. Seven-year-old me thought that was cool. Now twelve-year-old me thinks it\'s silly. But I crouched down and looked at those wobbly little characters, shaking my head with a smile.\n\nSix years passed right at this desk.\n\nI remember learning to write in first grade, unable to hold the pen correctly no matter what. The teacher held my hand and wrote one character stroke by stroke—the character "person" (人). She said: "First learn to be a person, then learn to write." I didn\'t understand then. Now I do.\n\nI remember fighting with my deskmate over an eraser in third grade, so angry I skipped lunch. That afternoon he handed me a bag of crackers: "Are you hungry?" I forgave him immediately. The eraser vanished long ago, but the taste of those crackers I still remember—seaweed flavor.\n\nI remember the relay race at the fifth-grade sports day. I ran the last leg. The baton nearly slipped during the handoff, and the whole class\'s hearts leaped to their throats. I sprinted desperately. Crossing the finish line, my knee was scraped raw, but ringing in my ears was the loudest cheering I\'d ever heard.\n\nThe classroom door was pushed open. The homeroom teacher walked in, glanced at the empty seats, and said: "Still not leaving?"\n\n"In a minute." I stood up and took one last look at the carved corner of the desk.\n\nSix years of primary school taught me a lot—writing, math, running, making friends. But the most important thing it taught me is: some things feel ordinary when you have them. Only after losing them do you discover their name is youth.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Discovering the six-year-old carving—a sense of time'},{fnEn:'First grade: learning to write'},{fnEn:'Third grade: the eraser and the crackers'},{fnEn:'Fifth grade: the relay race'},{fnEn:'Leaving the classroom + reflection'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Object as anchor',detailEn:'The desk carving is the key that unlocks memory—this detail makes the whole essay real'},{pointEn:'Three-part memories',detailEn:'One scene each from first/third/fifth grade—wide time span without being scattered'},{pointEn:'Grounded insight',detailEn:'"Feels ordinary when you have it, precious when it\'s gone"—plain but accurate'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'First learn to be a person, then learn to write',whyEn:'The teacher\'s words are simple yet profound—the essay\'s spiritual core'},{textEn:'The eraser vanished long ago, but the taste of those crackers I still remember',whyEn:'Brilliant contrast—the quarrel is forgotten, the kindness remembered'},{textEn:'Some things feel ordinary when you have them; only after losing them do you discover their name is youth',whyEn:'A closing golden line that perfectly captures graduation-season emotions'}]},
    {titleEn:'Unforgettable Primary School Life',fullTextEn:'The most unforgettable thing about my primary school life isn\'t any single day—it\'s 4:30 every afternoon.\n\n4:30 is when the dismissal bell rings. But for me, it means something else—it\'s the time Mom stands at the school gate waiting for me.\n\nIn first grade, she stood at the very front, on tiptoe craning her neck to find me. Spotting me from afar, she\'d wave vigorously. I felt so happy.\n\nIn third grade, she stood a bit farther back, waiting quietly. I\'d spot her from a distance and run over. She\'d take my backpack and ask: "Was today fun?" I\'d say yes, and she\'d smile.\n\nIn fifth grade, I started feeling "embarrassed" to be picked up by Mom. All my classmates walked alone, and I was the only one still being met. I told her: "Don\'t come anymore. I\'ll walk myself." She paused for a moment, then said "Okay."\n\nThe next day at 4:30, I walked out the gate alone. When I instinctively looked up—she wasn\'t there. At the neighborhood entrance, I realized she had been following behind the whole time, just staying far back, not appearing at the gate.\n\nI pretended not to notice.\n\nIn sixth grade, Mom truly stopped coming. She got busy with work; sometimes I\'d arrive home before her. Opening the door alone, setting down my bag, the quiet living room held nothing but the hum of the refrigerator. That\'s when I realized—that figure at the school gate at 4:30 wasn\'t a restriction. It was safety.\n\nTomorrow is graduation. Just now Mom texted: "What time is the ceremony tomorrow? I\'ll come pick you up."\n\nI replied with three characters: "Four thirty."\n\nThe most unforgettable part of primary school life is the person who waited for me. Though it took six years to learn to appreciate it—at least it\'s not too late.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'4:30—a unique time motif'},{fnEn:'First grade: close-up waiting—happy'},{fnEn:'Third grade: slightly farther—warm'},{fnEn:'Fifth grade: refusal + distant following—turning point'},{fnEn:'Sixth grade: she stops coming—loss'},{fnEn:'"Four thirty" echo + reflection'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Timeline narration',detailEn:'First/third/fifth/sixth grade—distance changes chart emotional changes'},{pointEn:'Distance IS emotion',detailEn:'From the very front → farther back → following from afar → not coming—physical distance maps emotional distance'},{pointEn:'Opening-closing "4:30" echo',detailEn:'Opens as a time concept, closes as an emotional declaration'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'She wasn\'t there',whyEn:'A three-word sentence—the sense of loss hits instantly'},{textEn:'I pretended not to notice',whyEn:'Five words capture all a child\'s stubbornness and a mother\'s restraint'},{textEn:'I replied with three characters: "Four thirty"',whyEn:'Doesn\'t say "I love you" or "thank you"—just a time. Everything is unspoken'}]},
    {titleEn:'Unforgettable Primary School Life',fullTextEn:'On graduation day, I found a forgotten diary in my desk drawer. The first page read in wobbly handwriting: Sept 1 Sunny Today is the first day of school My teacher is pretty My deskmate is a boy He has freckles on his nose\n\nI burst out laughing. The handwriting was terrible back then, no punctuation either, but it felt as real as if freshly transported from 2018.\n\nFlipping to the middle—\n\nThird grade: Today I was chosen as group leader! Mom says she\'ll buy me ice cream to celebrate!\n\nFourth grade: I got third in the class on finals, but I\'m not that happy because my goal was first. Teacher said: Progress matters more than ranking. I think she\'s right.\n\nFifth grade: Had a fight with Xiao Li today. I think she\'s being unreasonable. But thinking about it tonight, I think I was the one who grabbed her paintbrush first. Need to apologize tomorrow.\n\nThe last page was blank. The date said "Sixth grade," with nothing written beneath—probably too busy and forgot.\n\nI picked up a pen and wrote today\'s diary on the final page:\n\nJune 30 Sunny Today is the graduation ceremony I wore a new dress Stood in the schoolyard and sang the graduation song Halfway through the teacher cried I didn\'t cry But after walking out the school gate I cried secretly Because I suddenly realized I\'ve walked through that gate for six years After walking out today I\'ll never walk back in as a student again\n\nClosing the diary, I drew a smiley face on the cover, then packed it into my bag.\n\nSome things you think you\'ll forget. But just open a page, and all the winds come blowing back.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'Discovering the diary—memory\'s medium'},{fnEn:'Diary excerpts from different grades—growth trajectory'},{fnEn:'The blank page—a turning point'},{fnEn:'Writing the final diary entry—the essay\'s climax'},{fnEn:'Closing the diary + thesis'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Diary as narrative thread',detailEn:'Using the diary to string together six years—both reminiscence and evidence of growth'},{pointEn:'Mimicking different ages\' voices',detailEn:'First grader\'s naivete → fourth and fifth grader\'s maturity—language style evolves with age'},{pointEn:'The blank page is the art of negative space',detailEn:'Nothing written for sixth grade—leaves imagination for the reader'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Sept 1 Sunny Today is the first day of school My teacher is pretty My deskmate is a boy He has freckles on his nose',whyEn:'Perfectly mimics a first-grader\'s diary—innocent to the point of adorable'},{textEn:'I\'ve walked through that gate for six years After walking out today I\'ll never walk back in as a student',whyEn:'This line in the final diary entry strikes straight to the heart'},{textEn:'Just open a page, and all the winds come blowing back',whyEn:'A poetic metaphor—memory is like wind, beautiful and formless'}]},
    {titleEn:'Unforgettable Primary School Life',fullTextEn:'If I had to choose one thing to represent my six years of primary school, I\'d choose the osmanthus tree by the school gate.\n\nWhen I started first grade, the osmanthus tree was exactly my height. I stood beside it for my first school photo—bangs cut straight across, one front tooth missing, grinning so hard my eyes became slits.\n\nIn second-grade autumn, the osmanthus bloomed, scenting the entire campus with sweetness. My classmates and I gathered fallen blossoms under the tree, pressing them between textbook pages as bookmarks. Opening a textbook to that fragrance made even math problems seem lovable.\n\nIn third grade, I fell under that tree and scraped my knee. The school nurse dabbing medicine said: "It\'s nothing—you\'ll be fine in a couple days. People are like trees—bumps and scrapes make you grow sturdier."\n\nIn fourth grade, we rehearsed choir under the osmanthus tree. We sang "Let Us Swing the Oars," forty-some students standing in the shade, sunlight filtering through the leaves and scattering flecks of gold across us all. That was the first time I felt choir sounds better than a solo—because forty voices together are so much warmer than one.\n\nIn fifth grade, I had a falling out with my best friend under the tree. I circled it for many laps, walking and thinking "whose fault is it really." On the eighth lap, she came out from the classroom. We said nothing. She handed me half a chocolate bar. We were good again.\n\nIn sixth grade, osmanthus season came again. I went and measured the tree—it now towered well above me. I touched its trunk, as if telling a six-year companion: look—we both grew up.\n\nThe graduation photo was taken under this tree. Same spot as six years ago. What\'s different: the front tooth grew back, the bangs are cut at an angle, and the eyes still become slits when I smile.\n\nGoodbye, osmanthus tree. Goodbye, my primary school.',
    sections:[{fnEn:'The osmanthus tree represents six years—core image'},{fnEn:'First grade: the photo—starting point'},{fnEn:'Second grade: gathering blossoms—joy'},{fnEn:'Third/fourth/fifth grade: falling down/choir/making up—growth'},{fnEn:'Sixth grade: the tree outgrew me—time passing'},{fnEn:'Graduation photo echoes enrollment photo + farewell'}],
    principles:[{pointEn:'Object threads six years together',detailEn:'The osmanthus tree is the core image—every year\'s story revolves around it'},{pointEn:'Tree mirrors life',detailEn:'The tree\'s growth mirrors personal growth—a natural, profound metaphor'},{pointEn:'Photos echo at beginning and end',detailEn:'Enrollment photo → graduation photo, same location, different person—time\'s best footnote'}],
    highlights:[{textEn:'Even math problems seemed lovable',whyEn:'A childlike exaggeration capturing the magic of osmanthus fragrance'},{textEn:'Sunlight filtering through leaves, scattering flecks of gold',whyEn:'Superb imagery—intensely visual'},{textEn:'Front tooth grew back, bangs cut at an angle, eyes still become slits when I smile',whyEn:'Concrete appearance changes are the most intuitive proof of growing up'}]}
  ]
};
// ── Topic: zt2021_comp_a "未来的家乡" ──
TOPICS['zt2021_comp_a'] = {
  promptEn:'Write an essay titled "My Hometown in the Future." Describe the changes in your hometown using reasonable imagination and smooth sentences.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'A hybrid "imagination + scenery" topic. Key points: (1) base imagination on your hometown\'s actual conditions; (2) be specific about changes—don\'t just say "it got better," describe how; (3) include both material changes (environment, buildings, transportation) and spiritual changes (people\'s lifestyles); (4) contrast present vs. future.',
    pitfallsEn:['Imagination too wild and unrealistic','Only writing about material things, not people—a cold future city','Jumping around without a main thread','Forgetting to express feelings about the hometown'],
    keyPointsEn:['Pick 2-3 specific dimensions of change and develop them deeply','Base imagination on solving real current problems','Include human activities to add warmth','End with "my" feelings and expectations']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'My Hometown in the Future',
     fullTextEn:'I always imagine what my hometown Zhaotong will look like twenty years from now.\n\nThe morning begins at 6:30. The alarm is the sound of birds—real ones, because the city has restored the wetlands on the east side, and white egrets have returned. I open the window, and the air carries a faint grassy scent, completely unlike the coal ash smell I remember.\n\nThe old stinky ditch by the school gate has become a clear creek with small fish darting about. The embankment is lined with osmanthus trees donated by residents. Every autumn, the whole street smells sweet.\n\nGrandpa no longer takes the bumpy bus into the city. The high-speed rail station is twenty minutes from home, and there are air buses gliding silently on magnetic tracks between districts. But Grandpa still prefers walking because "legs that don\'t walk will rust."\n\nThe school looks the same outside but completely different inside—smart blackboards, holographic globes. But some things haven\'t changed: the playground still has kids jumping rope, and the flagpole still flies the five-star red flag.\n\nI stand on the bridge and look toward Wumeng Mountain in the distance, the sunset painting the snow peaks orange-gold—this hasn\'t changed. Maybe the best kind of future is this: technology makes life more convenient, but the human warmth hasn\'t diminished one bit.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Morning in the future—scene introduction'},{fnEn:'Environmental change—stinky ditch → clear creek'},{fnEn:'Transportation change—bus → high-speed rail + air bus'},{fnEn:'Education change—preserving what hasn\'t changed'},{fnEn:'Wumeng Mountain sunset—using constancy to highlight change'},{fnEn:'Balance of technology + human warmth'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Dialectic of change and constancy',detailEn:'Each "change" is paired with an "unchanged" element—playground jump rope, grandpa walking—adding philosophical depth'},{pointEn:'Contrast enhances authenticity',detailEn:'Present problems (stinky ditch, coal ash) vs. future solutions make the imagination more grounded'},{pointEn:'Local character',detailEn:'Wumeng Mountain, egrets, osmanthus—specific Yunnan details make this feel real, not generic'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Mosquitoes so thick they could carry a person away',whyEn:'Humorous hyperbole that vividly captures current conditions'},{textEn:'The playground still has kids jumping rope',whyEn:'Among all the high-tech changes, this unchanged detail is deeply moving'},{textEn:'Technology makes life more convenient, but the human warmth hasn\'t diminished one bit',whyEn:'The thesis statement—concise and powerful'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Hometown in the Future',
     fullTextEn:'The self-driving car pulled into Mengzi at sunset. I hadn\'t been home in fifteen years.\n\nThe roads were the first shock—no more potholes, but smooth solar panels that glowed faintly at night. On both sides, buildings had green walls covered in plants, filtering the air naturally. The old coal plant had become an eco-park.\n\nGrandpa was waiting at the village entrance. Behind him, a drone was planting rice seedlings in the paddy field. "This thing is more capable than me," he chuckled, but his eyes sparkled like a child\'s. The young people were coming back—because remote work and smart agriculture meant the village could prosper too.\n\nBut not everything had changed. Grandpa insisted on keeping one plot of old rice paddy, farming it by hand. "Roots can\'t be cut," he said. The village still spoke Yunnan dialect, greeting each other warmly.\n\nStanding at the village edge, I realized: the best development isn\'t demolishing the past and starting over—it\'s growing new shoots from old roots.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Returning home—perspective of fifteen years away'},{fnEn:'Roads and green technology'},{fnEn:'Drone farming—grandpa\'s transformation'},{fnEn:'People returning—spiritual change'},{fnEn:'Preserving the old paddy—roots can\'t be cut'},{fnEn:'Growing new shoots from old roots'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Homecoming perspective',detailEn:'Fifteen years away creates natural contrast between past and present'},{pointEn:'Material + spiritual dual change',detailEn:'Technology changes are paired with people\'s return and renewed community spirit'},{pointEn:'"Roots can\'t be cut" as thesis',detailEn:'Grandpa\'s old paddy field symbolizes cultural preservation amid modernization'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Greeting warmly in Yunnan dialect',whyEn:'Dialect represents cultural identity—language persists even as everything else changes'},{textEn:'This thing is more capable than me',whyEn:'Grandpa\'s humorous acceptance of technology, showing generational adaptability'},{textEn:'Not demolishing the past and starting over, but growing new shoots from old roots',whyEn:'The core metaphor—elegant and profound'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Hometown in the Future',
     fullTextEn:'My hometown is a small town that most people can\'t find on a map. But in my imagination, twenty years from now it will be the happiest place I know.\n\nMorning: I walk through the organic farm. Tomatoes are red as jewels, cucumbers green as jade. No pesticides—intelligent sensors manage everything. The market has moved online, but the old auntie at the corner still insists on selling her pickled vegetables in person.\n\nAfternoon: I visit the Memory Hall—a museum of our town\'s history. The "Dialect Wall" plays recordings of grandparents telling stories. "We can\'t let these voices disappear," the curator says.\n\nEvening: The old mountain roads have become scenic walkways with solar lights. The reservoir powers the whole town. But the best part? Family dinner. Everyone sits around, eating hotpot, just like always.\n\nMy future hometown doesn\'t need to be glamorous. It just needs to let every person live with dignity and with a smile.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Hometown introduction—a small remote town'},{fnEn:'Transition sentence'},{fnEn:'Environmental and food changes'},{fnEn:'Memory Hall—cultural preservation'},{fnEn:'Mountain roads → scenic walkways + reservoir'},{fnEn:'Family dinner—human warmth unchanged'},{fnEn:'What makes a good future'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Single-day timeline',detailEn:'Morning → afternoon → evening structures the imagination naturally'},{pointEn:'Dialect Wall and Memory Hall',detailEn:'A creative cultural preservation concept—the most original element'},{pointEn:'Humble vision of happiness',detailEn:'Not about grandeur but dignity and smiles—a mature, grounded perspective'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Tomatoes red as jewels, cucumbers green as jade',whyEn:'Simple but vivid metaphors that make the scene tangible'},{textEn:'We can\'t let these voices disappear',whyEn:'A powerful statement about cultural heritage preservation'},{textEn:'Doesn\'t need to be glamorous, just needs every person to live with dignity and a smile',whyEn:'A remarkably mature thesis for a primary school student'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Hometown in the Future',
     fullTextEn:'I received a mysterious email: "Congratulations! Your hometown has won the Global Most Livable Small Town Award. Please attend the ceremony."\n\nThe green-energy train pulled into a station that looked like a small hill—covered entirely in plants. The car ran on hydrogen, leaving only water vapor. The river I remembered as murky now ran crystal clear, with children splashing in it.\n\nThe biggest change: young people had come back. The coffee shop owner used to work in Shanghai; the drone pilot used to code in Shenzhen. They came home because home was finally worth staying for.\n\nAt the ceremony, the trophy was made of local clay. The inscription read: "To a town that chose to grow without sacrificing its soul." I held the trophy, feeling the rough warmth of the clay.\n\nDevelopment isn\'t an excuse to sacrifice the environment. Home isn\'t a place you have to escape. It just needs to become—a place people want to come back to.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Email introduction—award ceremony suspense'},{fnEn:'Green station + eco-friendly car'},{fnEn:'River + young people returning'},{fnEn:'Clay trophy + award inscription'},{fnEn:'"No need to escape" realization'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Award ceremony as framework',detailEn:'Creative narrative structure that naturally showcases the changes'},{pointEn:'Clay trophy is the finishing touch',detailEn:'A trophy made of local earth—symbolizing that true value comes from roots'},{pointEn:'Young people returning',detailEn:'The most meaningful change is people choosing to stay/return'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'From a distance it looked like a small hill',whyEn:'The plant-covered station embodies harmony between technology and nature'},{textEn:'Development isn\'t an excuse to sacrifice the environment; home isn\'t a place you have to escape',whyEn:'A powerful double statement that serves as the essay\'s thesis'},{textEn:'It just needs to become—a place people want to come back to',whyEn:'Simple yet profound conclusion'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Hometown in the Future',
     fullTextEn:'My hometown has mountains I\'ve climbed, rivers I\'ve waded, peaches I\'ve stolen, and roads where dogs chased me. I don\'t want to turn it into a sci-fi movie. I just want a few simple things.\n\nI hope the road has lights. When Dad drives home from work at night, the road won\'t be pitch dark anymore. Solar-powered streetlights, one every fifty meters—that would be enough.\n\nI hope there\'s a clinic with a kind doctor who speaks our dialect, so Grandma won\'t have to ride three hours to the city hospital for a checkup.\n\nI hope there\'s a library—not a huge one, just two rooms with picture books, novels, and encyclopedias. So kids like me don\'t have to rely solely on textbooks.\n\nI hope Mom and Dad don\'t have to work far away anymore. If the town has jobs, we can eat dinner together every night.\n\nI hope the mountains stay green and the river stays clear. Don\'t cut down the old banyan tree at the village entrance—kids still climb it.\n\nMy hometown doesn\'t need flying cars or robot servants. It just needs a lit road, a kind doctor, a small library, and parents who come home for dinner.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Honest hometown introduction + anti-sci-fi stance'},{fnEn:'Roads and lights—infrastructure'},{fnEn:'Clinic—healthcare'},{fnEn:'Library—education'},{fnEn:'Parents don\'t need to work far away—family reunion'},{fnEn:'Preserving nature—environmental protection'},{fnEn:'A humble wish list'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Anti-sci-fi humble imagination',detailEn:'Deliberately avoids grand technology—each wish is small but deeply meaningful'},{pointEn:'Parallel "I hope" structure',detailEn:'Repetitive structure builds emotional momentum'},{pointEn:'Authentic rural perspective',detailEn:'Written from a child who truly lives in a rural area—raw and genuine'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Has mountains I\'ve climbed, rivers I\'ve waded, peaches I\'ve stolen, and roads where dogs chased me',whyEn:'Four vivid childhood images in one sentence—immediately establishes authenticity'},{textEn:'A clinic with a kind doctor who speaks our dialect',whyEn:'Incredibly specific and touching—this is a real need, not an imagined one'},{textEn:'Doesn\'t need flying cars... just a lit road',whyEn:'The contrast between sci-fi expectations and humble reality is devastating'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: zt2021_comp_b "生活里的别样课堂" ──
TOPICS['zt2021_comp_b'] = {
  promptEn:'Write an essay titled "A Different Kind of Classroom in Life." At least 500 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'The key words are "different" and "classroom." "Classroom" isn\'t limited to school lessons—it encompasses all learning experiences in life. "Different" emphasizes uniqueness compared to regular classrooms, requiring both distinctiveness and profound insight.',
    pitfallsEn:['Only writing about school classes without the "different" element','Listing multiple events without depth','Having events but no reflective insight'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose one educationally meaningful life experience','Highlight what makes this "classroom" special','Extract a life lesson from the experience']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'A Different Kind of Classroom in Life',
     fullTextEn:'The most memorable classroom of my life wasn\'t in school—it was at the morning market.\n\nLast summer, Mom handed me fifty yuan and said: "Go buy groceries for lunch. Tomatoes, eggs, and tofu." She added with a mysterious smile: "Pay attention to everything."\n\nThe air was thick with fish smell and the fresh scent of vegetables. I was excited yet nervous. First attempt: the tomatoes I picked were big and red but turned out to be mealy and tasteless. Second attempt: I bought eggs without checking—two were cracked. Third attempt: the tofu lady shortchanged me by two yuan, and I was too shy to say anything.\n\nWhen I got home, Mom examined my haul and said: "Tomatoes—smell the stem, fragrant ones are ripe. Eggs—hold them up to the light, cloudy ones are bad. And always count your change." Then she said something I\'ll never forget: "Being careful in everything you do—that\'s not just about buying groceries. That\'s about life."\n\nThat morning market taught me more than a whole semester of textbooks.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Scene entry, establishing the morning market setting'},{fnEn:'Mom assigns the task, psychological description'},{fnEn:'Three shopping experiences, progressively learning'},{fnEn:'Mom\'s review, deriving the lesson about "carefulness"'},{fnEn:'Extending the insight, echoing the title'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Small things reveal big truths',detailEn:'Buying groceries becomes a life lesson—classic "small event, big meaning" approach'},{pointEn:'Dialogue drives plot',detailEn:'Mom\'s words propel the narrative and deliver the theme'},{pointEn:'Opening and closing echo',detailEn:'Market → life lesson → "more than a semester of textbooks" ties everything together'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Air thick with fish smell and fresh vegetable scent',whyEn:'Vivid sensory detail immediately transports the reader to the market'},{textEn:'Excited yet nervous',whyEn:'Four words perfectly capture a child\'s first independent errand'},{textEn:'Being careful isn\'t just about buying groceries—it\'s about life',whyEn:'The thesis, delivered naturally through Mom\'s dialogue'}]},
    {titleEn:'A Different Kind of Classroom in Life',
     fullTextEn:'Where is the most unique classroom? For me, it\'s Grandma\'s kitchen.\n\nLast Spring Festival, Grandma decided to teach me her famous sour fish soup. Step one: filleting. The fish slices under my hands were thick and uneven, "like they\'d been gnawed on." Grandma\'s were paper-thin and translucent. Step two: marinating with just the right amount of sour bamboo shoots. "Too much and it\'s sour, too little and it\'s bland. Cooking is like being a person—you have to find the right balance."\n\nStep three: the crucial part—adding the broth. Grandma let me control the fire. I turned it too high and the broth boiled over; too low and it wouldn\'t simmer. She calmly adjusted the flame and said: "See? Everything has its own rhythm."\n\nAt the New Year dinner, everyone praised the soup. Grandma smiled so wide that every wrinkle on her face seemed to unfold. I knew the soup was mostly her doing, but that classroom—that was all mine.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Rhetorical question introduction, establishing the "kitchen classroom"'},{fnEn:'Filleting → marinating → cooking, three-step progression'},{fnEn:'Warm scene at the New Year dinner'},{fnEn:'Extracting the lesson, elevating the theme'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Three-stage apprenticeship',detailEn:'Filleting → marinating → cooking naturally structures the narrative'},{pointEn:'Using objects to express philosophy',detailEn:'"Cooking is like being a person" draws a natural parallel'},{pointEn:'Warmth as conclusion',detailEn:'Grandma\'s smile wraps up the story with emotional warmth'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Cooking is like being a person—you have to find the right balance',whyEn:'Grandma\'s folk wisdom perfectly bridges cooking and life philosophy'},{textEn:'Fish slices like they\'d been gnawed on',whyEn:'Self-deprecating humor that makes the contrast vivid'},{textEn:'Grandma smiled so wide every wrinkle seemed to unfold',whyEn:'An exquisite image of pure joy—visual and emotional'}]},
    {titleEn:'A Different Kind of Classroom in Life',
     fullTextEn:'I used to think "toiling under the blazing sun" was just a line in a poem. Until last summer at Grandpa\'s cornfield.\n\nWe set out at dawn. The corn stalks were taller than me, and the leaf edges were sharp as little knives, leaving red scratches on my arms. Breaking off corn ears looked simple when Grandpa did it—twist, snap, toss into the basket. My first ear took a full minute; his took three seconds.\n\nBy mid-morning, sweat was pouring into my eyes. My back ached from bending. I wanted to quit, but looking at Grandpa\'s calloused, weathered hands moving so nimbly, I felt ashamed.\n\n"Grandpa, \'sweat dripping onto the soil\' isn\'t a poem line—it\'s a real-life taste," I said, wiping my face. He laughed: "Now you understand."\n\nThat day in the cornfield, I learned that every grain of rice comes from someone\'s sweat. That\'s a lesson no textbook can teach.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Opening with a poem, setting up the cornfield experience'},{fnEn:'Dawn departure, entering the corn field'},{fnEn:'Learning to harvest corn, contrasting with Grandpa\'s skill'},{fnEn:'Understanding the ancient poem through sweat'},{fnEn:'Summary and elevation, tying back to the title'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Experiential writing',detailEn:'The ancient poem\'s meaning becomes real through physical labor'},{pointEn:'Making a poem come alive',detailEn:'"Sweat dripping onto the soil" transforms from abstract to tangible'},{pointEn:'Contrast technique',detailEn:'The child\'s clumsiness vs. Grandpa\'s expertise highlights the learning process'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Leaf edges sharp as little knives',whyEn:'A specific sensory detail that city kids would never know'},{textEn:'"Sweat dripping onto the soil" isn\'t a poem—it\'s a real-life taste',whyEn:'The moment when textbook knowledge becomes lived experience'},{textEn:'Grandpa\'s calloused, weathered hands moving so nimbly',whyEn:'A vivid image that embodies decades of labor and skill'}]},
    {titleEn:'A Different Kind of Classroom in Life',
     fullTextEn:'Our class went hiking in the mountains last autumn. I was so excited about the scenery that I wandered off from the group—and suddenly realized I was lost.\n\nFear crept up like vines wrapping around me. The forest was dense, the paths all looked the same, and my phone had no signal. My first instinct was to run, but I forced myself to stop.\n\n"Calm down first, then act," I told myself—something Dad always said. I looked around and noticed trail markers on tree trunks. Blue arrow: main trail. I followed them, one by one, checking my direction against the sun.\n\nTwenty minutes later, I emerged at the gathering point. The teacher looked stern for a few seconds, then suddenly patted my shoulder: "Good job finding your way back."\n\nThat forest taught me: when you\'re lost—in the woods or in life—the first thing to do is stop panicking. Then look for signs. The way out is always there; you just need calm eyes to find it.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Suspenseful introduction, building anticipation'},{fnEn:'Separating from group → realizing I\'m lost → fear and psychology'},{fnEn:'Calming down → finding trail markers → following the path'},{fnEn:'Returning to the gathering point, teacher\'s response'},{fnEn:'Extracting the lesson, extending to life'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Psychological change as narrative thread',detailEn:'Excitement → fear → calm → confidence tracks emotional growth'},{pointEn:'Concrete problem-solving',detailEn:'Trail markers and sun direction make the survival element believable'},{pointEn:'Lesson extends beyond the incident',detailEn:'Getting lost in the forest becomes a metaphor for life\'s challenges'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Fear crept up like vines wrapping around me',whyEn:'A powerful simile that physically manifests the feeling of being lost'},{textEn:'Calm down first, then act',whyEn:'A simple but universally applicable life principle'},{textEn:'The teacher looked stern for a few seconds, then suddenly patted my shoulder',whyEn:'This brief moment captures the teacher\'s concern melting into pride'}]},
    {titleEn:'A Different Kind of Classroom in Life',
     fullTextEn:'The deepest knowledge hides in the most ordinary everyday life. My "different classroom" was at a street cobbler\'s stall.\n\nOne Saturday, my shoe sole came loose. Mom took me to old Mr. Chen by the school gate. He examined my shoe with one glance and said: "The sole isn\'t just loose—the stitching inside is broken too. The place most likely to break is always the connection point."\n\nI watched him work: prying off the old sole, cleaning the glue residue, applying new adhesive evenly, then pressing firmly for exactly thirty seconds. When restitching, he reinforced the heel area. "This spot bears the most weight. I\'ll add extra stitches for safety."\n\n"The place most likely to fail is the connection point." That phrase echoed in my mind. Isn\'t friendship like that? Isn\'t family? The connections between people need maintenance too.\n\nI walked home in my repaired shoes, feeling like I\'d had a philosophy lesson—from a cobbler who probably never went to college.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Character introduction, building curiosity'},{fnEn:'Observing shoe repair, dialogue unfolding'},{fnEn:'Shoe philosophy → life philosophy'},{fnEn:'Reinforcement detail + second layer of insight'},{fnEn:'Double takeaway—shoes and wisdom, tying back to the title'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'A person as a classroom',detailEn:'The cobbler becomes an unexpected philosopher'},{pointEn:'Professional wisdom',detailEn:'Shoe repair terminology naturally becomes life metaphor'},{pointEn:'Two-layer insight',detailEn:'First layer: connection points break first. Second layer: relationships need maintenance too'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'His secret was exposed by a single glance',whyEn:'Personifying the shoe\'s defect, making a mundane moment dramatic'},{textEn:'The place most likely to fail is always the connection point',whyEn:'A cobbler\'s occupational wisdom that doubles as life philosophy'},{textEn:'The deepest knowledge hides in the most ordinary everyday life',whyEn:'The essay\'s thesis—perfectly encapsulated'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: dq2021_comp_a "童年难忘的事" ──
TOPICS['dq2021_comp_a'] = {
  promptEn:'Is there an event from your childhood that you can\'t forget? Choose your own title and write a narrative essay of at least 450 words. Express genuine emotions with specific content.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'A highly open-ended narrative prompt. The core requirements are "personal experience" and "unforgettable." Choose one specific event and explain what made it unforgettable (moving/lesson/surprise/growth). Emotions must be authentic.',
    pitfallsEn:['Topic too broad and vague to write deeply','Listing events like a chronological log without focus','Only narrating without expressing feelings'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose one specific, deeply memorable small event','Describe key scenes in detail','Let insights flow naturally from the event']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'That Bowl of Ginger Soup',
     fullTextEn:'Of all childhood memories, the one that steams the warmest is a bowl of ginger soup.\n\nThat afternoon, dark clouds hung over the village like an upturned iron pot. I was caught in the downpour walking home from school, drenched to the bone by the time I stumbled through the door.\n\nGrandma\'s reaction was faster than the rain. She pulled off my wet clothes, wrapped me in a towel, and rushed to the kitchen. I heard the knife hitting the cutting board—she was slicing ginger with a speed that didn\'t match her age.\n\nThe soup arrived in minutes: ginger slices swimming in brown sugar water, steam curling up like gentle fingers. The first sip burned my tongue, the ginger\'s spiciness spreading through my body like a small fire. By the third sip, warmth reached my frozen toes.\n\nThat night, Grandma fell asleep in the chair beside my bed, her hand still resting on my forehead. By morning, my would-be cold had vanished.\n\nSpicy with a hidden sweetness, sweet with a hidden warmth—that\'s Grandma\'s ginger soup. That\'s Grandma\'s love.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Opening—establishing the core memory'},{fnEn:'Setting the scene—rainstorm + getting drenched'},{fnEn:'Grandma\'s urgency and care'},{fnEn:'Detailed description of the ginger soup and drinking it'},{fnEn:'The next morning\'s detail + emotional elevation'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Five senses engaged',detailEn:'Sound of the knife, sight of steam, taste of ginger—full sensory immersion'},{pointEn:'Contrast highlights warmth',detailEn:'Cold rain outside vs. warm soup inside creates emotional resonance'},{pointEn:'Ending ties it together',detailEn:'"Spicy with sweetness, sweet with warmth" echoes both the soup and the love'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Dark clouds like an upturned iron pot',whyEn:'A vivid rural metaphor—visual and foreboding'},{textEn:'Grandma fell asleep in the chair beside my bed',whyEn:'The understated devotion—she watched over me all night'},{textEn:'Spicy with a hidden sweetness, sweet with a hidden warmth',whyEn:'A layered description that works for both the soup and the love'}]},
    {titleEn:'My First Bike Ride',
     fullTextEn:'Among my childhood memories, learning to ride a bike shines like a medal of honor.\n\nDad held the back of the seat as I wobbled down the village road. I fell three times in the first ten minutes—knees scraped, palms stinging. "Maybe I should just walk forever," I muttered.\n\n"Again," Dad said simply. He held the seat and ran alongside me. Slowly, the wobbling lessened. I was concentrating so hard on the handlebars that I forgot to be scared.\n\nThen I looked back—and Dad was standing ten meters behind me, hands on his hips, grinning. He\'d let go without telling me.\n\n"How long have you not been holding on?!" I shouted, half angry, half amazed.\n\n"Since the big tree," he laughed.\n\nI\'d been riding on my own for fifty meters without knowing it. The moment I realized it, I nearly fell again—but this time, I kept my balance.\n\nThat evening, I rode circles around the village square, wind in my hair, feeling like I owned the world. Dad taught me something that day: believe you can keep your balance, and you actually can.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Metaphorical introduction—a medal of honor'},{fnEn:'Falling and Dad\'s guidance'},{fnEn:'Dad holds the seat → secretly lets go (classic scene)'},{fnEn:'Looking back to discover Dad already let go → self-balance'},{fnEn:'Joy of riding + life lesson'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Classic material, fresh writing',detailEn:'Everyone has this story but the "looking back" discovery moment is well-executed'},{pointEn:'Plot reversal',detailEn:'The surprise of riding alone creates a natural emotional peak'},{pointEn:'Measured insight',detailEn:'"Believe you can balance and you actually can"—not over-philosophizing'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Like a medal of honor in my memory',whyEn:'Elevates a simple childhood moment to something ceremonial'},{textEn:'Dad standing ten meters behind, hands on hips, grinning',whyEn:'A cinematic image of parental pride and gentle teaching'},{textEn:'Believe you can keep your balance, and you actually can',whyEn:'A truth about confidence that applies far beyond bicycles'}]},
    {titleEn:'Flying a Kite',
     fullTextEn:'The most unforgettable moment of my childhood was my fingers holding a kite string and feeling something alive tugging from the sky.\n\nThe kite was homemade by my cousin from bamboo strips and newspaper. "Store-bought ones fly, but handmade ones have a soul," he said.\n\nWe ran to the field behind the village. I held the kite while cousin sprinted with the string. Once, twice, three times—it kept crashing. On the fourth try, a gust caught it. The kite shot up as if grabbed by an invisible hand.\n\nCousin passed me the string. The pull was astonishing—like a living creature was up there, tugging at me. When the wind shifted, the kite dipped; I panicked and pulled, and it soared again. My palms went red from the friction, but I couldn\'t let go.\n\nWe flew it until sunset painted the sky orange. When we finally reeled it in, cousin said: "A kite without a string is just a plastic bag."\n\nI thought about that for a long time. Freedom needs a string. Connection needs a hand. That afternoon, a newspaper kite taught me philosophy.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Opening with the core sensation—feeling something alive'},{fnEn:'Kite\'s origin, cousin\'s words as foreshadowing'},{fnEn:'Launch → crisis → success, dynamic narrative'},{fnEn:'Holding the string—unique tactile experience'},{fnEn:'Cousin\'s golden quote + sensory memory to close'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Dynamic description',detailEn:'The launch sequence has cinematic energy—action verbs drive the narrative'},{pointEn:'Detailed touch sensation',detailEn:'The pull of the string, red palms—haptic details most writers overlook'},{pointEn:'Open-ended conclusion',detailEn:'"A kite without a string is just a plastic bag"—leaves the reader thinking'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Handmade ones have a soul',whyEn:'A philosophical statement about craftsmanship from a child\'s mouth'},{textEn:'Like a living creature was up there tugging at me',whyEn:'Transforms a simple activity into something magical'},{textEn:'A kite without a string is just a plastic bag',whyEn:'A devastatingly simple metaphor about freedom and connection'}]},
    {titleEn:'Catching Tadpoles',
     fullTextEn:'Not a trip to Disneyland, not a birthday party, not getting a new phone—the most unforgettable thing in my childhood was catching tadpoles.\n\nThe news spread through the village like wind: tadpoles had appeared in the rice paddy behind Old Wang\'s house. Within minutes, seven or eight kids materialized with buckets, bowls, and even a strainer.\n\nThe mud was soft and squishy—cool mud oozed between my toes. The tadpoles were tiny black commas darting everywhere. I scooped with my bowl—empty. Again—empty. Uncle Da\'s grandson taught me: "Don\'t chase them. Put your bowl down and wait."\n\nIt worked. Three tadpoles swam right into my bowl. The thrill was electric—I screamed so loud that everyone looked over.\n\nBy afternoon, we compared our catches: the most was twenty-three, the least was two (mine). But everyone was grinning.\n\nMom said I couldn\'t keep them. I protested, then relented. Pouring them back into the paddy, I felt a tiny sadness and a bigger relief.\n\nThat afternoon of tadpoles, laughter, and muddy toes—it was the kind of afternoon that cities can\'t manufacture.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Parallel negations + suspense, revealing the topic'},{fnEn:'Village kids assembling, props described'},{fnEn:'Observing tadpoles → catching technique → learning the method'},{fnEn:'Comparing catches—pure joy'},{fnEn:'Mom\'s verdict + releasing them—bittersweet'},{fnEn:'Past and present contrast, nostalgic ending'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Group portrait',detailEn:'Multiple kids create a bustling, communal atmosphere'},{pointEn:'Sensory immersion',detailEn:'Cool mud between toes, black commas darting—rich tactile and visual detail'},{pointEn:'Layered narrative',detailEn:'Learning → catching → competing → releasing—each layer adds depth'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'The news spread through the village like wind',whyEn:'Captures the electric excitement of rural childhood'},{textEn:'Cool mud oozed between my toes',whyEn:'A sensory detail so specific it triggers childhood memories in any reader'},{textEn:'That afternoon of tadpoles, laughter, and muddy toes',whyEn:'Three images that perfectly distill the essence of rural childhood joy'}]},
    {titleEn:'An Umbrella in the Storm',
     fullTextEn:'What is the warmest thing in the world? For me, it\'s a stranger\'s umbrella on a rainy day.\n\nThird grade. School let out. Rain hammered the ground like a thousand drums. One by one, classmates were collected by parents holding umbrellas. The crowd thinned until I was alone under the eaves, watching puddles grow.\n\nI\'d told Mom not to pick me up—"I\'m a big kid now." But I wasn\'t expecting a typhoon.\n\nA woman I\'d never met walked up. She wore a blue raincoat and held a yellow umbrella. "Where do you live, sweetie? I\'ll walk you partway."\n\nUnder her umbrella, the rain became background music instead of an enemy. My head was dry. My heart was warm. She walked me to the intersection and handed me the umbrella: "Keep it. Return it to anyone who needs it someday."\n\nI never saw her again. But I still have that yellow umbrella—a bit faded now. And when I see someone caught in the rain, I know what to do.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Rhetorical question, suspense upfront'},{fnEn:'Rainstorm + being alone → loneliness'},{fnEn:'Stranger appears + offers umbrella'},{fnEn:'Walking under the umbrella—feelings'},{fnEn:'The umbrella\'s afterlife + value elevation'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Environment mirrors emotion',detailEn:'The shrinking crowd and growing puddles externalize the child\'s isolation'},{pointEn:'Beauty in restraint',detailEn:'The stranger is barely described—her kindness speaks for itself'},{pointEn:'Object carries memory',detailEn:'The faded yellow umbrella becomes a tangible symbol of the experience'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Classmates collected one by one by umbrella-holding parents',whyEn:'The gradual emptying creates palpable loneliness'},{textEn:'My head was dry, my heart was warm',whyEn:'Parallel structure connecting physical and emotional states perfectly'},{textEn:'When someone\'s caught in the rain and you have an umbrella, hand it over',whyEn:'The stranger\'s philosophy of paying it forward—simple and powerful'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: dq2021_comp_b "我的___" (写人) ──
TOPICS['dq2021_comp_b'] = {
  promptEn:'Write an essay titled "My ___" (at least 450 words). Capture the person\'s distinctive traits and reveal their character through specific examples.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'A typical character-portrait semi-open essay. Fill in the blank with a family member, teacher, or friend. The key is "capturing distinctive traits" and "specific examples." Avoid vaguely listing multiple events—focus on one or two events to create a vivid character portrait.',
    pitfallsEn:['Listing too many events, leaving the character vague','Only describing appearance without inner qualities','Using hollow adjectives (kind, hardworking) without concrete examples'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose a person with distinctive traits','Use one or two typical events to portray them vividly','Use appearance + dialogue + actions + psychology for multi-angle portrayal']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'My Grandma',
     fullTextEn:'If I had to describe Grandma in one word, it would be "stubborn." Her silver hair is always combed neatly—not a strand out of place—stubborn even in that.\n\nGrandma\'s vegetable garden is her kingdom. Neighbors buy vegetables at the market, but she insists on growing her own. "Plants are alive—if you don\'t tend them, they die." Even when her knees ached, she\'d hobble out at dawn to water and weed.\n\nOne summer, a rainstorm flattened her tomato stakes. I woke at midnight to find her gone. Dad and I rushed out with flashlights—there she was, in the pouring rain, tying the tomato vines back up with rope. "Go inside!" Dad shouted. "If I don\'t save them now, they\'ll rot by morning!" she shouted back, rain streaming down her face.\n\nShe\'s stubborn about my homework too. At eighty, she can\'t read most of the questions, but she sits beside me every evening. "Are you done? Check it again," she\'d say. Every single night.\n\nGrandma\'s stubbornness is exasperating and heartwarming at the same time. She\'s stubborn about her garden because she respects life. She\'s stubborn about my homework because she respects the future. That kind of stubbornness—I hope I inherit it.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Appearance + one-word character summary: "stubborn"'},{fnEn:'Vegetable garden—persistence in growing'},{fnEn:'Rainstorm rescue—stubborn to the extreme'},{fnEn:'Homework supervision—stubbornness about education'},{fnEn:'Summarizing the meaning of "stubborn," emotional elevation'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Single-character framing',detailEn:'One word—"stubborn"—unifies all the examples'},{pointEn:'Multiple examples supporting one trait',detailEn:'Garden, rainstorm, homework—three scenarios, one consistent character'},{pointEn:'Dialogue shapes personality',detailEn:'Her words ("Plants are alive," "Check it again") reveal her character naturally'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Silver hair always combed neatly—not a strand out of place',whyEn:'Even grooming reflects her stubborn personality—clever detail'},{textEn:'Plants are alive—if you don\'t tend them, they die',whyEn:'Grandma\'s folk philosophy—simple words, deep respect for life'},{textEn:'Stubborn enough to make you both angry and heartwarmed',whyEn:'The paradox captures the complexity of love perfectly'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Deskmate',
     fullTextEn:'My deskmate Lin Hao is a walking contradiction: class clown on the outside, warrior on the inside.\n\nAfter mid-terms, everyone\'s faces looked "like frost-bitten eggplants." Lin Hao stood on his chair and announced: "Ladies and gentlemen, welcome to the \'How Badly Did We Fail\' show!" He proceeded to rank his own worst answers, making everyone laugh until they cried.\n\nBut here\'s the twist.\n\nAt the school sports day, Lin Hao signed up for the 800-meter run. "You?" we said. He\'s the shortest in class. At the starting gun, he fell behind immediately. By the second lap, his face was red as a tomato, every step looking like he was walking on cotton. We thought he\'d quit.\n\nHe didn\'t. He finished last—dead last—gasping like a broken bellows. But when he crossed the finish line, he raised his fist and shouted: "Last place... but I finished the whole thing!"\n\nThe class erupted. That was the loudest cheer of the entire sports day.\n\nThat\'s Lin Hao. He makes you laugh when you\'re down, and he shows you what perseverance looks like when you least expect it.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Appearance + dual-nature character summary'},{fnEn:'Post-exam comedy—the "class clown" side'},{fnEn:'Transition to reveal the second side'},{fnEn:'800-meter run—the perseverance side'},{fnEn:'Summarizing the dual personality + insight'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Dual-sided character',detailEn:'Clown + warrior creates a memorable, complex character'},{pointEn:'Dialogue reveals personality',detailEn:'"Last place... but I finished the whole thing!" defines him in one line'},{pointEn:'Contrast technique',detailEn:'Comedy scene → athletic struggle shows depth without telling'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Faces like frost-bitten eggplants',whyEn:'A hilarious simile that captures post-exam misery perfectly'},{textEn:'Every step like walking on cotton',whyEn:'A vivid physical description of exhaustion'},{textEn:'Last place... but I finished the whole thing',whyEn:'The thesis in one line—perseverance matters more than ranking'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Dad',
     fullTextEn:'My dad is the quietest person in our family. He doesn\'t say "I love you." He doesn\'t hug. For most of my childhood, I thought he just... didn\'t care.\n\nThen one day, I accidentally opened Dad\'s phone gallery. Every single photo was of me. Me eating breakfast. Me at the school play. Me sleeping on the couch with a book on my face. Hundreds of photos I never knew were taken.\n\nAnother time—my birthday. Dad was working construction in another city. He\'d promised to be home but wasn\'t. I was furious. At 9 PM, he walked through the door, dusty and exhausted, pulling from his bag a squashed cake box. "The bus was bumpy," he said, embarrassed.\n\nI opened the box. The cake was a disaster—frosting smeared, a strawberry crushed. But on the surviving half it read: "Happy Birthday Sweetheart."\n\nI hugged that ugly cake and laughed, then cried.\n\nDad\'s love is like his phone gallery—always there, always watching, just never shown. Now I know: some people don\'t say it. They carry a squashed cake across three hundred kilometers to say it.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Summary: "silent" trait, reverse introduction'},{fnEn:'Childhood belief that Dad didn\'t care'},{fnEn:'Phone gallery—the truth about his love'},{fnEn:'Squashed birthday cake—clumsy tenderness'},{fnEn:'Parallel summary, emotional elevation'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Build-up then reveal',detailEn:'Thinking he doesn\'t care → discovering the gallery → the cake revelation'},{pointEn:'Objects carry emotion',detailEn:'Phone photos and squashed cake are more eloquent than any words'},{pointEn:'Ending with parallels',detailEn:'"He carries a squashed cake across 300km"—says everything about silent love'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Every single photo was of me',whyEn:'A devastating revelation—the quietest love documented in hundreds of secret photos'},{textEn:'Dusty and exhausted, pulling from his bag a squashed cake box',whyEn:'A cinematic image of paternal devotion—imperfect but absolute'},{textEn:'I hugged that ugly cake and laughed, then cried',whyEn:'The emotional complexity in five words—joy and pain simultaneously'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Chinese Teacher',
     fullTextEn:'Mr. Wang is the "strangest" teacher in our school. Strange rule number one: writing class takes place in the garden. "Sit in the classroom and write about spring? That\'s like describing food you\'ve never tasted."\n\nHe took us to the school garden with notebooks. "Write what you see. But—no adjectives allowed."\n\n"No adjectives?!" we protested.\n\n"Anyone can write \'beautiful flowers.\' I want you to make me see the flowers without telling me they\'re beautiful."\n\nI stared at a rose bush for ten minutes, then wrote: "An ant climbed up the rose branch. When it reached the petal, it stopped, turned around, and climbed back down." Mr. Wang read it aloud and said: "See? That\'s real writing. You showed me something happening, not a string of fancy words."\n\nHe also had a rule for editing: "Every time you write \'Mom\'s love is like sunshine,\' ask yourself—what kind of sunshine exactly? Morning sun? Noon sun? Is it warm or blinding?" He made me rewrite three times until "Mom\'s love" became "Mom always leaves the last piece of fish for me."\n\nMr. Wang taught me that real writing isn\'t about decoration. Chinese isn\'t for exams—it\'s for living.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Summary: "strangest" teacher, sparking curiosity'},{fnEn:'Garden writing class—no adjectives allowed'},{fnEn:'Editing process—from abstract to concrete'},{fnEn:'Summary of Mr. Wang\'s teaching philosophy'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Teaching scene recreation',detailEn:'The reader experiences the lesson alongside the students'},{pointEn:'Meta-writing',detailEn:'An essay about writing technique that itself demonstrates those techniques'},{pointEn:'Details replace concepts',detailEn:'"Mom always leaves the last fish" replaces "Mom\'s love is sunshine"—showing vs. telling'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Chinese isn\'t for exams—it\'s for living',whyEn:'Mr. Wang\'s philosophy—this alone makes him unforgettable'},{textEn:'An ant climbed up the rose branch',whyEn:'The student\'s breakthrough moment—showing instead of telling'},{textEn:'What kind of sunshine exactly? Morning sun? Noon sun?',whyEn:'A masterclass in pushing students from cliché to specificity'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Mom',
     fullTextEn:'My mom\'s hands aren\'t remarkable—they\'re a little rough, nails kept short. But those hands have covered our entire house in sticky notes.\n\n"Bring your umbrella." "Drink water." "Math quiz today—you\'ve got this!" "Wear the thick jacket." Every morning, there\'s a new note on the breakfast table, my backpack, or the front door. I used to find them annoying.\n\nOne morning, there were no notes. Mom had left early for a business trip. I walked into a note-less kitchen, and it felt like entering a room with no lights on—everything was there, but something essential was missing.\n\nI forgot my umbrella that day. Got drenched. Forgot my math homework. Got scolded. At dinner, the house was too quiet.\n\nWhen Mom came home three days later, the first thing I said was: "Mom, don\'t forget to put up the notes tomorrow."\n\nShe laughed. I laughed too, but my eyes stung a little.\n\nNow I\'m in middle school, living at the dorm. Every Sunday when I unpack my bag, there\'s a note tucked inside: "Miss you. Eat well. ❤"\n\nThose small, colorful pieces of paper have covered the warmth of my entire childhood.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Summary: Mom\'s hands → sticky notes'},{fnEn:'Specific note contents displayed'},{fnEn:'The day without notes → contrasting their importance'},{fnEn:'Boarding school notes—love doesn\'t stop'},{fnEn:'Elevation—sticky notes as love letters'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Object-based narrative',detailEn:'Sticky notes are the throughline—creative and cohesive'},{pointEn:'From annoyance to appreciation',detailEn:'The emotional arc mirrors real parent-child dynamics'},{pointEn:'Metaphor as conclusion',detailEn:'"A room with no lights" = a life without Mom\'s small gestures'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Like entering a room with no lights on—everything was there but something was missing',whyEn:'A perfect metaphor for the absence of daily love'},{textEn:'Mom, don\'t forget to put up the notes tomorrow',whyEn:'A child asking for love in the most indirect, touching way'},{textEn:'Small colorful pieces of paper covered the warmth of my entire childhood',whyEn:'The final image—physical and emotional warmth fused'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: dh2023_comp "科幻故事" ──
TOPICS['dh2023_comp'] = {
  promptEn:'Use your imagination to write a science fiction story. You may write about future transportation, future schools, future homes, etc. At least 450 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'An open-ended sci-fi prompt with broad creative latitude. The key is choosing one specific sci-fi scenario and developing it fully rather than covering everything. Good sci-fi essays need: a concrete future setting + a complete story with characters + reflections on technology and humanity.',
    pitfallsEn:['Only listing inventions without a story','Imagination too unrealistic without internal logic','Lacking characters and plot'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose one specific sci-fi setting','Tell a complete story around that setting','Weave emotion or philosophical reflection into the sci-fi']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'The Talking Backpack',
     fullTextEn:'On my tenth birthday, Dad gave me a new backpack. It looked ordinary—navy blue, two pockets. Then it spoke.\n\n"Good morning! Current temperature: 14 degrees. Recommendation: wear the blue jacket. Also, your breakfast is getting cold."\n\nThis backpack was more nagging than Mom.\n\nIt had opinions about everything. When I walked slowly: "Your walking speed has decreased 23% from yesterday. Pick up the pace or you\'ll be late." During Chinese class, when I secretly asked it how to write a character, it projected the answer onto my desk—and then loudly announced "CORRECT!" so the teacher praised me. I was terrified and thrilled.\n\nThe biggest shock came during PE. We were running 800 meters—my worst nightmare. The backpack vibrated once for "slow down," twice for "speed up." I followed its rhythm: not too fast at the start, push in the middle, sprint at the end. I got my best time ever.\n\nThat night, I asked it: "Do you think your existence has meaning?"\n\nSilence. Then: "I help you eat breakfast on time. I help you write characters correctly. I help you run faster. Whether that counts as \'meaning\'... I suppose my existence probably does have meaning."\n\nI stared at the backpack for a long time. A machine was pondering its own existence. Maybe I should too.\n\nThe backpack is still annoying. But I\'ve stopped finding it quite so unbearable.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'AI backpack\'s entrance'},{fnEn:'The backpack\'s nagging—breakfast reminders'},{fnEn:'Secretly asking for characters—getting praise'},{fnEn:'800-meter pacing guidance → best time ever'},{fnEn:'Philosophical dialogue—meaning of existence'},{fnEn:'Attitude shift—not so unbearable anymore'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Personified AI',detailEn:'The backpack has personality—nagging, opinionated—making technology relatable'},{pointEn:'Everyday scenes made sci-fi',detailEn:'Breakfast, Chinese class, PE—familiar school life through a sci-fi lens'},{pointEn:'Unexpected philosophical depth',detailEn:'An AI pondering its own existence elevates a fun story to something thought-provoking'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'This backpack is more nagging than Mom',whyEn:'Immediately humanizes the AI through humorous comparison'},{textEn:'One vibration for slow down, two for speed up',whyEn:'Simple, elegant interface design—shows real thought about how AI assists'},{textEn:'My existence probably does have meaning',whyEn:'An AI\'s tentative self-reflection—simultaneously funny and profound'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Memory Bakery',
     fullTextEn:'There\'s a peculiar bakery on Maple Street that sells memories instead of bread.\n\nThe sign reads: "Eat a piece, experience someone else\'s memory." Each flavor corresponds to a different person\'s recollection. Vanilla: a grandmother teaching knitting. Chocolate: a soldier\'s homecoming. Strawberry: an old couple\'s first date.\n\nI chose strawberry. The moment I bit into it, the bakery dissolved.\n\nI was standing in a kitchen. An old woman was making dumplings, humming an old song. Sunlight slanted through the window, catching flour particles floating like tiny stars. A little girl—maybe five—sat on a stool, kicking her legs, trying to pinch dumplings that looked more like crumpled paper.\n\nThe old woman laughed, kissed the girl\'s flour-dusted cheek, and said: "Ugly ones taste the same."\n\nThree minutes. That\'s how long each memory lasts. When the bakery returned around me, my mouth still tasted like strawberries, but my eyes were wet.\n\nI asked the baker: "Can I turn my own memories into bread?"\n\nHe smiled: "Whose memory would you preserve?"\n\n"My grandma\'s kitchen," I said without hesitation.\n\nBecause memories fade. But maybe, just maybe, memories baked into bread can last forever.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Bakery setting and concept'},{fnEn:'Flavor menu → choosing strawberry'},{fnEn:'Entering the memory—grandma\'s kitchen'},{fnEn:'Three minutes end → tears'},{fnEn:'Wanting to preserve own memories + meaning'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Concept innovation',detailEn:'Eating bread to experience memories—a fresh, original sci-fi premise'},{pointEn:'Sensory immersion',detailEn:'Flour particles like stars, strawberry aftertaste—the senses blur between real and remembered'},{pointEn:'From others to self',detailEn:'Experiencing someone else\'s memory inspires preserving your own—beautiful emotional arc'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Eat a piece, experience someone else\'s memory',whyEn:'The premise in one line—immediately hooks the reader'},{textEn:'Mouth still tasted like strawberries, but my eyes were wet',whyEn:'Physical and emotional sensations perfectly fused'},{textEn:'Memories fade. But memories baked into bread might last forever',whyEn:'The thesis—technology as a vessel for preserving love'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Last Tree',
     fullTextEn:'In the year 2150, there was one tree left on Earth. Just one.\n\nIt stood in a glass dome in the center of the Global Nature Museum, guarded by twelve security robots. People lined up for hours just to look at it. Children pressed their faces against the glass: "Mom, is this what a \'tree\' is?"\n\nI was one of those children. I\'d never seen a tree outside of a textbook. The real thing was... more than I expected. The bark was rough and cracked. The leaves were green—but a green no screen could replicate. A kind of green that made my chest ache.\n\n"How do we breathe without trees?" I asked my teacher.\n\n"Oxygen factories," she said. "They produce enough for everyone."\n\nThe air was clean. But it always felt like something was missing.\n\nThat night, I searched "forest" online. Videos of wind through pine trees. Birds singing in canopies. A child swinging from a branch. I watched for three hours. Then I dreamed I was standing in a forest. I could hear leaves rustling. I could smell soil after rain. A leaf floated down, spinning like a tiny butterfly.\n\nI woke up crying. And I made a decision: when I grow up, I will make Earth grow trees again.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Setting—the last tree on Earth'},{fnEn:'Viewing the tree like viewing a fossil'},{fnEn:'How breathing works without trees → oxygen factories'},{fnEn:'Separated by glass + searching "forest" online'},{fnEn:'Dreaming of a forest—five senses alive'},{fnEn:'Resolution—to make Earth grow trees again'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Dystopian setting',detailEn:'One tree in a glass dome—a haunting image of environmental loss'},{pointEn:'Longing through glass',detailEn:'Being separated from nature by glass symbolizes humanity\'s self-imposed distance from the natural world'},{pointEn:'Dreams as the most powerful technology',detailEn:'No gadget can replicate what a forest dream delivers—the contrast indicts technology subtly'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'The air was clean, but it always felt like something was missing',whyEn:'Captures the emptiness of a technically sufficient but spiritually barren world'},{textEn:'A leaf floated down, spinning like a tiny butterfly',whyEn:'In the dream, this simple image carries immense emotional weight'},{textEn:'Maybe one day, people won\'t have to look at trees through glass anymore',whyEn:'Hope expressed as a negative—not what we\'ll gain, but what we\'ll stop losing'}]},
    {titleEn:'Time Delivery',
     fullTextEn:'The doorbell rang on a Tuesday afternoon. A delivery drone hovered outside with a small package.\n\n"Time Express Delivery. Sender: Li Jianguo. Sent: March 15, 2009. Delivery date: March 15, 2060."\n\nLi Jianguo was my grandfather. He passed away in 2012—three years after sending this package. A package he sent before I was even born.\n\nInside was a wristwatch—old-fashioned, with actual hands that ticked. And a letter.\n\n"Dear grandchild I haven\'t met: if this watch still works when it reaches you, please wear it. Time is the most expensive gift. I won\'t be there when you read this, but know that a man who never saw your face loved you before you existed."\n\nI put the watch on. It was still ticking. Fifty-one years of stored time, delivered in one afternoon.\n\nI sat at my desk, watching the second hand circle. In 2060, we have quantum teleportation, neural implants, and memory backup. But no technology can bring back a person.\n\nSome love doesn\'t need meeting. Some gifts don\'t need wrapping. And some people are in your life before your life begins.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Delivery arrival—suspense'},{fnEn:'Discovering it\'s from Grandpa'},{fnEn:'Grandpa\'s letter—the core'},{fnEn:'Watch detail + feelings'},{fnEn:'Technology\'s limits + love\'s eternity'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Sci-fi shell, emotional core',detailEn:'Time delivery is the sci-fi premise; the real story is love across time'},{pointEn:'Object-based narrative',detailEn:'The ticking watch carries fifty years of love in a tangible form'},{pointEn:'Love from beyond absence',detailEn:'A person who never met you loving you—transcends typical family narratives'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'A person who never saw your face loved you before you existed',whyEn:'One of the most powerful lines in all the essays—love predating existence'},{textEn:'Time is the most expensive gift',whyEn:'Grandpa\'s philosophy—simple words with immense weight'},{textEn:'Some love doesn\'t need meeting, some gifts don\'t need wrapping',whyEn:'A trinity of truths that redefine how we think about connection'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Dream Classroom',
     fullTextEn:'In 2080, the Ministry of Education launched the "Dream Learning System." Put on the headset, close your eyes, and you\'re transported into any era of history.\n\nToday\'s lesson: Li Bai\'s "Early Departure from Baidi City."\n\nThe headset flickered, and suddenly I was standing on a wooden boat. Mountains towered on both sides, their peaks lost in mist. Water roared beneath us. And there—at the bow—stood Li Bai himself.\n\nBut he wasn\'t the elegant poet from textbook illustrations. His robes were wrinkled, his hair messy. His eyes were red—he\'d been crying.\n\nThe AI teacher whispered in my ear: "He\'s just been pardoned from exile. He\'s heading home."\n\nLi Bai gripped the railing and spoke, not in the measured tones of a textbook recording, but in a voice cracking with emotion: "The apes cry on both banks ceaselessly—"\n\nHis voice wasn\'t beautiful. It was raw, and broken, and real. And I almost applauded.\n\nBack in the classroom, I understood something. "Early Departure from Baidi City" isn\'t a landscape poem. It\'s a poem about going home after the worst years of a man\'s life. The monkeys aren\'t background noise—they\'re the soundtrack to freedom.\n\nThe dream faded. But what lingers isn\'t technology—it\'s feelings. What truly moves the heart will always be emotion, never the machine that delivers it.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Dream learning system setting'},{fnEn:'Arriving in Tang Dynasty Chang\'an'},{fnEn:'AI Li Bai\'s performance'},{fnEn:'Li Bai\'s transformation—from elegant to raw'},{fnEn:'After class reflection + insight'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Educational sci-fi',detailEn:'Technology serves pedagogy—a refreshing sci-fi premise for a student writer'},{pointEn:'Bringing ancient poetry alive',detailEn:'Li Bai becomes a real person with red eyes, not a textbook figure'},{pointEn:'Technology serves emotion',detailEn:'The thesis: what moves the heart is always emotion, not the machine'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'His voice wasn\'t the measured tones of a textbook—it was cracking with emotion',whyEn:'Deconstructs the sanitized way we teach poetry—raw authenticity'},{textEn:'I almost applauded Li Bai',whyEn:'A student so moved by a 1300-year-old poem that they forget it\'s virtual—magic'},{textEn:'What truly moves the heart will always be emotion, not the machine',whyEn:'The definitive thesis—technology is a means, never the end'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: qj2023_comp_a "幸福的故事" ──
TOPICS['qj2023_comp_a'] = {
  promptEn:'Combining your own life experiences, tell a story about happiness. You may title it "My Happiness Story," "A Moment of Happiness," "Happiness Is All Around," etc.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'The key lies in understanding "what is happiness." The prompt emphasizes "hard work leads to happiness," but grand narratives aren\'t necessary. Best strategy: (1) discover happiness in everyday small things; (2) show a transformation from "not feeling happy" to "realizing happiness"; (3) convey the feeling of happiness through specific scenes, not abstract definitions.',
    pitfallsEn:['Defining happiness abstractly without concrete stories','Choosing an overly grand or fake-sounding topic','Only listing happy events without showing the realization process'],
    keyPointsEn:['Discover happiness in everyday life','Show the transformation in understanding happiness','Convey happiness through specific, vivid scenes']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'My Happiness Story',
     fullTextEn:'I used to think happiness was getting a hundred on a test or receiving a new toy. But that summer at Grandma\'s village, I found a different answer.\n\nEvery morning, Grandma would be in the kitchen by five. Steam rose from the pot as she made rice porridge, adding red dates one by one. "Three dates per bowl—too many and it\'s too sweet," she\'d say.\n\nI asked: "Grandma, are you happy?"\n\nShe thought about it: "Your grandpa plants vegetables; I cook. In the evening we sit in the yard and watch the stars. I guess that counts as happy."\n\nGrandpa was the same. He\'d spend a whole morning tending his garden, talking to his tomato plants: "Grow a little more, grow a little more." When he harvested them, he\'d arrange them like treasures.\n\nOne evening, I helped Grandpa carry baskets of vegetables home. Grandma had set the table—porridge, stir-fried greens, and the eggs I\'d helped collect that morning. We ate quietly. Frogs croaked outside.\n\n"Is this happiness?" I wondered. No test scores, no toys, no applause. Just porridge, vegetables, and stars.\n\nYes. I think this is.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Former definition of happiness—material'},{fnEn:'Grandma\'s daily routine—the porridge detail'},{fnEn:'Asking Grandma about happiness—simple answer'},{fnEn:'Grandpa\'s garden—talking to tomatoes'},{fnEn:'Evening dinner scene—quiet contentment'},{fnEn:'Redefining happiness—simplicity'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Redefinition arc',detailEn:'From material to spiritual—the child\'s understanding evolves through observation'},{pointEn:'Quiet scenes over dramatic events',detailEn:'Porridge, vegetables, stars—happiness is in stillness, not excitement'},{pointEn:'Question as structure',detailEn:'"Is this happiness?" frames both the beginning and the ending'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Three dates per bowl—too many and it\'s too sweet',whyEn:'Grandma\'s philosophy of moderation in one cooking instruction'},{textEn:'Talking to tomato plants: grow a little more',whyEn:'Pure, unhurried contentment expressed through a tender rural habit'},{textEn:'Just porridge, vegetables, and stars',whyEn:'The simplest possible definition of happiness—and the truest'}]},
    {titleEn:'A Moment of Happiness',
     fullTextEn:'Happiness wasn\'t a thing I found. It was a thing I kept missing—until I stopped looking.\n\nIt happened on a rainy Tuesday. Nothing special planned. After school, Mom picked me up. We stopped at a small noodle shop. The windows fogged up from the steam.\n\nWe ordered two bowls of beef noodles. Mom blew on each chopstick-load before passing it to me—a habit from when I was four that she never outgrew.\n\nI slurped my noodles and looked out the window. Rain streaked down the glass, making the streetlights look like melting gold. Mom hummed something under her breath. The shop owner\'s cat slept on the counter.\n\nAnd right there—wet shoes, foggy glasses, beef noodle broth on my chin—I felt it. Not fireworks happiness. Not birthday happiness. Just... warm happiness. Like putting on a dry shirt after getting caught in the rain.\n\nI didn\'t say anything. Mom didn\'t notice. The moment passed like water—smooth, quiet, invisible.\n\nBut I remember it. And that\'s enough.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Thesis: happiness comes when you stop looking'},{fnEn:'Ordinary setting—rainy Tuesday noodle shop'},{fnEn:'Mom\'s habitual caring gesture'},{fnEn:'Window rain + streetlights + cat—atmospheric details'},{fnEn:'The moment of recognition—warm, not explosive'},{fnEn:'Memory is enough—quiet conclusion'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Anti-climax as the point',detailEn:'No dramatic event—the happiness is in the ordinariness itself'},{pointEn:'Atmospheric writing',detailEn:'Foggy windows, melting gold streetlights, sleeping cat—every detail contributes to mood'},{pointEn:'Water metaphor',detailEn:'"The moment passed like water"—happiness is fluid, not solid'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Mom blew on each chopstick-load—a habit from when I was four',whyEn:'Twelve years of unchanged love in one gesture'},{textEn:'Like putting on a dry shirt after getting caught in the rain',whyEn:'A perfect simile for low-key, ordinary happiness—physical and emotional'},{textEn:'The moment passed like water—smooth, quiet, invisible',whyEn:'Poetic and true—happiness often isn\'t noticed until it\'s gone'}]},
    {titleEn:'Happiness Is All Around',
     fullTextEn:'I once asked different people: "What is happiness?"\n\nGrandpa said: "When the rice grows well. When the harvest can cover the year\'s expenses and still leave a little for your grandmother\'s medicine." He said it while weeding, face glistening with sweat, speaking as casually as if reciting weather.\n\nMom said: "When you\'re home for dinner." Just five words. But she said them so fast, like she\'d been holding them in.\n\nMy best friend said: "When you sit next to me in class." She punched my arm after saying it.\n\nI noticed: none of these happinesses are big. They\'re like water—ordinary, tasteless, easy to overlook.\n\nThen one night, something happened. The power went out. The whole neighborhood was dark. I walked to the window, panicking a little.\n\nThen our kitchen light flickered on—Dad had found the candle. Its small flame made the walls glow orange. Mom laughed: "Haven\'t used candles in years!" Dad put on a funny shadow show with his hands.\n\nAnd I thought: a lit house when the world goes dark. That\'s it. That\'s happiness.\n\nHappiness isn\'t a light that\'s always on. It\'s the one that stays on when everything else goes dark.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Asking different people about happiness—multiple perspectives'},{fnEn:'All their happinesses are small—extracting the pattern'},{fnEn:'The lit lamp—core image'},{fnEn:'Power outage night—darkness as contrast'},{fnEn:'The minimalist definition'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Interview-style structure',detailEn:'Collecting different answers creates a kaleidoscope of perspectives'},{pointEn:'Lamp as core image',detailEn:'A single candle in a blackout—the most vivid metaphor for happiness in dark times'},{pointEn:'Negative-proof deepens meaning',detailEn:'The power outage proves happiness through its absence, then restoration'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Harvested enough for the year with a little left for grandmother\'s medicine',whyEn:'Rural happiness defined in heartbreakingly practical terms'},{textEn:'Like water—ordinary, tasteless, easy to overlook',whyEn:'Happiness as the most essential, least noticed thing in life'},{textEn:'The light that stays on when everything else goes dark',whyEn:'A brilliant final image—simple and universally resonant'}]},
    {titleEn:'Happiness Is a Bowl of Noodles',
     fullTextEn:'Everyone says Grandma makes the best noodles in the world. I believed it until I tried to make them myself.\n\nGrandma\'s noodle ritual: heat the lard until it sizzles (the sound alone makes your mouth water). Add scallions—they curl and dance in the oil. Then broth, noodles, a drizzle of soy sauce, and her secret: a pinch of white pepper at the very end.\n\nI tried to replicate it at home. Same ingredients, same steps. But the taste was... wrong. Like a photocopy of a painting—technically similar, spiritually empty.\n\nI called Grandma: "Why don\'t mine taste like yours?"\n\nShe laughed: "Did you stand by the stove for twenty minutes watching the broth simmer?"\n\n"No, I went to watch TV."\n\n"That\'s why. The secret ingredient isn\'t in the recipe. It\'s patience. And—" she paused— "thinking about the person who\'s going to eat it. I start thinking about you before you even arrive."\n\nThat sentence hit me like a warm wave. Grandma\'s noodles aren\'t delicious because of lard or pepper. They\'re delicious because while she\'s cooking, she\'s already loving me.\n\nI\'ve eaten Grandma\'s noodles for twelve years. If I could, I\'d eat them for a lifetime.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Setup—best noodles in the world'},{fnEn:'Grandma\'s detailed cooking process'},{fnEn:'Failed replication → calling Grandma'},{fnEn:'Grandma\'s answer + happiness definition'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Food as emotional vessel',detailEn:'Noodles carry love—the most universal metaphor in Chinese culture'},{pointEn:'Failed replication reveals truth',detailEn:'You can copy ingredients but not love—a poignant discovery'},{pointEn:'Grandma\'s words are the core',detailEn:'"I start thinking about you before you arrive"—this sentence IS the essay'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Lard sizzling in the pan',whyEn:'An onomatopoeic detail that triggers sensory memory'},{textEn:'I start thinking about you before you even arrive',whyEn:'The essay\'s emotional core—love begins before the recipient knows'},{textEn:'I\'ve eaten these noodles for twelve years. I want to eat them for a lifetime',whyEn:'Simple repetition that carries enormous emotional weight'}]},
    {titleEn:'Happiness Is Struggle',
     fullTextEn:'Everyone says happiness is eating candy, playing games, sleeping in. But the happiest I\'ve ever felt was standing on a mountaintop, legs shaking, barely breathing.\n\nDad signed us up for a mountain climb—2,800 meters. "It\'ll be fun!" he said. By the halfway point, I was ready to divorce my father.\n\nMy calves burned. Every ten steps I had to stop. The trail seemed infinite—just when I thought the top was near, another ridge appeared. "Just ten more steps," I told myself. Then another ten. Then another.\n\nBy the 2,500-meter mark, my legs had completely stopped obeying me. But my heart was flying. Something wild and fierce was building inside me, something I\'d never felt sitting in a classroom.\n\nThen—the summit. And beyond it: clouds. Not below the clouds—I was above them. An ocean of white cotton stretching to the horizon, peaks poking through like islands. The sunrise painted everything gold.\n\nI didn\'t cheer. I didn\'t take photos. I just stood there. And then, completely unexpectedly, I started crying.\n\nDad put his arm around me. "Why are you crying?"\n\n"I don\'t know."\n\nBut I think I do now. That was happiness—the kind you earn with blisters on your feet. Its beauty isn\'t in the view. It\'s in knowing you almost quit a hundred times, but didn\'t.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Contrasting common happiness with earned happiness'},{fnEn:'Exhaustion and wanting to quit'},{fnEn:'Ten steps at a time—willpower'},{fnEn:'Reaching the summit → cloud sea → emotional eruption'},{fnEn:'"Worth it" defined + happiness philosophy'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Directly echoing the prompt',detailEn:'"Hard work leads to happiness" made concrete through a mountain climb'},{pointEn:'Physical sensation conveys inner struggle',detailEn:'Burning calves, shaking legs—the body tells the psychological story'},{pointEn:'Surprise emotion at the climax',detailEn:'Crying at the summit—not expected by the narrator or the reader'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Just ten more steps—then another ten',whyEn:'The simplest willpower strategy—and the most effective'},{textEn:'My legs had stopped obeying me, but my heart was flying',whyEn:'Body vs. spirit conflict expressed in one sentence'},{textEn:'Sometimes happiness is blisters on your feet',whyEn:'A counterintuitive but deeply true redefinition of happiness'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: cg2024_comp_b "___的那一刻" ──
TOPICS['cg2024_comp_b'] = {
  promptEn:'Write an essay titled "___ That Moment." Complete the title. Content should be specific, theme clear, ideas healthy, presentation neat. At least 400 words. No real names or school names.',
  contextEn:'The movie "YOLO" (Hot and Spicy) features Du Leying\'s efforts to push boundaries and challenge herself... exploring challenges, transcendence, and self-realization in growth.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'"That moment" pins the essay to a single point in time—the entire essay focuses on one instant. Key points: (1) fill in a word with emotional impact (overcoming fear / being understood / growing up); (2) build up context before "that moment" and extend its significance after; (3) show the psychological transformation before and after "that moment."',
    pitfallsEn:['Time span too wide—it\'s "that moment" not "that day"','Lacking buildup—jumping to the moment without context','Emotions unfocused—too many events dilute the impact','Filler word too bland—"happy moment" lacks tension'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose a moment with a turning-point quality','Structure as buildup → climax → reflection','Zoom into that one second of psychological experience','End with a life insight extracted from the "moment"']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'The Moment I Was Understood',
     fullTextEn:'For years, Dad and I had an invisible wall between us. He wanted me to study; I wanted to draw. We lived in the same house but spoke different languages.\n\nI drew in secret—only after confirming he was asleep, late at night, under my desk lamp. My sketchbook lived under a pile of textbooks, hidden like contraband.\n\nThen came the school art exhibition. The teacher selected my piece. I was thrilled and terrified—thrilled because it was recognition; terrified because Dad would find out.\n\nThe exhibition was on a Saturday. I went alone, expecting only classmates. Then I saw him. Dad. Standing in front of my painting. Just standing there.\n\nThe painting was called "Waiting for Dad to Come Home." A child sitting at a window, chin on hands, a half-moon outside. Dad stared at it for a long time. Then he turned to me and said four words: "You drew this well."\n\nFour words. After years of silence on the topic, four words.\n\nI didn\'t cry. But something cracked open—something I\'d been pressing shut for years. In that moment, I understood: he wasn\'t against my drawing. He just didn\'t know how to express support. And the painting told him what I couldn\'t say in words.\n\nHe wasn\'t incapable of understanding me. He just needed a door. My painting was that door.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Father-son rift established'},{fnEn:'Drawing in secret—the hidden life'},{fnEn:'Art exhibition—conflict point'},{fnEn:'Dad appears → sees the painting → four words'},{fnEn:'"That moment\'s" significance—understanding'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'The power of secrets',detailEn:'Hidden sketching builds tension that the exhibition moment releases'},{pointEn:'The painting speaks for the child',detailEn:'"Waiting for Dad to Come Home"—the painting says what words can\'t'},{pointEn:'Four words carry immense weight',detailEn:'After years of silence, four words of approval create an earthquake'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Only drew after confirming he was asleep, late at night',whyEn:'The secrecy reveals how deeply the child fears disapproval'},{textEn:'The painting was called "Waiting for Dad to Come Home"',whyEn:'The title alone is a love letter—the father sees his child\'s longing through art'},{textEn:'He wasn\'t incapable of understanding me—he just needed a door',whyEn:'A mature realization about communication—understanding requires access'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Moment I Surpassed Myself',
     fullTextEn:'Zero. That was my pull-up count at the start of sixth grade. Zero.\n\nThe PE teacher announced the fitness test would include pull-ups. Everyone groaned; I nearly fainted. I hung from the bar like a fish on a hook—ugly and helpless.\n\nThree months of training. Every morning before school: ten attempts. At first I couldn\'t even bend my arms. By week three, a quivering half-pull-up. By month two, three shaky but complete ones.\n\nExam day arrived. The bar gleamed in the winter sun. I chalked my hands, jumped up, and pulled. One. Arms screaming. Two. Vision blurring. Three. Someone counted aloud. Four. The class started clapping rhythmically. Five. I didn\'t know I was crying. Six.\n\nSix pull-ups. From zero to six.\n\nWhen I dropped from the bar, the applause was deafening. But louder than the cheering was the voice inside me: "I did it."\n\nThat moment, I learned: surpassing yourself isn\'t about beating others. It\'s about making yesterday\'s impossible today\'s reality. You are stronger than you think.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Zero pull-ups—the embarrassing starting point'},{fnEn:'Three months of training progression'},{fnEn:'Exam—counting each pull-up to six'},{fnEn:'Definition of surpassing oneself'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Numerical narrative',detailEn:'0 → 3 → 6: numbers tell the growth story more powerfully than adjectives'},{pointEn:'Physical sensation as psychology',detailEn:'Arms screaming, vision blurring—the body narrates the inner battle'},{pointEn:'Collective reaction amplifies the climax',detailEn:'Rhythmic clapping + applause creates a cinematic finish'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Hung from the bar like a fish on a hook—ugly and helpless',whyEn:'Self-deprecating humor that makes the starting point vivid and relatable'},{textEn:'Louder than the cheering was the voice inside: "I did it"',whyEn:'Internal triumph matters more than external validation—the core message'},{textEn:'You are stronger than you think',whyEn:'Direct address to the reader—universal and empowering'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Moment of Forgiveness',
     fullTextEn:'For an entire semester, there was an empty chair beside me. The person who used to sit there—my best friend Xiao Lin—and I hadn\'t spoken since the incident.\n\nIt started small. Xiao Lin copied my homework. A classmate reported it. The teacher blamed both of us. I could have spoken up—"I didn\'t let her copy; she took my notebook without asking." But I said nothing.\n\nSilence can be its own kind of wrong.\n\nXiao Lin stopped talking to me. Not because she was angry about being caught, but because when she needed me to tell the truth, I chose to protect myself.\n\nMonths passed. The empty chair grew heavier every day—like a hole in the room.\n\nThen one morning, a note appeared on my desk. Her handwriting: "I\'m sorry I took your notebook. Are we still friends?"\n\nI turned around. She was watching me, biting her lip.\n\nI wrote back: "I\'m sorry I didn\'t speak up. Yes."\n\nIn that moment, I learned two things. Forgiveness isn\'t just about accepting someone\'s apology. It\'s about admitting your own fault too. And silence can be its own kind of betrayal.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'A whole semester of cold shoulder—arousing curiosity'},{fnEn:'The incident and "my" cowardly silence'},{fnEn:'The note → apology → mutual forgiveness'},{fnEn:'Dual meaning of forgiveness'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Honest self-criticism',detailEn:'The narrator admits their own fault—rare and brave for a student essay'},{pointEn:'Silence as wrongdoing',detailEn:'"Silence can be its own kind of wrong"—a sophisticated moral insight'},{pointEn:'Waiting required courage',detailEn:'The reconciliation took courage from both sides—the note and the reply'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Being used as "the answer source" gave me a tiny bit of pride',whyEn:'Brutally honest about a petty ego satisfaction—disarming authenticity'},{textEn:'The empty chair grew heavier every day, like a hole in the room',whyEn:'Absence given physical weight—an evocative metaphor for broken friendship'},{textEn:'Silence can be its own kind of wrong',whyEn:'The essay\'s moral center—a truth most adults struggle to articulate'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Moment I Grew Up',
     fullTextEn:'People ask: "When did you grow up?" I used to have no answer. Now I do. It was a Tuesday evening when I noticed the words "further examination recommended" on Mom\'s medical report.\n\nMy heart rate spiked. Mom was in the kitchen, humming a song, as if nothing had happened. I wanted to ask but couldn\'t find the words. That night, I lay awake, staring at the ceiling, replaying every time Mom said "I\'m fine" and wondering if any of them were lies.\n\nThe next morning, I got up before Mom. Made breakfast—porridge with red dates, her favorite. Set the table. When she came out and saw it, she froze.\n\n"You made this?"\n\n"Sit down and eat," I said. My voice was calm, but inside I was panicking—the porridge was probably terrible.\n\nIt wasn\'t. She ate two bowls.\n\nThat evening, Dad came home and saw me bringing Mom a glass of warm water. He looked at me and said: "Thank you."\n\nNot "good job." Not "you\'re so capable." Just "thank you"—the way you thank an equal. An adult.\n\nThat was the moment. The person who always took care of me—one day, she needed me to take care of her. Growing up isn\'t a birthday. It\'s a responsibility that arrives quietly.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'The question "when did you grow up?"'},{fnEn:'Discovering Mom\'s medical report'},{fnEn:'Proactively caring for Mom—making breakfast, serving water'},{fnEn:'Dad\'s "thank you"—being treated as an adult'},{fnEn:'Definition of growing up'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Role reversal as growth marker',detailEn:'The caretaker needing care—a universal sign of maturity'},{pointEn:'Action over words',detailEn:'Making breakfast and serving water speak louder than declarations'},{pointEn:'Dad\'s "thank you" is the certification',detailEn:'Being thanked like an equal—that\'s when childhood ends'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'"Further examination recommended" made my heart rate spike',whyEn:'Medical jargon triggering fear—a very modern, relatable detail'},{textEn:'I said this calmly, but inside I was panicking',whyEn:'The gap between composed exterior and terrified interior IS maturity'},{textEn:'The person who always took care of you one day needs you to take care of her',whyEn:'The simplest, most powerful definition of growing up'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Moment I Decided',
     fullTextEn:'Tomorrow was the deadline to submit the form. Piano class or soccer team? I couldn\'t sleep.\n\nFor three years, Mom had driven me to piano lessons every Saturday. I was decent—Grade 6 certificate on the wall. But every time I heard the soccer team practicing on the school field, my feet itched.\n\nI\'d never told Mom. Her dream was for me to perform at the school concert. My dream was to score a goal in a real match.\n\nThat night, I went to get water and passed Mom\'s room. Her phone screen glowed—she was texting Dad: "Actually, I know he wants to play soccer. But piano took so long... I don\'t know what to say."\n\nMy hand froze on the doorknob. She knew. She\'d known all along.\n\nI went back to my room, picked up the form, and checked "soccer." Then I walked to Mom\'s room.\n\n"Mom, I chose soccer."\n\nShe was quiet for three seconds. Then she smiled: "I know. Go to bed."\n\nThe next morning, the piano was still there. So were the three years of effort. But the check mark on that form—that was mine. My hand drew it. My decision made it.\n\nThat moment, I learned: growing up is when you stop following someone else\'s path and start drawing your own.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'The pressure of choice—tomorrow is the deadline'},{fnEn:'Inner conflict—piano vs. soccer'},{fnEn:'Seeing Mom\'s text—she already knew'},{fnEn:'Making the decision → Mom\'s response → insight'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Choice as growth',detailEn:'Making an autonomous decision is the central act of growing up'},{pointEn:'The text message as turning point',detailEn:'Discovering Mom already knows removes guilt and enables honesty'},{pointEn:'Quiet climax',detailEn:'"I know. Go to bed."—three words of acceptance more powerful than any speech'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'My heart was like a bird trapped in a cage',whyEn:'A physical metaphor for feeling constrained by others\' expectations'},{textEn:'Actually, I know he wants to play soccer',whyEn:'Mom\'s secret awareness—parents often know more than children think'},{textEn:'That check mark was mine—my hand drew it',whyEn:'Ownership of a decision, expressed through a tiny physical act'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: gd2024_comp_a "追光路上的___" ──
TOPICS['gd2024_comp_a'] = {
  promptEn:'Write an essay titled "On the Path of Chasing Light: ___." Record the person or event that left the deepest impression during your primary school years. Content should be specific, appropriately detailed, and express genuine feelings. At least 400 words.',
  contextEn:'The school is hosting a "Light-Chasing Youth Growth Season" graduation event.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'"Chasing light" is the core metaphor—representing the pursuit of ideals, progress, and brightness. The blank should relate to this metaphor. You can fill in a person (guide/companion/oneself) or an event (setback/turning point/companionship). The 2024 Guandu District exam weaves a "light-chasing youth" theme throughout.',
    pitfallsEn:['Not understanding the "chasing light" metaphor—writing about literally chasing light','Filling in a bland word—"the story on the path of chasing light" is too vague','Only writing about "light" without the "path"—lacking the sense of process','Disconnecting from primary school life—should write about campus experiences'],
    keyPointsEn:['Fill in a word with emotional weight','Clarify what "light" is—what you\'re pursuing','Describe what happened on the "path"—the process and difficulties','End with having "caught the light" or "understood the light"']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'The Guide on My Path of Chasing Light',
     fullTextEn:'If primary school is a road, then for most of it, I walked in the dark. Until Teacher Zhou turned on a light.\n\nIn third grade, I was the invisible student—a pothos plant in the classroom corner, alive but unnoticed. I never raised my hand. My compositions were three lines long. No one expected anything from me, including myself.\n\nTeacher Zhou was different. One day, she kept me after class and said: "Your composition was short. But every word was real. That\'s rare."\n\nThree lines. She found something worth praising in three lines.\n\nShe started giving me small assignments: "Write me five sentences about what you see on the way home." Then: "Write a paragraph about your dinner." Then: "Read this passage to the class tomorrow."\n\nEach step was small enough not to scare me. By fifth grade, I could write a full essay without freezing up. By sixth grade, I stood on stage at the graduation ceremony, reading my own composition—about a pothos plant that learned to grow toward the light.\n\nAfter the ceremony, Teacher Zhou said three words: "You\'re glowing now."\n\nOn the path of chasing light, not everyone can find the light alone. Some of us need a guide—someone who doesn\'t carry us, but walks ahead, leaving small lamps along the way.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Road + light metaphor opening'},{fnEn:'Invisible student status'},{fnEn:'Teacher Zhou\'s method—from three lines to the stage'},{fnEn:'Fifth grade → sixth grade → graduation ceremony'},{fnEn:'"You\'re glowing" + understanding of "guide"'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Pothos metaphor',detailEn:'A pothos plant in the corner—alive but unnoticed—perfectly mirrors the student\'s state'},{pointEn:'Gradual growth progression',detailEn:'5 sentences → paragraph → essay → stage speech—each step is specific and believable'},{pointEn:'"You\'re glowing" ties everything together',detailEn:'Three words that echo "chasing light"—the guide confirms the light has been found'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Like a pothos plant in the classroom corner—alive, but unnoticed',whyEn:'A devastating self-portrait—plants as metaphor for overlooked students'},{textEn:'Your writing is short, but every word is real. That\'s rare',whyEn:'Teacher Zhou finds gold in three lines—this is what great teaching looks like'},{textEn:'On the path of chasing light, not everyone can find the light alone',whyEn:'Acknowledging the need for help—a mature and generous insight'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Stumbling Block on My Path of Chasing Light',
     fullTextEn:'When people write about "chasing light," they usually fill in beautiful words—guide, dream, companion. I\'m going to write about a stumbling block. Because sometimes, what trips you is what teaches you the most.\n\nFourth grade. Math competition. I\'d been the class champion for two years, so I entered the district level with complete confidence. Result: 41 out of 100. Forty-one.\n\nThat number lived in my brain for weeks. Competition problems and textbook problems weren\'t even the same species—textbook problems walked; competition problems flew.\n\nI wanted to quit. My teacher said: "Quitting is easy. But then you\'ll always wonder."\n\nSo I trained. All winter break. Workbooks, practice papers, online tutorials. By spring, I entered again. Score: 81. Third prize.\n\nNot first. Not even close. But 81 minus 41 equals 40 points of pure growth.\n\nI kept that 41-point test paper. It\'s taped above my desk—next to the third-prize certificate. Because the certificate shows what I achieved, but the test paper shows where I started. And the distance between them is the real trophy.\n\nEvery fall teaches you where the ground is. And every time you get up, the light gets a little closer.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Why write about a stumbling block?'},{fnEn:'41-point competition disaster'},{fnEn:'Teacher\'s guidance + winter training'},{fnEn:'81 points and third prize'},{fnEn:'Meaning of the stumbling block'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Reverse word choice wins',detailEn:'Choosing "stumbling block" instead of something positive is creative and attention-grabbing'},{pointEn:'Numbers tell the story',detailEn:'41 → 81 = 40 points of growth—math speaks louder than words'},{pointEn:'Keeping the test paper',detailEn:'Displaying the failure alongside the success—a powerful visual statement'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'41 out of 100. That number lived in my brain for weeks',whyEn:'Repetition of the number emphasizes the psychological impact of failure'},{textEn:'Competition problems and textbook problems aren\'t even the same species',whyEn:'A humorous comparison that any student can relate to'},{textEn:'Every fall teaches you where the ground is',whyEn:'A reframing of failure as navigation—knowing the ground helps you walk'}]},
    {titleEn:'Myself on the Path of Chasing Light',
     fullTextEn:'Who am I chasing light with? After thinking for a long time, my answer is: myself.\n\nFirst grade me was timid. I cried when called on. I sat in the back row, hoping to disappear. My light was dim—barely a spark.\n\nThird grade me was competitive. I had to be first in everything. When I lost, I sulked for days. My light was fierce—but it burned others.\n\nFifth grade me was confused. Good at some things, bad at others. Not the best, not the worst. Just... average. My light was uncertain—flickering, unsure.\n\nSixth grade me? I think I\'m starting to accept. Accept that I\'m not always brave, not always first, not always sure. Accept that being ordinary is okay. My light now is—gentler.\n\nIf I were a color, first grade was pale, third grade was hot red, fifth grade was grey, and now... a gradient. Moving slowly from uncertain to steady. More and more like "my own" color.\n\nChasing light doesn\'t mean becoming the brightest. It means becoming more and more like yourself. And when you do, you\'ll realize: the person chasing light—is already glowing.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Why write about "myself"?'},{fnEn:'First grade: timid'},{fnEn:'Third grade: competitive'},{fnEn:'Fifth grade: confused'},{fnEn:'Sixth grade: acceptance'},{fnEn:'Gradient metaphor—the self evolving'},{fnEn:'Light is within oneself'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Courage of self-examination',detailEn:'Writing about one\'s own flaws across years requires real bravery'},{pointEn:'Gradient metaphor',detailEn:'Not sudden transformation but gradual color shift—realistic and poetic'},{pointEn:'Accepting imperfection',detailEn:'The thesis isn\'t about achievement but about self-acceptance'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'First grade timid, third grade competitive, fifth grade confused',whyEn:'Three ages, three states—a rapid-fire self-portrait across time'},{textEn:'More and more like "my own" color',whyEn:'Identity formation expressed as finding your unique shade—beautiful'},{textEn:'The person chasing light is already glowing',whyEn:'A liberating thesis—the search itself is the achievement'}]},
    {titleEn:'A Book on My Path of Chasing Light',
     fullTextEn:'My light didn\'t come from a person. It came from between the pages of a book.\n\nIn the school library, on a bottom shelf covered in dust, I found a worn copy of "A Little Princess." Nobody had checked it out in years.\n\nI read it three times. The first time, it was just a story—a girl who loses everything but keeps her dignity. The second time, I noticed how she spoke to cruel people—not with anger, but with quiet strength. The third time, I understood: the book wasn\'t about a princess. It was about what you are when everything is taken away.\n\nThat year, a classmate made fun of my glasses. "Four-eyes can\'t even see the blackboard!" Others laughed. I wanted to cry. But I thought of Sara Crewe—who, even as a servant, carried herself like royalty.\n\nI straightened my back, pushed up my glasses, and said nothing. The teasing stopped after a few days.\n\nThe light in my heart didn\'t come from someone else\'s praise. It came from a dusty book on a bottom shelf. A book that told me: you don\'t need others\' permission to have light. You carry it inside.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Light comes from books'},{fnEn:'Finding the book in the library'},{fnEn:'Three readings, three different insights'},{fnEn:'Being teased for glasses → the book gives strength'},{fnEn:'Inner light doesn\'t need external permission'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'A book as light',detailEn:'A non-human source of "light"—creative and bookish'},{pointEn:'Three progressive readings',detailEn:'Each reading reveals a deeper layer—showing genuine engagement with literature'},{pointEn:'Book and life echo each other',detailEn:'Sara Crewe\'s dignity directly inspires the narrator\'s response to bullying'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'From between the pages of a book, light leaked out',whyEn:'A gorgeous image—light as something that escapes from books'},{textEn:'Not eye-light but heart-light',whyEn:'Redefining light from visual to spiritual—a clever play on the glasses/vision theme'},{textEn:'Darkness isn\'t the end',whyEn:'A simple declarative statement with universal resonance'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Opponent on the Path of Chasing Light',
     fullTextEn:'If someone told me in first grade that I\'d write a thank-you essay about my biggest rival, I\'d have laughed.\n\nChen Yiming and I competed in everything for six years. Grades. Sports day. Even who got to the cafeteria first. If she scored higher, I\'d seethe; if I scored higher, I\'d gloat. It was exhausting and exhilarating.\n\nBut here\'s what I never admitted: she made me better. Every time she pulled ahead, I ran faster. Every time she aced something, I studied harder. Without her, I would have coasted.\n\nThe last monthly exam of sixth grade, something strange happened. I finished my paper and looked up—she was looking at me too. We both smiled. After six years, the competition had become something else. Not rivalry. Companionship.\n\nAfter the exam, she handed me a book. Inside the cover she\'d written: "You behind me, I couldn\'t stop. Thank you."\n\nI wrote in hers: "You ahead of me, I had to keep going. Thank you."\n\nOn graduation day, we took a photo together—the only photo in six years where we weren\'t competing. Just standing side by side, smiling.\n\nThe best opponent isn\'t someone who beats you. It\'s someone who runs beside you and makes you run faster.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'"Thank you" + "opponent"—contradictory combination'},{fnEn:'Six years of rivalry'},{fnEn:'The opponent\'s motivational effect'},{fnEn:'Last exam → exchanged looks → exchanged books'},{fnEn:'Mutual inscriptions + graduation photo'},{fnEn:'True meaning of an opponent'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Redefining "opponent"',detailEn:'From enemy to companion—a mature reinterpretation'},{pointEn:'Six-year time span',detailEn:'The long duration makes the final reconciliation more moving'},{pointEn:'Mutual inscriptions',detailEn:'Both thank each other in parallel—symmetry mirrors their relationship'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'If she scored higher I\'d seethe; if I scored higher I\'d gloat',whyEn:'Brutally honest about childish competitiveness—immediately relatable'},{textEn:'You behind me, I couldn\'t stop',whyEn:'Her inscription reveals the rivalry was mutual—both pushed each other'},{textEn:'Running beside you, making you run faster',whyEn:'The definitive reimagining of competition as collaboration'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: tc2024_comp_a "那一次，我___" ──
TOPICS['tc2024_comp_a'] = {
  promptEn:'Write an essay titled "That Time, I ___." Complete the title; content should be specific with smooth sentences; express genuine feelings; write neatly.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'"That time" limits the essay to a single event—write about one thing only. Fill in the blank with a word expressing emotion or action (cried/laughed/grew up/truly regretted/gathered courage). The key is showing how "that time" deeply impacted you.',
    pitfallsEn:['Filler word lacks tension—"that time I was happy" is too bland','Glossing over the most interesting part of the process','Insight disconnected from the story','Writing a checklist-style chronological account'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose a "that time" with an emotional turning point','Write the most critical moment in fine, vivid detail','Convey genuine feeling through details and inner monologue','End concisely and powerfully—one sentence to tie the theme']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'That Time, I Chose Honesty',
     fullTextEn:'The math test was halfway through. I was stuck on problem 12. My pen hovered in the air.\n\nZhang Wei\'s answer sheet was right there. He sat diagonally in front of me. Problem 12, answer: B. I could see it clearly.\n\nI almost copied it. My pen actually moved toward my paper. Then it stopped.\n\nWhat stopped me wasn\'t morality—not some grand principle. It was this: if I copied, the 92 on my report card would have two stolen points. And every time I looked at that score, I\'d know.\n\nI wrote my own answer: C. Wrong, as it turned out.\n\nZhang Wei got 92. I got 90. For a week, I felt a dull ache every time I saw his score. "Two points," I thought. "Just two points."\n\nBut here\'s the thing about stolen points: they don\'t stay stolen. They follow you. They turn every future 100 into a question: "Did I really earn this?"\n\nNinety is ninety. It\'s mine. Every point.\n\nScores can be made up. But honesty, once lost, has no make-up exam.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'The temptation during the exam—a split-second decision'},{fnEn:'Choosing not to copy—the internal process'},{fnEn:'Score comparison—brief regret'},{fnEn:'90 vs 92 value judgment'},{fnEn:'Honesty can\'t be recovered'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'A tiny but critical choice',detailEn:'Two points—seemingly trivial, but the essay makes them weigh tons'},{pointEn:'Honestly writing about regret',detailEn:'Admitting the dull ache of seeing 92 vs 90 is brave and authentic'},{pointEn:'Numerical contrast',detailEn:'90 vs 92 makes the abstract concept of honesty concrete and measurable'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Pen hovered in the air',whyEn:'A frozen moment—time stops as the moral choice is made'},{textEn:'Two stolen points',whyEn:'Framing copied answers as theft—a reframing that changes everything'},{textEn:'Scores can be made up, but honesty once lost has no make-up exam',whyEn:'The thesis—clever wordplay that lands perfectly'}]},
    {titleEn:'That Time, I Truly Regretted',
     fullTextEn:'The lie slipped out before I could catch it.\n\nMom came home from work, exhausted. She\'d made a special trip to buy my favorite dishes. "How was the test?" she asked, setting down bags of groceries.\n\n"Ninety-five," I said.\n\nI got seventy-eight.\n\nThe dinner was delicious. Mom smiled the whole time. "I knew you could do it!" she said, adding an extra chicken leg to my bowl. Every bite tasted like guilt.\n\nThat night, I couldn\'t sleep. I stared at the ceiling, calculating: how long before the teacher posts scores online? Two days? Can I intercept it? No. Can I retake the test? No. One lie needs more lies to cover it—like using a small bandage on a wound that keeps growing.\n\nAt 6 AM, I wrote a note: "Mom, I got 78, not 95. I\'m sorry I lied. I\'ll do better next time." I put it on the breakfast table and went to my room to wait.\n\nMom came in ten minutes later. She sat on my bed. She wasn\'t angry. She said, quietly: "You choosing to tell me the truth makes me happier than any 95."\n\nThat was worse than yelling. Because I\'d let her be happy for nothing. And the look in her eyes—relief mixed with sadness—that look cost more than any grade.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'The impulsive lie—a table full of food'},{fnEn:'Insomnia and mounting anxiety'},{fnEn:'Confessing via note—authentic detail'},{fnEn:'Mom\'s calm response'},{fnEn:'The cost of a lie'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Honest about wrongdoing',detailEn:'The narrator doesn\'t dodge blame—full accountability'},{pointEn:'Insomnia as authentic psychology',detailEn:'The ceiling-staring, calculations, growing panic—psychologically accurate'},{pointEn:'The note as detail',detailEn:'Writing a note instead of saying it face-to-face—a very real child behavior'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'One lie needs more lies to cover it',whyEn:'A universal truth about deception, expressed in child-accessible language'},{textEn:'You telling me the truth makes me happier than any 95',whyEn:'Mom values character over grades—a powerful parental message'},{textEn:'Let Mom be happy for nothing',whyEn:'The deepest sting—not the lie itself, but the wasted joy it created'}]},
    {titleEn:'That Time, I Gathered Courage',
     fullTextEn:'The school needed someone to sing at the charity concert. Nobody raised their hand. I wanted to—desperately—but my arm weighed a thousand pounds.\n\nTwo years ago, fourth grade talent show. I\'d sung half a song before my voice cracked. The laughter that followed took up residence in my brain and never left.\n\nBut this time, something was different. Maybe it was the silence. Maybe it was the teacher\'s disappointed face. Maybe it was the fact that I was sick of being the person who "almost" does things.\n\nMy hand went up. The entire class turned to look at me. The teacher\'s eyebrows rose.\n\nTwo weeks of practice. I sang in the shower, in my room, into my pillow. My brother said I was "terrorizing the household." I sang to the mirror until the mirror\'s expression stopped scaring me.\n\nConcert night. Backstage, my hands were ice. The emcee called my name. During the eight-beat intro, I thought seven things—six of them were "I can still run."\n\nThen I opened my mouth. The first note wobbled. The second was better. By the chorus, I wasn\'t thinking anymore. I was just singing.\n\nThe applause was loud. But what I remember most is the two seconds of silence right before it—when the last note hung in the air and the world held its breath. In those two seconds, I knew: there was never a cliff beneath my feet. Only solid ground I\'d been too scared to step on.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'The need for a singer—nobody volunteers—I want to'},{fnEn:'Fourth-grade trauma memory'},{fnEn:'Hand goes up—the decisive moment'},{fnEn:'Two weeks of practice (humorous details)'},{fnEn:'On stage → fear → opening my mouth → applause'},{fnEn:'Definition of courage + life insight'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Deep psychological portrayal',detailEn:'The fourth-grade trauma and its lingering effect make the courage meaningful'},{pointEn:'Humor adjusts pace',detailEn:'Brother\'s complaint and mirror practice add lightness to the tension'},{pointEn:'"Two seconds of silence" before applause',detailEn:'The most powerful moment is the silence, not the clapping—superb instinct'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'That laughter took up residence in my brain and never left',whyEn:'Trauma described as an unwanted tenant—vivid and psychologically real'},{textEn:'During the eight-beat intro, I thought seven things—six were "I can still run"',whyEn:'Hilarious and terrifying simultaneously—perfect comedy-in-crisis'},{textEn:'There was never a cliff beneath my feet. Only solid ground',whyEn:'A revelation: the fear was always bigger than the reality'}]},
    {titleEn:'That Time, I Cried',
     fullTextEn:'I don\'t cry easily. Ask anyone. But that Thursday afternoon, seven pieces of paper made me fall apart.\n\nOur class did an anonymous note activity. Everyone wrote something nice about a classmate, folded the paper, and dropped it in a box. The teacher distributed them randomly.\n\nI expected zero notes. Or maybe one obligatory one. I\'m the quiet kid. The one who reads during recess. The one nobody fights over for group projects.\n\nSeven notes fell out of my envelope.\n\n"Thank you for always lending me your eraser without me having to ask."\n"You explain math better than the teacher. Don\'t tell her I said that."\n"Thank you for being there, quiet and steady, like the classroom clock."\n"I like sitting near you because you smell like books."\n"When I\'m sad, I look at you reading and feel calmer."\n"Thank you for always being quiet and nice—it makes me know that not talking is also okay."\n"Thank you for existing."\n\nI read them one by one. By the fifth note, my vision blurred. By the seventh, I was crying at my desk, notes clutched in both hands.\n\nNot because I was sad. Because I\'d spent years thinking I was invisible, and seven pieces of paper told me I was wrong. I was seen. I was needed. I mattered—in ways I never imagined.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Setting: I don\'t cry—then why did I?'},{fnEn:'Anonymous note activity + self-doubt'},{fnEn:'Receiving seven notes—one by one'},{fnEn:'Crying—the reason + insight'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Low expectations → high reward',detailEn:'Expecting zero and receiving seven—the gap is the emotional engine'},{pointEn:'Notes are the essay\'s highlight',detailEn:'Each note is a tiny masterpiece of observation—the best content in the piece'},{pointEn:'Redefining self-worth',detailEn:'From "invisible" to "needed"—a profound psychological shift'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Thank you for being quiet and nice—it makes me know not talking is also okay',whyEn:'Validates introverted children in one sentence—incredibly affirming'},{textEn:'Thank you for existing',whyEn:'Two words that carry infinite weight—the simplest and most powerful note'},{textEn:'I mattered in ways I never imagined',whyEn:'The realization that impact ≠ visibility—one can matter quietly'}]},
    {titleEn:'That Time, I Said "No"',
     fullTextEn:'I have always been the "good kid." The one who says yes. Yes to extra homework. Yes to switching seats. Yes to lending my favorite pen even when I know it won\'t come back.\n\nThen Da Zhuang asked me to sweep the floor for him. Again.\n\n"You\'re better at it," he said, flashing his signature grin. He\'d used this line five times this month.\n\nSomething snapped. Not loudly—more like a thread finally giving way.\n\n"No."\n\nThe whole classroom went quiet for one second. Da Zhuang\'s grin froze. I could feel my heart hammering.\n\n"What?"\n\n"No. It\'s your turn. You sweep."\n\nHe stared at me. I stared back. For three eternal seconds, I thought the sky would fall. It didn\'t.\n\nDa Zhuang shrugged, picked up the broom, and swept. The world continued spinning.\n\nAfter that, I said "no" to other things too. No, I won\'t give you my eraser if you never return it. No, I won\'t let you copy during the test. Each "no" was terrifying and liberating.\n\nThe word "no" has only one stroke in Chinese (不). But it\'s the most powerful character I\'ve ever learned.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'The "always yes" persona'},{fnEn:'Da Zhuang asks me to sweep—again'},{fnEn:'Saying "no"—the moment'},{fnEn:'His reaction + my shock that nothing bad happened'},{fnEn:'Learning to say more "no"s'},{fnEn:'The power of "no"'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Everyday courage',detailEn:'Not a dramatic event—saying no to a bully-lite is relatable and impactful'},{pointEn:'One word\'s power',detailEn:'"No" is tiny but seismic—the essay respects this word\'s weight'},{pointEn:'Breaking the "good kid" trap',detailEn:'The realization that being nice ≠ being a pushover'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'The whole classroom went quiet for one second',whyEn:'One second of silence = the social earthquake of breaking a pattern'},{textEn:'The sky didn\'t fall',whyEn:'The anticlimax IS the lesson—fear of consequences was worse than the consequences'},{textEn:'This character has only one stroke, but it\'s the most powerful one I\'ve learned',whyEn:'Metalinguistic brilliance—connecting Chinese character structure to life philosophy'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: wh2024_comp_a "童年一件事" ──
TOPICS['wh2024_comp_a'] = {
  promptEn:'Recall your childhood and select one event to write about. Choose your own title, at least 450 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'A wide-open narrative prompt. The key is "one event"—don\'t turn it into a list of multiple events. Choose something interesting, touching, or educational that reflects childhood qualities (innocence, curiosity, joy).',
    pitfallsEn:['Choosing a boring event with nothing meaningful to say','Narrating too briefly without details','Mixing multiple events without focus'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose one truly memorable event','Describe key scenes in rich detail','Let emotions flow naturally from the narrative']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'Stealing Bayberries',
     fullTextEn:'The most delicious bayberries in the world grow on Grandma\'s tree. Also the most forbidden.\n\nEvery June, the tree loaded with fruit drove me crazy. Purple-red bayberries hung like agate beads, each one glistening with morning dew. Grandma said: "Wait until they\'re fully ripe." But I was seven. Waiting wasn\'t in my vocabulary.\n\nOne afternoon while Grandma napped, I dragged a stool to the tree, climbed up, and reached for the biggest cluster. The first one burst in my mouth—sweet, sour, cold, with that fuzzy texture that tickles your tongue. I ate one. Then five. Then I lost count.\n\nSuddenly: "What are you doing up there?!"\n\nGrandma stood below, hands on hips. I froze, cheeks bulging with a bayberry I didn\'t dare chew.\n\nBut she didn\'t scold me. She sighed, went inside, and came back with a basket: "At least use this so you don\'t drop them everywhere."\n\nAs she turned away, I clearly saw her hiding a smile.\n\nThe price: my teeth were so sore I couldn\'t eat dinner. Grandma watched me struggling with rice porridge and said nothing. But her eyes were laughing.\n\nThat tree was cut down years ago for road construction. Now I buy bayberries at the supermarket. They\'re fine. But they\'re not the same. Nothing tastes like stolen fruit from a grandmother\'s tree while she pretends not to see.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Setting the scene—Grandma\'s bayberry tree'},{fnEn:'Can\'t wait + Grandma naps'},{fnEn:'Climbing and eating—taste description'},{fnEn:'Grandma catches me → unexpected response'},{fnEn:'Sore teeth aftermath + Grandma\'s hidden laugh'},{fnEn:'Present-day nostalgia'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Pure childhood fun',detailEn:'No heavy moral—just the joy and mischief of being seven'},{pointEn:'Taste-based narrative',detailEn:'The sensory description of bayberries drives the whole essay'},{pointEn:'Grandma\'s reversal',detailEn:'Expected scolding → handing a basket—this twist is pure love'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Purple-red bayberries hung like agate beads',whyEn:'A beautiful and precise visual metaphor'},{textEn:'Cheeks bulging with a bayberry I didn\'t dare chew',whyEn:'A perfectly frozen moment of caught-in-the-act comedy'},{textEn:'As she turned away, I clearly saw her hiding a smile',whyEn:'Grandma\'s secret indulgence—love disguised as stern looks'}]},
    {titleEn:'My First Train Ride',
     fullTextEn:'My first time on a train felt like a movie—a very long movie where I had the best window seat.\n\nDad and I took the train to Dali. Everything at the station was huge: the ceiling, the display boards, the crowds. My neck hurt from looking up.\n\nOnce the train moved, the world outside started changing like a slideshow. Tall buildings became fields. Fields became hills. Hills became mountains with clouds sitting on them like cotton hats.\n\nI pressed my face against the glass for three hours straight. Mom later said I left a nose-print.\n\nA tunnel came without warning—WHOOSH—darkness swallowed everything. I yelped. Then light returned, and mountains were even closer, as if they\'d jumped toward us.\n\nAn old man across the aisle taught me a game: guess what\'s around the next bend. I guessed "more mountains" seven times in a row. He said that\'s because Yunnan is all mountains.\n\nWhen we arrived, I stepped off the train and saw Cangshan Mountain in the distance—a giant wearing a purple cloak. The air tasted different. Cleaner. Wetter.\n\nThat train ride taught me: the world is very big, and the best way to see it is with your face pressed against the glass.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Movie metaphor opening'},{fnEn:'Train station—everything is huge'},{fnEn:'Window scenery changing—slideshow'},{fnEn:'Tunnel surprise'},{fnEn:'Old man\'s guessing game'},{fnEn:'Arriving in Dali—first impression'},{fnEn:'Insight—the world is big'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Fresh-eye perspective',detailEn:'Everything seen for the first time—the narrative captures childlike wonder'},{pointEn:'Dynamic description',detailEn:'Buildings → fields → hills → mountains—motion creates rhythm'},{pointEn:'Multisensory arrival',detailEn:'Seeing Cangshan, tasting the air—the destination engages all senses'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Tall buildings became fields, fields became hills',whyEn:'A cinematic sequence captured in one smooth sentence'},{textEn:'Cangshan Mountain in the distance—a giant wearing a purple cloak',whyEn:'A child\'s metaphor for a mountain—imaginative and vivid'},{textEn:'Face pressed against the glass',whyEn:'The defining image of childhood curiosity—simple and universal'}]},
    {titleEn:'A Very Special Birthday',
     fullTextEn:'The most memorable birthday of my life was also the most heartbreaking—and then the most wonderful. All on the same day.\n\nI turned eleven on a Wednesday. Not one person mentioned it. Not Mom at breakfast. Not Dad before work. Not a single classmate. By afternoon, I was convinced the world had collectively decided to forget me.\n\nAfter school, Mom picked me up and said: "Let\'s go to Aunt Li\'s house." Strange. On my birthday?\n\nWe walked in. Darkness. Then—\n\n"SURPRISE!"\n\nLights, balloons, cake, and every person I cared about screaming at me. My best friend was holding a sign: "I almost told you three times today. Nearly died of secrecy."\n\nBut the best part wasn\'t the cake or the decorations. It was a small envelope from my classmates—a card with thirty-two messages:\n\n"Happy birthday to the person who always shares her snacks."\n"Wishing you grow to 180cm" (from the shortest boy in class).\n"You forgot your umbrella last month and I saw a teacher give you one. I think the universe likes you."\n\nI read all thirty-two. Some made me laugh. Some made me cry. All of them told me something I\'d forgotten: the small things I do get noticed. I matter.\n\nThe best birthday gift isn\'t something you unwrap. It\'s knowing you\'re loved by people you love back.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Emotional setup—funny AND touching'},{fnEn:'A whole day of nobody mentioning the birthday → sadness'},{fnEn:'Surprise party reveal'},{fnEn:'Best friend\'s line—the confession card—most touching gift'},{fnEn:'Insight—"being loved" is the real gift'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Classic build-up and payoff',detailEn:'The longer the silence, the bigger the surprise—textbook emotional structure'},{pointEn:'Layered surprises',detailEn:'Party → card → messages—each layer goes deeper'},{pointEn:'Laughter through tears',detailEn:'The messages blend humor and tenderness perfectly'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Nearly died of secrecy',whyEn:'A hilarious confession that captures the effort behind surprises'},{textEn:'Wishing you grow to 180cm',whyEn:'The shortest boy\'s wish is absurd and endearing—pure childhood humor'},{textEn:'The small things I do get noticed. I matter',whyEn:'The deepest gift—validation through others\' attention to your kindness'}]},
    {titleEn:'Poking the Hornets\' Nest',
     fullTextEn:'Let me tell you about the bravest—which is to say, the stupidest—thing I ever did.\n\nAge nine. My cousin and I discovered a hornet\'s nest under the eaves of the old house. Gray, papery, the size of a basketball. The adults said: "Don\'t touch it." Naturally, we immediately decided to touch it.\n\nWeapon of choice: a bamboo pole. Strategy: poke and run. Flaw in strategy: we underestimated how fast hornets can fly.\n\nI poked. The nest fell. And what fell with it was a dark, buzzing cloud of fury. The buzzing filled the air—not a sound you hear, a sound you feel in your bones.\n\nWe ran. Cousin went left, I went right. I dove into the kitchen and slammed the door. Three hornets got in with me. I screamed. Grandpa burst in with a towel, swatting like a warrior.\n\nFinal score: three stings on my arm, two on cousin\'s ear. Grandpa\'s lecture lasted longer than the stings hurt. "When adults say don\'t touch, don\'t touch!"\n\nYears later, I drove past the old house. The eaves were empty. But I swear I still felt a phantom itch on my arm. And a smile on my face.\n\nSome memories hurt. But the gray nest and two gray-faced kids? That\'s childhood.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Self-deprecating intro—brave = stupid'},{fnEn:'Discovery of nest, ignoring adults'},{fnEn:'Poking → nest falls → hornets chase'},{fnEn:'Being stung → Grandpa\'s rescue'},{fnEn:'Grandpa\'s lecture + aftermath'},{fnEn:'Years later—nostalgia + humor'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Adventure + humor',detailEn:'Danger is real but treated with self-aware comedy throughout'},{pointEn:'Pacing control',detailEn:'Quick action → sudden crisis → slower aftermath—cinematic rhythm'},{pointEn:'Dual ending',detailEn:'Phantom itch + smile = pain and joy coexisting in memory'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'What fell with it was a dark buzzing cloud of fury',whyEn:'Personifying the swarm as "fury"—visceral and dramatic'},{textEn:'The buzzing—not a sound you hear, a sound you feel in your bones',whyEn:'Synesthetic description that makes the reader\'s skin crawl'},{textEn:'The gray nest and two gray-faced kids—that\'s childhood',whyEn:'Color-matched humor—the gray parallelism ties nest and children together'}]},
    {titleEn:'Catching Fireflies at Night',
     fullTextEn:'There are prettier things in the world than fireflies. But at age six, standing barefoot in Grandpa\'s rice paddy at dusk, I was sure there weren\'t.\n\nIt started as tiny green sparks floating over the water. Like someone had scattered broken stars across the field. I gasped and grabbed Grandpa\'s hand.\n\n"Want to catch one?" he whispered.\n\nHe showed me how: cup your hands, wait, and when one lands, close gently—very gently, like holding a soap bubble. I tried seventeen times. Failed sixteen.\n\nThe seventeenth: a faint glow pulsed between my fingers. I opened a crack to peek—my hand had become a little lantern. The light was barely there, but in the darkness, barely there was everything.\n\nWe caught five more and put them in a glass jar. That night, I put the jar beside my pillow. The faintest nightlight in the world. I fell asleep watching them blink.\n\nIn the morning, they looked different. Gray, ordinary, not glowing at all. Grandpa said: "They only shine in the dark. Just like stars."\n\nWe released them that evening. I watched each one reignite and drift away, back into the rice paddy where they belonged.\n\nThirty years from now, if my children ask what my childhood looked like, I\'ll tell them: it looked like a handful of fireflies in a dark field—small, fragile, and shining.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Poetic opening—declaring fireflies supreme'},{fnEn:'Discovering fireflies in the rice paddy'},{fnEn:'Learning to catch them—seventeen tries'},{fnEn:'Glass jar nightlight—sleeping with fireflies'},{fnEn:'Morning contrast—gray and ordinary'},{fnEn:'Environmental metaphor + cherished memory'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Poetic narrative',detailEn:'Lyrical language throughout—"broken stars," "soap bubble," "little lantern"'},{pointEn:'Complete narrative arc',detailEn:'Discover → catch → keep → realize → release—a full emotional journey'},{pointEn:'Hidden environmental consciousness',detailEn:'Releasing them is both ecological and philosophical—they belong in the dark field'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Like someone scattered broken stars across the field',whyEn:'One of the most beautiful similes in all the essays—fireflies as fallen stars'},{textEn:'My hand had become a little lantern',whyEn:'Holding light in your palm—a magical childhood image'},{textEn:'They only shine in the dark. Just like stars',whyEn:'Grandpa\'s wisdom doubles as a life philosophy—adversity reveals brilliance'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: wh2024_comp_b "昆明景物/家乡景物" ──
TOPICS['wh2024_comp_b'] = {
  promptEn:'You must have admired beautiful scenery during your childhood. Choose a scenic spot in Kunming or your hometown and write about it. Create your own title, at least 450 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'A scenery essay that requires detailed, vivid depiction of landscape features. Wuhua District examinees can write about Kunming landmarks like Green Lake, Dianchi Lake, or Western Hills. Key elements: orderly observation (spatial or temporal sequence) + multisensory description + emotion woven into the scenery.',
    pitfallsEn:['Reading like a tour guide listing attractions','Only visual descriptions without other senses','Having scenery but no emotion—hollow and dull'],
    keyPointsEn:['Choose a place you have emotional connection to','Describe systematically (moving observation or fixed-point)','Weave emotion into scenery—express feelings through landscape']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'Green Lake Through the Seasons',
     fullTextEn:'If Kunming is a person, Green Lake is its heart—right in the center, beating quietly all year round.\n\nSpring: willows dip their branches into the water like green fingers testing the temperature. Ducks paddle lazily. Old people on benches soak up sunlight, newspapers over their faces, sleeping the most peaceful sleep in the city.\n\nSummer: lotus leaves crowd the surface like a giant green blanket. Lotus flowers push through—pink, white, some still bashfully closed. If you lean close, you can smell a sweetness that isn\'t quite flower, isn\'t quite water. Koi flash beneath the leaves—golden, red, one enormous white one everyone calls "the Emperor."\n\nAutumn: ginkgo trees along the shore turn gold. Walking underneath, fallen leaves crunch like nature\'s bubble wrap. But the real magic is the sound—wind through ginkgo branches isn\'t like wind through anything else. It\'s the whole street talking to you.\n\nWinter: the red-billed gulls arrive from Siberia. Thousands of them. They swoop for bread crumbs, their wings brushing past your face—you can feel the wind from their feathers. No other city in China has this. Winter in Kunming isn\'t cold; it\'s crowded—with birds.\n\nOn weekends, old men play erhu under the trees. College students sketch on the bridge. Children chase pigeons. Tourists ask: "Is it always this beautiful?" Locals smile and say nothing. Because yes. It is.\n\nGreen Lake isn\'t just a lake. It\'s where Kunming breathes.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Metaphor opening + geographic relationship'},{fnEn:'Spring: willows + ducks + sunbathing'},{fnEn:'Summer: lotus + koi'},{fnEn:'Autumn: ginkgo leaves + the sound'},{fnEn:'Winter: red-billed gulls—the most special season'},{fnEn:'Human activities + emotional conclusion'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Four-season structure',detailEn:'Each season gets one signature element—clear and memorable'},{pointEn:'Each season has one standout feature',detailEn:'Spring: ducks. Summer: lotus. Autumn: ginkgo sound. Winter: gulls—no clutter'},{pointEn:'People in the landscape',detailEn:'Erhu players, sketching students, pigeon-chasing children—the lake lives through its people'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Lotus leaves crowd the surface like a giant green blanket',whyEn:'A vivid collective noun image—"crowd" and "blanket" work perfectly together'},{textEn:'The whole street is talking to you',whyEn:'Personification of sound—autumn wind given a voice and presence'},{textEn:'Wings brushing past your face—you can feel the wind from their feathers',whyEn:'Tactile description of the gulls—moves beyond visual to physical sensation'}]},
    {titleEn:'Dusk by Dianchi Lake',
     fullTextEn:'I didn\'t choose to see Dianchi at dusk. Mom took me there after a bad test score. I was in no mood for beauty.\n\nBut beauty doesn\'t ask permission.\n\nThe lake stretched to the horizon—so vast it looked like the sky had been folded down and laid flat. The Western Hills sat across the water like a sleeping beauty (that\'s literally what locals call the mountain silhouette). Clouds were doing things I\'d never seen clouds do: turning pink, then orange, then purple, all within minutes.\n\nIt was as if someone had dumped a bucket of paint into the water—except the colors kept changing, kept blooming. A fishing boat drifted slowly across the sunset, its silhouette black against gold.\n\nMom sat beside me and said: "A bad test is like the sun going down. It\'s not the end of the world. Tomorrow it comes back up."\n\nSimple words. But sitting there, watching the greatest color show on earth, I believed her.\n\nBy the time we left, the sky was dark purple. City lights had replaced the sunset. A vendor was selling roasted corn—the smell drifted over, warm and golden, matching the last sliver of sun.\n\nThe wind was strong, the corn was delicious, and the sunset was the most beautiful I\'d ever seen. Mom was right. Tomorrow the sun comes back up.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Time setting + emotional context'},{fnEn:'Lake surface + Western Hills + clouds + fishing boat'},{fnEn:'Mom\'s words—using scenery to teach a lesson'},{fnEn:'Psychological shift'},{fnEn:'Night scene ending + emotional summary'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Scenery as emotional medicine',detailEn:'Beauty heals a bad test score—landscape serves emotional purpose'},{pointEn:'Five senses intertwined',detailEn:'Sight (sunset), sound (quiet), smell (corn), touch (wind)—full immersion'},{pointEn:'Concise dialogue',detailEn:'Mom\'s one sentence carries the entire theme'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Like someone dumped a bucket of paint into the water',whyEn:'A vivid metaphor for sunset reflections—dynamic and colorful'},{textEn:'A bad test is like the sun going down—it\'s not the end of the world',whyEn:'Mom\'s analogy—simple, wise, perfectly timed with the view'},{textEn:'The wind was strong, the corn was delicious, the sunset was beautiful',whyEn:'Three short parallel clauses—sensory trinity that captures the whole experience'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Ancient Trees of Golden Temple',
     fullTextEn:'Golden Temple\'s ancient trees have been standing for hundreds of years. I\'ve only been alive for twelve. Standing among them, I felt very, very small.\n\nThe stone steps leading up are flanked by cypresses and pines so old their bark looks like the face of time itself—deeply furrowed, cracked, but solid. Each tree is wider than my arm span. I tried hugging one. My fingers didn\'t even come close to meeting.\n\nGrandpa pointed at a cypress: "This one was planted during the Ming Dynasty. Four hundred years old." I stared. Four hundred years. When this tree was a sapling, there was an emperor.\n\nI touched the bark. It was rough, warm from the afternoon sun, and somehow alive in a way that walls and chairs aren\'t. Grandpa said: "A tree is like a person. The deeper the roots, the taller it grows."\n\nThe most famous tree: an 800-year-old crape myrtle. Despite its age, it was blooming—delicate pink flowers on ancient branches. Eight hundred years, and it still flowers every summer.\n\n"Even an 800-year-old tree blooms," Grandpa mused. "What\'s our excuse for giving up?"\n\nWalking down, I looked back. The trees stood against the sky like silent elders, watching Kunming change century by century. Through them, you can almost hear the trees whispering to each other about the old days.\n\nKunming has many modern buildings. But the truest part of the city might be these trees—rooted, patient, and still blooming.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Establishing the age contrast—trees vs. me'},{fnEn:'Stone steps and ancient cypresses/pines'},{fnEn:'Grandpa introduces the Ming Dynasty tree'},{fnEn:'Touch + Grandpa\'s metaphor'},{fnEn:'800-year crape myrtle—life force'},{fnEn:'Looking back + summary'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Temporal dimension',detailEn:'Human lifespan vs. tree lifespan creates philosophical resonance'},{pointEn:'Touch as participation',detailEn:'Actually touching the bark—beyond looking, into experiencing'},{pointEn:'Grandpa as narrator-guide',detailEn:'His words provide historical context and philosophical depth'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Bark like the face of time itself—deeply furrowed, cracked, but solid',whyEn:'Personifying tree bark as an aged face—poetic and apt'},{textEn:'800 years old and still blooming',whyEn:'The ultimate symbol of resilience—age doesn\'t stop vitality'},{textEn:'Like the trees whispering to each other about the old days',whyEn:'Personification that makes the trees feel like wise elders—magical realism'}]},
    {titleEn:'The Long Couplet at Grand View Tower',
     fullTextEn:'I first saw the Grand View Tower couplet on a spring outing. I was nine, and I had absolutely no idea why adults were so excited about words on a wall.\n\nGrand View Park is pretty enough—green water, arched bridges, willow trees doing that thing where they brush the lake surface. But the crowd gathered at the tower, all staring at two wooden panels covered in tiny characters.\n\n"One hundred and eighty characters," our teacher announced reverently. "The longest couplet in China."\n\nShe began reading it aloud. I understood about thirty percent. But something strange happened—the words had a rhythm, a music, that made my skin prickle. It was like standing on a mountaintop with wind blowing from all directions.\n\nAn old gentleman standing nearby explained it to me: "The top half describes the 500-li Dianchi Lake. The bottom half covers Yunnan\'s thousands of years of history. One couplet, one lake, one civilization."\n\nOne hundred and eighty characters. Five hundred li of landscape. Thousands of years of history. I couldn\'t fully comprehend it, but I felt something—the power of language to compress vastness into beauty.\n\nBefore leaving, I stood at the tower\'s edge and made a silent wish: someday, I want to write words that make people\'s skin prickle too.\n\nEvery character in that couplet was shining. I want mine to shine as well.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Spring outing context + suspense'},{fnEn:'Park scenery → seeing the couplet tower'},{fnEn:'Teacher reciting + old man explaining'},{fnEn:'Initial perception of language\'s power'},{fnEn:'Personal wish + significance'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Cultural landscape',detailEn:'A man-made landmark appreciated through a child\'s growing understanding'},{pointEn:'Child\'s perspective on classics',detailEn:'Only understanding 30% but feeling 100%—authentic learning experience'},{pointEn:'From scenery to aspiration',detailEn:'Seeing great writing inspires the desire to write—the essay comes full circle'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Like standing on a mountaintop with wind from all directions',whyEn:'How great writing feels to a nine-year-old—visceral, not intellectual'},{textEn:'180 characters can hold 500 li of landscape and thousands of years of history',whyEn:'The compression ratio of great literature—awe expressed mathematically'},{textEn:'Every character was shining',whyEn:'A child\'s simple but profound response to beauty—luminous'}]},
    {titleEn:'Dragon Gate on Western Hills',
     fullTextEn:'People visit Western Hills to see the sunrise from Dragon Gate. We went on Chinese New Year\'s Day—which meant climbing 1,200 steps in the dark.\n\n"Who climbs a mountain at 5 AM on New Year\'s Day?" I groaned. Dad said: "Apparently, we do."\n\nThe stone steps were narrow, worn smooth by centuries of feet. In the flashlight beam, each step looked like a tiny stage. My calves burned by step 300. By step 800, I was negotiating with my legs.\n\nThen we reached Dragon Gate. And I forgot everything.\n\nBelow us: Dianchi Lake, still dark. The sky was the color of bruised plum—deep purple shading into gray. We waited. And waited.\n\nThen a line of gold appeared on the horizon. Slowly—so slowly—the sun peeled away from the earth. The sky graduated: purple → rose → amber → blazing gold. The lake caught the light and became a mirror of fire.\n\nDad pointed east: "See that? That\'s what 500 li of Dianchi looks like at dawn."\n\nI couldn\'t speak. The colors were doing something inside my chest—expanding, pressing, aching.\n\nBelow Dragon Gate, there\'s a story: a stonemason carved the entire tunnel by hand over twelve years, one chisel strike at a time. Twelve years for this view.\n\nLooking at the sunrise, I understood: some things in life require twelve years of chiseling. And the view from the top—it\'s worth every strike.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'New Year dawn climb—setup with humor'},{fnEn:'Step descriptions + burning calves'},{fnEn:'Reaching Dragon Gate'},{fnEn:'Sunrise—color graduation'},{fnEn:'Dad\'s commentary'},{fnEn:'Stonemason story + three-layer conclusion'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Ascending to panoramic views',detailEn:'Physical climb → visual reward—classic structure with excellent execution'},{pointEn:'Color graduation',detailEn:'Purple → rose → amber → gold—precise color sequence'},{pointEn:'Nature + human endeavor as dual layers',detailEn:'Natural beauty + stonemason\'s labor create two complementary themes'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'The sky graduated: purple → rose → amber → blazing gold',whyEn:'A color sequence that reads like watching the actual sunrise unfold'},{textEn:'The lake caught the light and became a mirror of fire',whyEn:'The moment when Dianchi transforms—simple words, enormous image'},{textEn:'A city waking up in morning light',whyEn:'The final panoramic image—intimate and grand simultaneously'}]}
  ]
};

