// ── Topic: gd2024_comp_b "未来的自己" ──
TOPICS['gd2024_comp_b'] = {
  promptEn:'Write an essay titled "My Future Self." Use your imagination, at least 450 words.',
  guide:{
    analysisEn:'An imaginative essay requiring the student to envision their grown-up self—career, life, accomplishments. The key is making the imagination reasonable (based on real interests/strengths) while including concrete scenes and settings, not just a dry "plan." Blend professional life with emotional depth.',
    pitfallsEn:['Vaguely listing future plans without vivid scenes','Imagination too unrealistic','Only writing about career without emotion'],
    keyPointsEn:['Set up a specific future scenario','Use details to make the imagined scenes vivid','Weave in growth reflections or emotional content']
  },
  essays:[
    {titleEn:'My Future Self',
     fullTextEn:'Morning. Alarm at 6:30. I put on my white coat—it\'s been twelve years, and it still feels like a costume.\n\nI\'m a pediatrician. My pockets always have candy—not for me, for the crying ones.\n\nToday\'s first patient: a girl, maybe five, clutching a teddy bear. Her mom says she hasn\'t eaten for two days. The girl looks at me with enormous, fearful eyes.\n\nI crouch down: "Does teddy bear have a tummy ache too? Let me check him first." I pretend to listen to the bear\'s chest with my stethoscope. She giggles. Fear: gone.\n\nAfternoon: an appendectomy on a seven-year-old boy. Three hours of focus—hand steady, breath controlled. When I walk out and tell his parents "He\'s fine," the father\'s knees buckle with relief.\n\nEvening: driving home, I pass my old primary school. The building looks smaller than I remember. I imagine a girl in third grade, struggling with math, dreaming of being... a ballerina? No. An astronaut? Not quite. She hadn\'t decided yet.\n\nThat girl is me. She didn\'t know she\'d become a doctor. But the seeds were there—she bandaged her dolls, she worried when classmates got hurt, she always wanted to fix things.\n\nFuture me to past me: you turned out okay. Not a ballerina. But you still dance—between the beds of children who need you.\n\nI didn\'t become a doctor to wear the white coat. I became one so children can grow up healthy.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Morning scene + identity reveal'},{fnEn:'Examining a child patient—warm side'},{fnEn:'Surgery—professional side'},{fnEn:'Passing old school—present-past echo'},{fnEn:'Self-dialogue—point of the title'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'One-day timeline',detailEn:'Morning → afternoon → evening structures the imagination naturally'},{pointEn:'Imagination grounded in reality',detailEn:'Candy in pockets, teddy bear trick—specific, believable doctor behavior'},{pointEn:'Present-past dialogue',detailEn:'Driving past the old school connects future self to childhood self'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Pockets always have candy—not for me, for the crying ones',whyEn:'A tiny detail that defines the whole character—warmth in one sentence'},{textEn:'The building looks smaller than I remember',whyEn:'A universal adult experience used to bridge time'},{textEn:'Not a ballerina. But you still dance—between hospital beds',whyEn:'Gorgeous metaphor connecting childhood dreams to adult reality'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Future Self',
     fullTextEn:'I live in a small apartment with too many books and a cat named Chapter.\n\nI\'m a writer. Not famous—not yet, maybe not ever. But every morning I sit at my desk by the window, open my laptop, and write. The cursor blinks at me like a patient friend.\n\nToday, a letter arrived from a thirteen-year-old girl: "I read your book about the girl who talked to fish. After reading it, I decided I want to be a marine biologist. Thank you."\n\nI read the letter three times. Then I fed Chapter an extra treat.\n\nWriting is strange. You sit alone in a room, making up stories about people who don\'t exist. And then somehow, those made-up people change real people\'s real lives.\n\nEvening: I walk along the river near my apartment. The sunset is doing its thing—gold, pink, dimming. I think about my next book. It\'ll be about a boy who collects sounds.\n\nA boy who collects sounds. I smile. Because I know where the idea came from—fifth grade, when I spent an entire afternoon recording birds with a borrowed phone.\n\nFuture me isn\'t rich. Future me doesn\'t own a car. But future me is happy. Because writing makes me feel like the most honest version of myself.\n\nThe person who writes is happier than the person who reads. And the person who writes for others—that\'s the happiest of all.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Setting + cat named Chapter'},{fnEn:'Writing routine—the cursor as friend'},{fnEn:'Letter from a reader—writing\'s impact'},{fnEn:'Evening walk + next book idea'},{fnEn:'Self-dialogue—happiness defined'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Humble ideal',detailEn:'Not famous, not rich—happiness from craft, not status'},{pointEn:'Reader letter proves value',detailEn:'One letter justifies an entire career—impact over fame'},{pointEn:'Warmth pervades',detailEn:'The cat, the sunset, the treats—a gentle, contented life'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Writing makes people who read it happy. Writing makes me feel the most honest',whyEn:'A dual justification for the writer\'s life—giving and being'},{textEn:'A girl who read about talking to fish decided to be a marine biologist',whyEn:'Fiction inspiring real careers—the power of storytelling made concrete'},{textEn:'Not rich, but happy. Because writing is the most honest version of myself',whyEn:'A mature definition of success—authenticity over wealth'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Future Self',
     fullTextEn:'I\'m floating 400 kilometers above Earth. The planet below me is impossibly blue—the blue of every ocean poem combined.\n\nI\'m an astronaut. Outside the International Space Station, there is no sound, no wind—just infinite darkness and a blue marble hanging in it.\n\nToday\'s task: plant seeds in the orbital greenhouse. Tomato seeds. Tiny and brown and unremarkable—except that if they grow here, they\'ll be the first tomatoes grown in space by a Chinese astronaut.\n\nI place each seed carefully. In microgravity, they float before settling into the growth medium. I feel like a farmer and a scientist and a poet all at once.\n\nAfter the EVA (spacewalk) to repair a solar panel, I float back to the cupola window. Earth rotates slowly below. Clouds look like cotton candy spread over blue water. I can see the outline of Yunnan Province—my home.\n\nIn my locker, there\'s a photo: me at eight years old, at Kunming\'s planetarium, mouth open, staring at a model of the solar system. On the back, Dad wrote: "May you reach the stars."\n\nI did, Dad. But my heart is still pulled by Kunming.\n\nSpace is silent. But love is loud—even across 400 kilometers of vacuum.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Space setting + Earth description'},{fnEn:'Astronaut identity + tomato seeds'},{fnEn:'EVA repair—professional work'},{fnEn:'Cupola window—seeing home from space'},{fnEn:'Childhood photo + Dad\'s inscription'},{fnEn:'Connection between space and home'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Grand imagination + real detail',detailEn:'Space setting but anchored by tomato seeds and a childhood photo'},{pointEn:'Far-near contrast',detailEn:'400 km above Earth but heart in Kunming—distance amplifies connection'},{pointEn:'Photo as bridge',detailEn:'Eight-year-old\'s wonder → adult astronaut—the photo connects across time'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Clouds look like cotton candy spread over blue water',whyEn:'A child\'s metaphor used by an astronaut—showing the inner child persists'},{textEn:'No wind, no sound, just infinite darkness and a blue marble',whyEn:'The vast emptiness makes Earth\'s beauty more precious'},{textEn:'Heart forever pulled by Kunming',whyEn:'Even from orbit, home has gravity—emotional resonance'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Future Self',
     fullTextEn:'I\'m standing in a classroom. Chalk dust floats in the afternoon light, landing on my fingertips like tiny stars.\n\nI\'m a teacher. A Chinese teacher, to be specific. The kind that takes students to the garden to write about flowers instead of sitting in rows reciting.\n\nToday we\'re reading "Erta on the Grassland." A boy in the third row raises his hand: "Teacher, why was Li Bai so happy in this poem?"\n\nA girl answers before I can: "Because he just got released from prison. Anyone would be happy."\n\nI laugh. She\'s right—Li Bai had just been pardoned. His joy in the poem is the joy of freedom.\n\n"See?" I tell the class. "Poetry isn\'t about fancy words. It\'s about real people with real feelings. Li Bai was so happy he couldn\'t write a sad poem if he tried."\n\nAfter class, I sit at my desk. Twenty years ago, a teacher said something to me that changed everything: "Your writing is short, but every word is real." That seed grew into this—me, here, planting seeds in other people\'s children.\n\nThe seeds are small. But they grow.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Classroom scene + identity reveal'},{fnEn:'Teaching style—going outdoors'},{fnEn:'Student discussion of Li Bai'},{fnEn:'Teacher\'s insight—poetry is real feelings'},{fnEn:'Remembering own teacher—the seed metaphor'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Classroom recreation',detailEn:'The lesson scene feels alive—dialogue drives the narrative'},{pointEn:'Inheritance theme',detailEn:'Being inspired by a teacher → becoming one = the cycle of teaching'},{pointEn:'Seed metaphor',detailEn:'Seeds planted in you grow into seeds you plant in others—beautiful recursion'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Chalk dust on my fingertips like tiny stars',whyEn:'A magical opening image—the mundane made poetic'},{textEn:'She\'s right—Li Bai was just pardoned. Anyone would be happy',whyEn:'A student\'s blunt accuracy cuts through poetic mysticism'},{textEn:'Seeds are small. But they grow',whyEn:'The simplest possible thesis about teaching—and the truest'}]},
    {titleEn:'My Future Self',
     fullTextEn:'Everyone imagines their future self in a suit, in an office, in a city. Mine is in overalls, on a farm, hands covered in mud.\n\nI run a small organic farm outside Kunming. Mornings start at five. Bean pods hang like green wind chimes. Tomatoes ripen in clusters. The soil smells like earth should smell—alive.\n\nThis wasn\'t the plan. The plan was finance, or engineering, or "something with a future." But during college, I spent a summer volunteering at a rural school. The kids there had never seen a strawberry grow. Neither had I, actually.\n\nSomething shifted. Why do we all rush to cities when the land needs people too?\n\nNow, every Saturday, I host field trips. Primary school kids come and put their hands in the dirt. They learn where rice comes from (not the supermarket). They pull up carrots and scream with delight.\n\nEvening: I sit on the porch. No skyscraper view—just fields, hills, and a sky turning all the colors that money can\'t buy.\n\nFuture me doesn\'t wear suits. Future me wears dirt. And future me is perfectly, quietly, stubbornly happy.\n\nGrowing at your own pace is also a kind of greatness.',
     sections:[{fnEn:'Anti-expectation opening—overalls not suit'},{fnEn:'Morning farm scene'},{fnEn:'How the decision was made—rural volunteering'},{fnEn:'Hosting student field trips'},{fnEn:'Evening contentment'},{fnEn:'Self-dialogue—happiness on own terms'}],
     principles:[{pointEn:'Counter-conventional choice',detailEn:'Farm instead of office—deliberately challenges societal expectations'},{pointEn:'Pastoral idyll',detailEn:'Bean pods, tomato clusters, earth smell—sensory richness throughout'},{pointEn:'Values statement',detailEn:'"Growing at your own pace" = you don\'t need society\'s template to be great'}],
     highlights:[{textEn:'Hands covered in mud',whyEn:'Three words that reject the white-collar default and embrace earthiness'},{textEn:'Bean pods hanging like green wind chimes',whyEn:'A delicate rural metaphor—visual and auditory beauty fused'},{textEn:'Growing at your own pace is also a kind of greatness',whyEn:'The thesis—individualism and contentment as valid life paths'}]}
  ]
};

// ── Topic: pl2024_comp_a "难忘的瞬间" ──
